<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Africa Needs Massive Resources to Fight AIDS: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations Children's
Fund (UNICEF) said that countries in sub-Saharan Africa need a
massive infusion of resources to make significant headway against
the growing pandemic of HIV/AIDS in the region.
</P>
<P>
UNICEF Executive Director Carol Bellamy said this in Lusaka
Wednesday when she presented a paper on strategies to reduce HIV
transmission at the on-going 11th International Conference on AIDS
and STDS (sexually transmitted disease) in Africa.
</P>
<P>
Poor countries need more encouragement in the fight against
AIDS and they need more income support, debt relief and resources,
she said.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy also called on African countries to consider finding
new ways of attacking the crisis at country level.
</P>
<P>
She noted that since AIDS is straining a lot of resources,
African countries should consider setting up short-term targets
for prevention and treatment of the disease.
</P>
<P>
Bellamy noted that it was regrettable that Africa which deals
with four million new cases of AIDS every year only spends about
149 million U.S. dollars on HIV prevention while America spends
880 million dollars in the face of 40,000 new cases annually.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
