<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Emirate of Abu Dhabi has allocated 60 billion
dirhams (16.3 billion U.S. dollars) for investment projects to be
implemented during the period from 1999 to 2003, most of which
will be spent on the development of infrastructure, reported
Wednesday's Arab daily Al Hayat.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Abu Dhabi is anticipating a remarkable rise in
petroleum revenues this year, as compared to 1998, in view of the
improvement of oil prices. The income of Abu Dhabi Emirate is
expected to reach 48 billion dirhams (13.1 billion dollars) in
1999, up from 37 billion dirhams (10.1 billion dollars) in 1998.
</P>
<P>
SANAA -- The United Industries, Ltd, a subsidiary of the group
named "Ha'il Saeed Anaam &AMP; Partners," has embarked on the
construction of a new cigarette factory at an estimated cost of
about 25 million dollars, reported Wednesday's Al Hayat.
</P>
<P>
According to Shawki Ahmed Ha'il, deputy general manager of the
group, participating in the venture are the British-American
Tobacco company together with several Yemeni investors. The
production capacity of the factory is 360,000 cartons of
cigarettes a year.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The United Arab Emirates (UAE) will chair the 22nd
meeting of the Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) Ministerial
Committee on Oil Cooperation, to be held in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia,
on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
The participants will discuss the current situation of the
international oil market, coordinating their stands ahead of the
ministerial meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries, to be held in Vienna on September 22.
</P>
<P>
The GCC comprises the UAE, Saudi Arabia, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar
and Bahrain. 
</P>
</TEXT>
