<HEADLINE> Venezuelan President Calls for Helping Colombian Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, September 14 (Xinhua) -- Venezuelan President Hugo
Chavez said Wednesday he would urge international organizations,
such as the United Nations (UN) and the Organization of American
States (OAS), to back up the peace process in Colombia.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan leader said that a foreign intervention in
Colombia would be ominous for the country, Venezuela and the Latin
American region.
</P>
<P>
Chavez confirmed that he would visit the U.N. General Assembly
next week and the OAS.
</P>
<P>
"Wherever I go, I will continue to announce publicly and call
on the world for joint contribution with Colombia in the search
for peace," he added.
</P>
<P>
Chavez denied that his government was helping the guerrilla
movement in Colombia, as was stated by the chief of the
paramilitary group Autodefensas Unidas de Colombia, Pablo Catano.
He added that he would not be tricked into provocation.
</P>
<P>
The Venezuelan president provoked the anger of the Colombian
government when he said he was willing to meet with the Colombian
guerrilla movement on Venezuelan territory, to put an end to the
rebel activities. 
</P>
</TEXT>
