<HEADLINE> Iraq Dismisses Iran's Allegations on POWs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraq on Wednesday dismissed
Iran's allegations that Iraq still detains Iranian prisoners of
war (POWs).
</P>
<P>
A foreign ministry spokesman said in a statement that Iran
intentionally spread such lies to hide facts concerning the real
number of Iranian soldiers killed in the 1980-88 Iraq-Iran war,
the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah Najafi, an Iranian official in charge of POWs issue,
on Monday alleged that even the Iraqi negotiating delegation
confessed that Iraq are still holding Iranian POWs.
</P>
<P>
The Iraqi spokesman said that the Iranian side knows very well
that Iraq has released all Iranian POWs under the supervision of
the International Committee of Red Cross (ICRC) while Iran still
detains a large number of Iraqi POWs.
</P>
<P>
He said that there is a list of 3,199 Iranian
missing-in-actions (MIAs) and not POWs, claiming that Iraq has
shown a great deal of cooperation with the Iranian authorities to
find out information about those MIAs.
</P>
<P>
He accused the Iranian side of still refusing to offer more
information about those Iranian MIAs except a list of them.
</P>
<P>
The issue of POWs has been an outstanding obstacle standing
in the way of normalizing ties between Iraq and Iran, two
former foes which fought an eight-year war in the 1980s in
which some one million people were killed or injured.
</P>
<P>
Iraq accuses Iran of still detaining 13,000 Iraqi POWs while
Iran says there are still 5,000 Iranian POWs in Iraq's prisons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
