<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0008 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mozambique Urges for Consensus on SADC Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Mozambique Wednesday urged the
Southern African Development Community (SADC) to reach consensus
among its member countries before the implementation of the SADC
Trade Protocol, which aims to set up a free trade area in the
region.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Leonardo Simao said such a consensus should be
reached concerning the modalities of tariff reduction and the
rules of origin, taking into account the different levels of
development of the member countries, so as to avoid "the stronger
economics suffocating those that are still developing".
</P>
<P>
Addressing the Fourth Mozambique/Germany Forum, organized by
the German NGO, the Friedrich Ebert Foundation, Simao stressed
that the Mozambican government needed to continue its negotiations
with other SADC countries on the matter so that by December
consensus will have been reached leading to Mozambican
ratification of the protocol.
</P>
<P>
SADC had hoped that the trade protocol would take effect as
from January 2000, but that depends on at least two thirds of the
member countries ratifying it. So far, only five of the 11 SADC
members that signed the document have ratified it.
</P>
<P>
Simao said that in the case of Mozambique, one should take into
account that the economy is still recovering after a devastating
war, and "it needs a longer restructuring time before it attains
the levels of competitiveness of the other countries of the
region".
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Mozambican Association of Young Businessmen
Hipolito Hamela argued that the protocol should be implemented
sector by sector, thus protecting the most sensitive areas, such
as sugar, glass, and grain.
</P>
<P>
In the initial stage, Mozambique should enter the protocol with
the fishing, tobacco, timber, tea and cotton industries, he added.
</P>
<P>
Hamela insisted on a clear definition of national industrial
policy and, most of all, the relationship between formal and
informal trade.
</P>
<P>
Speaking of the free circulation of people within the region,
Simao said that this should be an important complement of the
circulation of goods and services, since it is essential that
business people may easily come and go within the region.
</P>
<P>
However, he noted that freedom of movement "should be done in
such a way that it does not create situations that may upset the
relations between the member states and, as a result, the regional
integration process itself". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
