<HEADLINE> GCC Oil Ministers to Meet on Market Condition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Oil ministers of the
Gulf Cooperation Council (GCC) will meet in the Saudi capital of
Riyadh on Saturday to discuss the situation in the world oil
market, GCC Secretary General Jamil Al-Hujailan said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which comes ahead of a session of the Organization
of Petroleum Exporting Countries (OPEC) due in Vienna later this
month, will be an opportunity to assess the market condition and
put forward new proposals aimed at achieving a more balanced
market, Al-Hujailan was quoted by the Kuwait News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
The oil-dependent GCC states have voiced satisfaction over the
improvement of oil prices in the past few months and promised a
continuous adherence to the OPEC production cut agreement signed
last March.
</P>
<P>
Oil prices have bounced back dramatically since OPEC members
and non-OPEC producers began to impose a daily output reduction of
2.1 million barrels on April 1.
</P>
<P>
But, the GCC states, along with other OPEC members, are still
looking forward to additional improvement in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
During the one-day meeting, the ministers will also review a
number of issues concerning the cooperation among GCC states in
the fields of oil and gas.
</P>
<P>
They will also discuss a possible feasibility study on
promoting gas trade between the European Union and the GCC
states, which account for 13.7 percent of the world's natural gas
reserves.
</P>
<P>
The GCC, a regional political and economic alliance, comprises
Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia and the United Arab
Emirates. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
