<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0011 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pakistan, India Once Close to Solution of Kashmir: Pak FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz disclosed on Wednesday that a four-point agreement
envisaging the resolution of the Kashmir dispute in nine to 12
months had once been very close to a conclusion during the Kargil
conflict.
</P>
<P>
But New Delhi backed out at the eleventh hour on the plea that
a caretaker government cannot make such a commitment, Aziz said.
</P>
<P>
He was responding to points of order in the Senate on reports
that the Kashmir dispute was to be solved by September or October
and the Kargil issue disrupted this process.
</P>
<P>
Aziz rejected the reports, but admitted that after the Lahore
summit in February this year, a process of "back channel"
diplomacy had started which remained active for about two months
and came to a standstill when the Atal Bihari Vajpayee government
collapsed in April.
</P>
<P>
During the Kargil crisis that broke out late May, India
approached Pakistan through back-door diplomacy in a bid to solve
the problem and a four-point understanding was developed, he said.
</P>
<P>
According to Aziz, the understanding included time-bound
negotiations on Kashmir leading to its resolution in nine to 12
months, respect for the Line of Control (LoC) as per the Simla
Agreement, defusing of the Kargil situation and accepting the
significance of the Kashmir problem.
</P>
<P>
The foreign minister said it was almost finalized and as per
the understanding, Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif was to have a brief
stopover in New Delhi after his China visit in late June. He was
to issue a joint statement in this regard.
</P>
<P>
But India backed out from the understanding on the plea that a
caretaker government should not make such vital commitments, he
said.
</P>
<P>
On the Kargil conflict, Aziz said there was "credible"
information to suggest that India was trying to cross the LoC.
Keeping this in view, Pakistani troops also moved on the LoC and
established some new posts.
</P>
<P>
During this course, Kashmiri Mujahideen (holy war fighters)
also occupied some posts in the Kargil-Drass sector in the
India-controlled Kashmir, he added.
</P>
<P>
He said some circles were trying to create misunderstanding by
giving an impression that the action of the armed forces disrupted
the process of dialogue with India.
</P>
<P>
As a result of the Kargil crisis, he said, India was under
intense international pressure to have meaningful dialogue with
Pakistan for resolution of the dispute. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
