<HEADLINE> Israeli Police Question Netanyahu </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Israeli police started
Wednesday an investigation of former prime minister Benjamin
Netanyahu on suspicions of bribe-taking and misuse of public funds.
</P>
<P>
Netanyahu and his wife Sara were summoned to the police
headquarters here Wednesday afternoon for questioning, a police
announcement said.
</P>
<P>
The police did not give details about the questioning, but
said both Netanyahu and his wife should be given chances of
cleaning themselves of the charges, it said.
</P>
<P>
The case broke Tuesday when the local Hebrew paper Yediot
Aharonot ran a promotion of its own investigation into Netanyahu's
dealings.
</P>
<P>
According to the daily, Netanyahu received various domestic
maintenance and home renovation services from Avner Amedi, a
58-year-old Jerusalem businessman who owns a maintenance company.
</P>
<P>
The report said that Amedi's company supplied the Netanyahus
with a variety of services during his term as prime minister, but
Amedi neither requested nor received any payment for the
services, which carried out not only at the prime minister's
office, but at the couple's home and their official residence.
</P>
<P>
According to the story, after Netanyahu lost the May election,
Amedi presented the Prime Minister's Office a bill for 440,000
shekels (about 100,000 U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The report said Netanyahu claimed he never asked Amedi to
carry out work for him.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested Amedi on Tuesday on suspicions of having bribed
Netanyahu and the Tel Aviv Magistrate Court remanded him for two
days. 
</P>
</TEXT>
