<HEADLINE> Hurricane Causes Minimal Damage at U.S. Space Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. National
Aeronautics and Space Administration (NASA) said Wednesday
Hurricane Floyd caused minimal damage at the Kennedy Space Center
in Cape Canaveral of Florida State.
</P>
<P>
The hurricane stayed 110 kilometers offshore, bringing
sustained wind of 100 kph, with gusts of 128 kph, NASA spokesman
George Diller said.
</P>
<P>
By Wednesday morning, workers had yet to check the two shuttle
launch pads. But a preliminary inspection of the buildings housing
the four shuttles and all the equipment for the international
space station uncovered no serious problems, Diller said.
</P>
<P>
He said that a piece of sheet metal blew off the 175-meter-high
Vehicle Assembly Building early Wednesday morning, and the phone
lines were down a few hours Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
"It's minimal, very minimal," he said. "You can get this kind
of damage in a severe thunderstorm. We're just really pleased."
</P>
<P>
NASA planned to reopen the space center Thursday morning. Some
12,500 workers at the center were evacuated Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
