<HEADLINE> Pakistan Holds Fresh Talks With Afghan Opposition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's negotiating team
has held the third round of talks with Afghan opposition leader
Burhanuddin Rabbani in Dushanbe, Uzbekistan, where they discussed
ways for the peaceful settlement of Afghan turmoil, official
sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Pakistani team, led by Interior Secretary Rustam Shah
Mohmand, returned to Islamabad Wednesday and plans to proceed to
Kandahar, Afghanistan on Thursday for talks with the ruling
Taliban militia, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
"The atmosphere of the talks was cordial," said the sources,
who gave no details of the Dushanbe meeting.
</P>
<P>
This was the first face-to-face contact in three years between
Pakistani government officials and Rabbani, chairman of the Afghan
opposition's newly-founded Political Office.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan launched shuttle diplomacy between Afghanistan's two
warring parties last month at the request of the deposed Afghan
president.
</P>
<P>
Younis Qanooni, a close aide to commander Ahmad Shan Masood,
led the Afghan opposition delegation in previous meetings with
Pakistani officials.
</P>
<P>
The Afghan opposition has accused Pakistan of backing the
Taliban, a charge denied by Islamabad. 
</P>
</TEXT>
