<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-15 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinians Present Police List to Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Israel said Wednesday that
the Palestinians have fulfilled one of their obligations in the
latest peace deal by presenting Israel the name list of the
Palestinian police force.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Ehud Barak's office said in a statement that
Israel would begin to review the name list according to the
procedure stipulated in the revised Wye agreement signed in Egypt
last week.
</P>
<P>
Under the latest agreement, the Palestinians have to continue
to fulfill their obligations set down in the Wye agreement signed
last year, such as reducing the number of the Palestinian police
forces and collecting illegal weapons.
</P>
<P>
Former hard-line Israeli prime minister Benjamin Netanyahu
froze the Wye agreement last year, two months after he signed on
it, accusing the Palestinians of failing to fulfill their
commitments.
</P>
<P>
Under signed accords between Israel and the Palestinians, the
number of Palestinian police should be kept at around
24,000. Israel said the current number was over 30,000.
</P>
<P>
In signs that the Israeli-Palestinian peace process has got
back on the track, Israel has fulfilled its obligations in the
first stage of the latest agreement, handing over 7 percent of
the West Bank to the Palestinians and releasing 199 Palestinian
political prisoners.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also launched the permanent talks Monday with the
aim of resolving the thorny issues in the century-old conflict,
such as the Palestinian statehood and Jerusalem, within a year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> African Lawmakers Express Concern over Debts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, September 15 (xinhua) -- African lawmakers ended
Wednesday the 36th session of the African Inter-Parliamentary
Union (AIPU), expressing deep concern over the impact of external
debts on the future development of the continent.
</P>
<P>
The participants of the three-day session held in Luanda,
capital of Angola, approved unanimously on Tuesday a project on
the resolution for external debts burdened by their countries.
</P>
<P>
Angolan legislator and former Financial Minister Augusto Tomas
said in a report that the current poverty in Africa is due to the
remarkable commercial deficit and the interference by certain
economic powers in the world.
</P>
<P>
In the last 20 years, the total debts of African countries
increased by 53%, mainly because the interest rates of the loans
offered by public or private banks have duplicated from from 5.5%
to 10.4% during this period, he said.
</P>
<P>
In the report, Tomas also mentioned the fluctuating exchange
rates as a progenitor for the augment of the debts under the title
"The External Debt of African Countries and the Impact on
Development and Democracy", saying that this kind of fluctuation
has made the reimbursements swell.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the African continent has seen the dropping prices
of coffee, cocoa, wood and other primary products, which has
seriously affected the export of the continent, he said.
</P>
<P>
The 36th session of AIPU, a preparatory meeting for the 22th
Conference of the organization, also approved projects on the
resolutions for public administration and terrorism in the
continent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan on Pros and Cons of Globalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan Wednesday listed pros and cons of globalization, saying,
"Globalization has become the essence of modern life. It must
become second nature in our thinking."
</P>
<P>
The statement came as the U.N. chief is addressing the 52nd
Conference of the U.N. Department of Public Information (DPI) and
Non-Governmental Organizations (NGO).
</P>
<P>
"Many experience globalization not as an agent of progress, but
as a disruptive force, almost hurricane-like in its ability to
destroy lives, jobs and traditions in the blink of an eye," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"For many there is an urge to resist the process and take
refuge in the comforts of the local," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Globalization may be exacerbating inequality," he said. "It
may also be disturbing cultural traditions and increasing our
sense of spiritual disorientation."
</P>
<P>
"It gives me no pleasure to recite this litany, because
globalization is undeniably improving standards of living and
creating more opportunity," he said. "It is making us more
familiar with diversity."
</P>
<P>
"I believe that on the whole, over the long term, globalization
has been positive," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We are all consumers in the same global economy," he said. "We
are all influenced by the same tides of political, social and
technological change."
</P>
<P>
"The ill winds and fouled waters of the earth's environment
likewise show no regard for the niceties of borders: pollution is
our common problem," he said.
</P>
<P>
"People and cultures are increasingly hybrid," he said. "The
same icons, whether on a movie screen or a computer screen, are
recognized from Berlin to Bangalore."
</P>
<P>
"We are connected, wired, interdependent," he said.
</P>
<P>
As the world is becoming increasingly interdependent, countries
are feeling the pros and cons of globalization from various
perspectives.
</P>
<P>
Globalization will be one of major issues discussed at the
General Assembly general debate, scheduled to begin on September
20, and the conference of NGO meetings during the debate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
