<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OIC Warns Disney Against Controversial Exhibition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUWAIT CITY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Organization of the
Islamic Conference (OIC) on Wednesday urged Walt Disney Co., the
U.S. entertainment giant, not to hold an Israel-financed
exhibition with the theme of "Jerusalem, Israel's Capital."
</P>
<P>
"The Israeli exhibition is a flagrant attempt to change
historical facts about Jerusalem," OIC Secretary General Ezzedin
Laraki said in a letter to Disney Chairman Michael Eisner, the
Kuwait News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Laraki said as "Jerusalem is the capital of Palestine," the
Israeli participation in the exhibition would negatively affect
the Palestinian-Israeli peace process.
</P>
<P>
He warned that the exhibition, if held, would offend more than
1.5 billion Muslims in 56 countries worldwide.
</P>
<P>
Recent reports said Israel intended to finance an exhibit at
Disney world's Epcot Center in Orlando, Florida of the United
States, which will depict Jerusalem as Israel's capital.
</P>
<P>
However, Saudi billionaire Prince Waleed Ibn Talal, who is one
of the major investors in Disney Land Company in France, said on
Monday he had received assurance from Eisner that the exhibition
would not be held under the controversial title. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
