<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0021 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Doubles Tobacco Export to Egypt </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwean Industry and
Commerce Minister Nathan Shamuyarira Wednesday signed a five
million U.S.dollars tobacco export agreement with Egypt.
</P>
<P>
The minister said the agreement would see Zimbabwe's tobacco
export earnings to Egypt more than doubling from about five
million U.S. dollars to 12 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Chairman of the Eastern Tobacco Company of Egypt Mohamed Sadek
Ragab said the move by the Egyptian government to sign the trade
agreement followed the country's joining of the Common Market for
Eastern and Southern Africa (COMESA) this year.
</P>
<P>
!0Being a member of COMESA, it means that Egypt is now exempted
from high import taxation. This will increase our imports of
tobacco from Zimbabwe to Egypt,!1 Ragab said.
</P>
<P>
He said his country is now able to import quality tobacco from
Zimbabwe at a subsidized duty of a reduction of about 90 percent,
hoping that the trade agreement with Zimbabwe will boost the
economies of the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has been importing tobacco from Brazil at very high
import duties over the past years, he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
