<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0022 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> First HIV Vaccine to be Tested on Human Beings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Production of the first ever
HIV vaccine with strains of the virus most common in Africa has
started.
</P>
<P>
President of the international AIDS vaccine initiative Seth
Berkley told journalists at the on-going 11th International
Conference on AIDS and STDS (sexually transmitted disease ) in
Africa (ICASA) in Lusaka Wednesday that the vaccine would be the
first ever to be produced between African researchers and those
from Britain.
</P>
<P>
He said the early clinical trials of the vaccine on human
beings begin in January 2000 in Britain before being introduced in
Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Berkley added that a vaccine is the only chance to end the
global AIDS pandemic.
</P>
<P>
"We need to get commitment from all levels of society that the
development of an HIV vaccine is a critical goal," he said.
</P>
<P>
At the briefing, Omo Anzala from the University of Nairobi said
the vaccine being developed, targeted the "Clade A" sub type, the
strain of HIV most common in Africa.
</P>
<P>
He explained that the vaccine contains fragments of getting the
body's immune system to recognize the virus and respond to it.
</P>
<P>
Anzala added that the vaccine would be tried on 40 healthy
Kenyans and a similar number of British volunteers to see the
expected immune response.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
