<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Backs Elected Lords in Britain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- More than 80 percent of
Britons favor an elected second chamber once the reform of the
House of Lords is completed, according to a survey released
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The survey of more than 1,000 people suggests only 11 percent
of the public back a system whereby the country's second most
important government institution would be solely appointed by the
prime minister of the day.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicates strong support for a chamber with
strong powers to delay government legislation.
</P>
<P>
The research was commissioned by the Joseph Rowntree Trust and
carried out by ICM.
</P>
<P>
The survey suggested 84 percent wanted an elected second
chamber, while only 11 percent opted for the appointed chamber,
which is one option being considered by ministers.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicates strong support for a second chamber
with increased powers.
</P>
<P>
Nearly half, or 46 percent, said it should be able to delay
government bills to which it objected "indefinitely" unless it
could agree to a compromise with the House of Commons.
</P>
<P>
A quarter thought it should be able to delay a new law for one
or two years and only a fifth would restrict the period of delay
to "a few months."
</P>
<P>
The new contributions on the future of the House of Lords come
as the bill ending the traditional right of hereditary peers to
sit and vote in the Lords -- the first stage of reform -- is due
to clear Parliament this autumn.
</P>
<P>
A ballot for the 92 hereditaries who will be allowed to stay
until stage two of reform is completed is scheduled to take place
in October. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0029 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
