<HEADLINE> Dhaka Lodges Protest With U.S. Magazine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Bangladeshi government has
expressed its displeasure and annoyance with the U.S. news
magazine Time for its failure to include the name of Sheikh
Mujibur Rahman in its special edition on prominent Asians of the
century, the official BSS news agency reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In a letter faxed Tuesday to the Time magazine in New York, the
United States, the Ministry of Foreign Affairs expressed its
"surprise" at the dropping of the name of "Bangabandhu Sheikh
Mujibur Rahman" from the weekly's cover story entitled "The most
influential Asians of the 20th century."
</P>
<P>
The letter, addressed to the editor of the magazine, said
Sheikh Mujibur was acknowledged as one of the world's charismatic
leaders and a forceful advocate for peace.
</P>
<P>
"His name would feature in any list of prominent Asians of the
20th century," the letter was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ministry in its letter expressed the hope that the magazine
in future would take appropriate steps to reflect reality and
facts, the BSS said.
</P>
<P>
Sheikh Mujibur Rahman, father of the country's incumbent Prime
Minister Sheikh Hasina, was born in March 1920 and was
assassinated in August 1975. He was the first prime minister of
independent Bangladesh. 
</P>
</TEXT>
