<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa to Pay for Arms Deal Over 8 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa will pay
21.3 billion rands (3.55 billion U.S. dollars) over the next eight
years for new defense equipment, with the option to buy 8.5
billion rands (1.42 billion U. S. dollars) more, Defense Minister
Patrick Lekota said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The conversion of 30 percent of the original contract value of
31 billion rands (5.17 billion dollars) into options ensured that
the defense force could obtain the required equipment as needed,
without creating immediate fiscal pressures, South African Press
Association (SAPA) quoted Lekota as saying at a media briefing in
Cape Town.
</P>
<P>
The cabinet at its fortnightly meeting had decided to buy the
following:
</P>
<P>
-- nine Grippen and 12 Hawk aircraft from British
Aerospace/Saab, to replace the current Cheetah and Impala
aircraft, with a further option to buy another 12 Hawks and 19
Grippens;
</P>
<P>
-- four patrol corvettes from the German Frigate Consortium,
to replace the present aging strike crafts;
</P>
<P>
-- 30 light utility helicopters from Italy's Augusta company,
to replace the Alouette helicopters; and
</P>
<P>
-- three submarines from the German Submarine Consortium, to
replace the aging Daphne submarines.
</P>
<P>
The 21.3 billion rands covers all statutory costs such as VAT,
custom duties, freight, export credit guarantees and program
management.
</P>
<P>
Lekota said that should the South African government decide not
to buy the outstanding equipment, it would not face any
cancellation penalties or costs.
</P>
<P>
The option has to be exercised by 2004.
</P>
<P>
If this is the case, the total equipment cost would increase by
8.5 billion rands to 29.9 billion rands (5 billion U.S. dollars),
over 12 years.
</P>
<P>
On whether the option would be exercised, Lekota said: "Most
probably."
</P>
<P>
The cabinet was fully satisfied with the arms-for-investment
offset arrangements, which would benefit the economy and advance
the socio- economic interests of the country, he said.
</P>
<P>
However, he was unable to give details. Instead, he spoke
broadly about " some job creation" as part of the production which
would take place in South Africa.
</P>
<P>
Lekota added that greater security for the country, linked to
the region, would also have spin-offs for investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
On which part of the defense force would benefit first, Lekota
said this was still under discussion.
</P>
<P>
"But personally, we are concerned with the state of the navy...
and then, of course, the air force," he said.
</P>
<P>
Lekota said the result of the procurement process was an
"affordable defense package combined with an industrial and
economic investment package spanning a variety of industrial
sectors and underpinning the government's industrial strategy".
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
