<HEADLINE> Athens Quake Death Toll Rises to 135 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The death toll from last
Tuesday's earthquake in northwestern Athens has climbed to 135,
and it is likely to reach 140.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press briefing Wednesday, Greek government
spokesman Dimitris Reppas said that rescue teams have so far
pulled 85 people alive from the rubble of collapsed buildings.
</P>
<P>
Last Tuesday, a strong earthquake registering 5.9 on the
Richter scale rocked Athens with its epicenter being in the Mount
Parnitha region, some 20 kilometers northwest of the Greek
capital.
</P>
<P>
The earthquake, which is estimated to cost the country more
than 200 billion drachmas (about 645 million U.S. dollars), left
more than 2,000 people injured and some 60,000 others homeless.
</P>
<P>
The Greek government has taken a series of measures to help
earthquake victims. So far a number of tent cities have been set
up for homeless people and the government has promised to move
these people from tent cities to more durable housing within
several weeks.
</P>
<P>
As aftershocks occur on a daily basis, seismologists insist
that this is natural following last Tuesday's powerful earthquake.
</P>
<P>
Although seismologists say it is unlikely that aftershocks will
exceed 5 on the Richter scale, this critical period may last
several weeks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
