<HEADLINE> France Expects Europe's Economy to Catch Up With U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- French Minister of Economy and
Finance Dominique Strauss-Kahn said Wednesday that Europe's
economic power will catch up with that of the United States in the
first decade of the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
"If the decade of the 1990s was that of American prosperity,
the primary decade after the year 2000 can be the return of growth
and power of Europe," said Strauss-Kahn at a press conference when
presenting the government's budget for 2000.
</P>
<P>
He said that next year, the global economic growth will be more
balanced as the United States will no longer be the only
locomotive of world economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"The growth will re-start everywhere in Europe," he said. "Most
of the economies in Asia, not Japan but Korea and Thailand, will
go better."
</P>
<P>
The minister also predicted that the biggest risk to be faced
by Europe is the impact from a forthcoming "touchdown" of the U.S.
economy, whose growth rate will fall by half in 2000 as compared
with 1999.
</P>
<P>
"Obtaining growth without the social inequality of the United
States" is the objective of Europe, he said.
</P>
<P>
Strauss-Kahn said that the major block faced by the French
economy is that it is much less supported by new technology than
that of the United States.
</P>
<P>
"The adoption of new technologies remains much slower in
France. To make up this backwardness can be one of the elements of
sustained growth in the coming years," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
