<HEADLINE> Turkey, Greece Hold Talks in Friendly Atmosphere </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ANKARA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A Turkish official have
signalled that the signing of an agreement on joint action against
terrorism will not be a precondition for bilateral cooperation in
this controversial area.
</P>
<P>
The issue of fighting terrorism and organized crime will be on
the agenda of the two-day Turco-Greek talks, which start on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The talks the last session of the second round of dialog which
started in late July.
</P>
<P>
"There is nothing like 'first agreement and then
cooperation'...An agreement is not a precondition. It is a means
of facilitating the cooperation," a Turkish official said.
</P>
<P>
He stated that "in our point of view, an agreement on
terrorism is necessary. It is still an objective for us, but it is
not being put forward as a precondition."
</P>
<P>
The official added that Turkey has worked productively in
cooperation with many countries on objectives not based on
defined agreements.
</P>
<P>
The thorny Turco-Greek ties went through a severe crisis in
February when Turkey's outlawed Kurdish Workers' Party (PKK)
leader Abdullah Ocalan surfaced at the Greek Embassy compound in
Nairobi, Kenya.
</P>
<P>
Turkey had long been accusing Greece of supporting the PKK and
harboring PKK militants.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece immediately improved bilateral ties
after the two neighboring countries were hit by strong quakes
separately.
</P>
<P>
After a 7.4-magnitude earthquake hit western Turkey on August
17, Greece sent a strong rescue team to help Turkey extricate
survivors trapped in the ruins of collapsed buildings in western
Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Later, Turkey was the first country to send its 20-member
rescue team to help Greece rescue the Greeks trapped in the
debris after a 5.9-magnitude quake hit Athens on September 8.
</P>
<P>
Turkey and Greece, both members of the North Atlantic
Treaty Organization (NATO), have long been at odds over the
limits of air space, sovereignty over some Aegean islands and
the Cyprus issue. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
