<HEADLINE> Aziz: Iraq to Accept Nothing Less Than Total </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister
Tariq Aziz said on Wednesday that Iraq will accept nothing less
than the total lifting of sanctions imposed on the country more
than nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
Aziz told reporters Wednesday evening on the sideline of the
on-going 9th International Popular Islamic Conference which has
been intended to show solidarity with the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
"We are not concerned with the London meeting," said Aziz,
adding that Iraq has made a legitimate and clear-cut demand for
totally lifting the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
A meeting attended by representatives of the five permanent
members of the U.N. Security Council, namely Britain, China,
France, Russia and the U.S., is underway in London to discuss the
Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said that the U.S. launched a propaganda campaign against
Iraq recently, which will not convince any fair-minded person,
because U.S. lies about Iraq has been widely exposed before the
international community.
</P>
<P>
He also said the just-concluded 112nd Arab League foreign
ministers meeting chaired by Iraqi Foreign Minister Mohammad Said
al-Sahaf was successful and was held in a positive atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
Since last December's U.S.-British airstrikes against Iraq,
deliberations inside the Security Council on the Iraqi issue
have reached an impasse.
</P>
<P>
Under relevant U.N. resolutions, the U.N. economic sanctions
imposed on Iraq following its 1990 invasion of Kuwait should be
lifted after U.N. weapons inspectors verify that it is free of
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
However, weapons inspections have not been resumed after the
withdrawal of the U.N. weapons inspectors from Iraq last December
before the U.S-British bombardment of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has repeatedly announced that the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) on disarming Iraq is "dead" and accused the commission
of spying for the U.S..
</P>
<P>
The London meeting will reportedly discuss the British-Dutch
proposal on the Iraqi issue, of which Iraq has time and again
voiced rejection.
</P>
<P>
The proposal recommends a temporary suspension of the
restrictions on Iraq's oil sales if Baghdad fully cooperates with
an enlarged body of weapons inspections which will replace UNSCOM
and agrees to the creation of strict financial controls of its oil
proceeds.
</P>
<P>
Baghdad has rejected the plan outright, insisting that it will
accept nothing less than a total lifting of the embargo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
