Brussels Wednesday to discuss "ways to further improve the security
situation in Kosovo".
</P>
<P>
At the NATO-Russia Permanent joint Council (PJC) meeting, both
sides condemned "all acts of violence and called opon all the people
of Kosovo to support and cooperate with the international security
and civil presences".
</P>
<P>
The NATO and Russian ambassadors said in a statement that they
discussed the situation in and around Kosovo and exchanged views on
NATO-Russia cooperation in the Kosovo international forces (KFOR).
</P>
<P>
The ambassadors at the NATO headquarters also stressed the
importance of the September 19 deadline over the demilitarization and
transformation of the Kosovo Liberation Army (KLA), the armed forces
of Kosovo Albanian separatists "as an additional milestone in
consolidating peace and security in Kosovo".
</P>
<P>
They urged the KLA leadership and "all Kosovar armed elements to
take all necessary measures in order to fulfill all their obligations
in this regard".
</P>
<P>
"NATO and Russia agreed that the international community should
keep this process under close security and ensure its proper
completion," the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also stressed their "commitment to full
implementation of the provisions and goals of United Nations Security
Council Resolution 1244" and "commended the cooperative and
professional relationship" among NATO participating countries and
Russia within KFOR.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the NATO said its Superme Allied Commander Europe,
General Wesley K. Clark, will present the findings of the Kosovo
Strike Assessment Team during a press briefing at NATO headquarters in
Brussels on Thursday. This will be the first NATO assessment for press
about the war against Yugoslavia since early June. 
</P>
