<HEADLINE> Boy of 13 years Old Convicted of Manslaughter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Youth Court in Alberta,
Canada, convicted a 13-year-old boy of manslaughter Wednesday months
after he shot an even younger boy to death at a birthday party.
</P>
<P>
According to a news dispatch from the province, the boy was told of
the conviction he "will live with for a long time". A pre-sentencing
report is due on November 5 for the 13-year-old, who was originally
charged with second-degree murder.
</P>
<P>
In what the court judge called "a horrible tragedy" on March 13, a
boy of 11 years old was shot while playing games with the convict,
whose father had 16 guns at home and was out around 10 p.m., leaving
five children unattended in the house at his son's birthday party.
</P>
<P>
After a horseplay, the two boys began challenging each other by
taking up guns. The victim was aimed at and got shot with a 30-30
calibre hunting rifle.
</P>
<P>
The 13-year-old later called police for help in a panicky voice: "I
just shot this guy. I didn't mean to... He's bleeding everywhere."
</P>
<P>
Individually owned weapons have caused increasing concerns in
Canada. A recent official survey shows "10 percent of Grade 9 boys
said their friends carry weapons." Of the 161 cases of expulsion from
Edmonton schools last year, 62 students were expelled for weapons
offenses, local media said. 
</P>
