<HEADLINE> Poverty, Excessive Consumption Major Causes of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The continued poverty of the
majority of inhabitants of the planet and excessive consumption by
the minority are the two major causes of environmental
degradation, the United Nations Environment Program (UNEP) said.
</P>
<P>
The UNEP revealed the key finding in its Global Environment
Outlook 2000 report issued in Nairobi Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The report is the most authoritative assessment ever of the
environmental crisis facing humanity in the new millennium.
</P>
<P>
It also finds that the present course is unsustainable
development and warns that postponing action is no longer an
option.
</P>
<P>
"Despite successes on various fronts, time for a rational and
well- planned transition to a sustainable system is running out
fast," UNEP Executive Director Klaus Toepfer was quoted as saying
in the report.
</P>
<P>
"In some areas, it has already run out. In others, new problems
are emerging which compound already difficult situations," he
said.
</P>
<P>
"Until recently, few individuals cared about or even knew of
the environmental issues facing the planet. Today, popular
movements in many countries are forcing authorities to make
changes," said Toepfer.
</P>
<P>
In a survey conducted by the scientific team for the report,
200 scientists in 50 countries identified water shortage and
global warming as the two most worrying problems for the new
millennium.
</P>
<P>
Desertification and deforestation at national and regional
levels was also a frequently cited concern in many regions.
</P>
</TEXT>
