<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Crime Can Be Addictive, Says UK Researcher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- People who have committed
criminal offenses tend to continue their activity at the risk of
getting caught because they are addicted to their behaviors, a
leading British criminal psychologist said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Normal criminal "motives" such as financial gain, revenge or group
activity do not seem to be sufficient to explain why some people
continue their life of crime despite the high probability of getting
caught.
</P>
<P>
John Hodge, from Nottinghamshire's Rampton Hospital, Britian's
most secure hospital where criminals with mental disorders are
housed, believed addiction may be the reason.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the British Association's Festival of Science in
Sheffield, England, Hodge said repeat offenders such as serial
killers, rapists and arsonists may be committing the same crimes
again and again because of the feeling that is produced by the act.
</P>
<P>
He said that when criminals carry out an activity to which they
are addicted, it makes them feel good. They then need to spend an
increasing amount of time on the activity in order to achieve the
same positive feelings.
</P>
<P>
Recent research has identified that addiction is not just about
chemical dependancy, and the concept of "behavioral addiction" has
been created to describle gambling, internet use and criminal act.
</P>
<P>
Using these new ideas, Hodge has found that "the criminal
activity can itself become an end in itself with no other purpose
than to help the perpetrator feel better".
</P>
<P>
He believed that examining the possibility of criminal behavior
itself being addictive may develop the understanding of both
addictions and of criminal behavior.
</P>
<P>
"It also opens up to criminals the wide range of interventions now
available to help people with addiction," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0058 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
