<HEADLINE> Kenya's Economic Recovery Needs Time: Central Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Central Bank of Kenya
said Wednesday that the country's economy is expected to remain
weak for the rest of this year and into early 2000.
</P>
<P>
In its September monthly economic review, the bank said that
Kenya's economy could recover in the second half of 2000 if the
government takes reform measures and appropriate economic
policies.
</P>
<P>
Since early this year, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi has
made a series of changes including several cabinet reshuffles in a
bid to recover the country's collapsed economy.
</P>
<P>
Last week, Moi announced a major government reshuffle, cutting
the number of ministries from 27 to 15 in order to improve the
efficiency of public services and reduce the expenditure of the
government.
</P>
<P>
The changes, especially in the public services, are greeted
with the welcome from some international agencies and also with a
glimpse of hope for resuming the negotiations with the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) on a suspended loan package.
</P>
<P>
Kenya's economic growth has declined dramatically since the IMF
 suspended the loan in July 1997. Its gross domestic product
(GDP) growth dropped to 1.8 percent in 1998 from 2.3 percent in
1997.
</P>
<P>
Its GDP further declined to 1.4 percent in the year to June,
due to poor infrastructure, increased insecurity and poor
governance, which lowered production efficiency and reduced
investors' confidence, according to the central bank's economic
review.
</P>
<P>
Permanent Secretary of Finance Ministry Martin Oduor said that
last week' s reshuffle was one of the first steps in Kenya's
journey toward economic recovery and the economy could not turn
around overnight.
</P>
<P>
A senior economist in the central bank held that recent efforts
taken by the government to turn the economy back on track would
need time to produce results. 
</P>
</TEXT>
