<BODY>
<HEADLINE> London Market Ends At Five-week Low </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- London stock market ended
Wednesday at a five-week low as U.S. inflation data failed to
completely reassure traders about the Federal Reserve's next rate
move.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE-100 Index opened in negative territory and stayed
there for most of the day, eventually closing 48.3 points down at
6067.7.
</P>
<P>
The index was weighed down by heavyweight oil stocks suffering
losses, as together, the oil giants constitute around 13 percent
of the blue-chip index.
</P>
<P>
BP Amoco and Shell followed Brent crude oil futures lower after
American Petroleum Institute data slightly disappointed market
makers. BP Amoco was down 34p at 1144p and Shell lost 7.75p to
497.25p.
</P>
<P>
The FTSE Eurotop 300, a broader measure of the largest
pan-European shares, was 0.22 percent lower at the close, at
1312.99.
</P>
<P>
News that U.S. inflation is firmly under wraps provided only a
temporary boost to blue chip shares in London.
</P>
<P>
"It has been a pretty volatile session with the U.S. data
causing gyrations in the market," said the head of trading at a
U.S. bank here. 
</P>
</TEXT>
