<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0063 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> CIS for Joint Action Against Threats to Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The defense officials of nine
member states of the Commonwealth of Independent States vowed here
Wednesday to work together to fight threats to their interests.
</P>
<P>
Any actions undermining the stability and security of CIS
countries "will be regarded as a threat to their national and
collective interests," said a joint statement approved by an
extraordinary meeting of CIS defense ministers.
</P>
<P>
The ministers confirmed their readiness "to take adequate joint
steps to prevent and eliminate" threats to their interests in the
framework of multilateral and bilateral understandings, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
They aired their support for the efforts of Central Asian
countries and Russia to stabilize the situation in Kyrgyzstan,
where large militant formations have occupied areas in the south.
</P>
<P>
The closed-door conference addressed the situation in southern
Kyrgyzstan and mapped out urgent measures to render military-
technical and other assistance in stabilizing the situation to
Bishkek, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
They expressed grave concern over the operations of terrorist
groups and said that such actions "create a threat to the security
of Central Asia as a whole, not just Kyrgyzstan."
</P>
<P>
The extraordinary meeting was called at the initiative of
Kyrgyz President Askar Akayev for the discussion of military aid
and supplies to Kyrgyzstan, which has been invaded by militants
from Tajikistan.
</P>
<P>
It is being attended by the Armenian, Belarussian, Kazakh,
Kyrgyz, Tajik and Russian defense ministers. Azerbaijan and
Georgia have also sent representatives.
</P>
<P>
Russian Prime Minister Vladimir Putin addressed the meeting,
saying international terrorism plans to destroy the CIS and set up
military dictatorships throughout the region.
</P>
<P>
"Those who pull the strings want the armed gangs to destroy the
common policy and the very unity of the Commonwealth countries,
subvert their security and establish pseudo-theocratic but
essentially military dictatorial regimes in countries which have
traditionally been close to us," he said.
</P>
<P>
Putin said the plans should be nipped in the bud.
</P>
<P>
"We must use all the resources of our organization and will" to
tackle the problem, he said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed Moscow's special interest in continuing the
dialogue and working out a common position with Trans-Caucasian
countries.
</P>
<P>
"The governments of Azerbaijan and Georgia will hopefully join
our consultations soon," he said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
