<HEADLINE> UNICEF Official Killed in Southern Somalia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOGADISHU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Unidentified Somali gunmen
Wednesday afternoon ambushed a UNICEF vehicle transporting senior
health officials and local staff members, killing one and wounding
five others.
</P>
<P>
The tragedy took place near Qalimow village, about 20
kilometers southwest of Jowhar town . Ayub Sheikh Yarow Abdiyow,
the UNICEF official in charge of the health and nutrition in
southern Somalia was killed when gunmen opened fire
indiscriminately on the Land-Cruiser.
</P>
<P>
Ayub's death was announced Thursday in the ICRC run Keysaney
hospital of north Mogadishu.
</P>
<P>
Witnesses said the driver, though suffered a hand injury, was
courageous enough to speed away through the rain of bullets fired
by the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
It is said that the gunmen were waiting on both sides of the
road targeting precious vehicles. The UNICEF vihicle was attacked
with no one had come out to help or defend them.
</P>
<P>
The shooting shocked many Somalis and those from the
humanitarian organizations.
</P>
<P>
Last month, Qasim Aden Egal, a Spanish senior officer in Lower
Jubba and Gedo regions of southern Somalia, was also killed in an
ambush by freelance gunmen near Jilib town.
</P>
<P>
Hundreds of people attended Ayub's funeral Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The reason for the attack is not known, however some reports
are relating the incident to rampant banditry activities.
</P>
<P>
In another event, the local authorities in the northeastern
region of Puntland detained a Somali-Canadian aid worker in
Garoweh district of Nugal region two days ago. The aid worker,
Faiza Abdisamad Warsameh, was detained after she allegedly made a
draft report on the Somali culture.
</P>
<P>
The local authorities of Puntland accused Faiza for propagating
anti- Islam culture and abusing the Koranic versus and the
narration of Prophet Mohammed concerning the Muslim women rights
and behaviors.
</P>
<P>
They took her before a court in the town, but a decision has
not been made yet. The authorities said they would proceed with
the legal aspects of her case. However, other sources said the
whole issue is a complicated case concerning money bribes which
she ought to give to the big brasses of the town before going
ahead with her seminar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
