<HEADLINE> Chinese Paleontologists Getting Close to Origin of Birds (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
In January, a palaeoanthropologist, Wu Xinzhi, wrote in the U.S.
journal "Science" on Peking Man's use of fire at Zhoukoudian, the
site near Beijing, and Zhu Min, also at the institute, unraveled a
mystery about primitive fish fossils in the British journal "
Nature" in February.
</P>
<P>
Chinese paleontologists have done a lot of research in
palaeoanthropology on origin of birds and feathered dinosaurs
recently, said Ye Jie, deputy director of the Institute of
Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology, and have attracted
attention from academics elsewhere. China has a lot of potential
in this research, he said.
</P>
<P>
China has many fossils, giving it an advantage in paleontology
research, and some reforms in the Institute encourage young
scientist to play a more important role in research. Most of the
authors of the articles mentioned above are less than 40 years old.
</P>
