<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon York Moves Away from Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Typhoon York, that caused
widespread damage and flooding to Hong Kong, has slowly moved away
from the region late Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest release issued by the Hong Kong
Observatory, the No. 3 strong wind signal has been hoisted at 22:
10 to replace the No. 8 Southwest gale or storm signal.
</P>
<P>
At 20:00, Typhoon York was about 60 kilometers west of Hong
Kong heading west-northwest at 10 kilometers an hour and due to
make landfall near Zhuhai in the Pearl River Delta in Guangdong,
China.
</P>
<P>
Tung Chee Hwa, chief executive of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region, who had himself been at work in his office
for part of the day, was especially concerned about the number of
casualties and the condition of those injured.
</P>
<P>
He also thanked the operational departments and emergency
services for their efforts serving the public in the heavy rain
and strong wind.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong government said that up till now one man was
killed, one was missing and 466 people have been injured during
the passage of Typhoon York, the strongest storm to hit Hong Kong
in 16 years.
</P>
<P>
Among those injured, eleven persons remain in hospital in
serious condition, the remainder are in stable or satisfactory
condition.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Signal No. 10 was hoisted at 06:45 to replace the
Tropical Cyclone Signal No. 9, which was hoisted at 05:20 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
More than 470 flights had been affected by the bad weather
while ferry, and tram services remain suspended.
</P>
<P>
The airport, express railway, KCR, light rail transit and two
buses companies are providing limited services.
</P>
<P>
A total of 55 cases of flooding have been recorded and sections
of 86 roads had been closed because of fallen trees, collapsed or
dangerous scaffoldings or sign boards and broken windows.
</P>
<P>
The No. 10 signal had been hoisted 12 times in Hong Kong since
1946, from when records are available.
</P>
<P>
The last hurricane signal No. 10 was hoisted on September 9,
1983 during the passage of Typhoon Ellen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
