<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0081 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Energy-Saving Legislation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Legislation to effectively
save energy in the Chinese capital was approved today by the
Standing Committee of the Beijing Municipal People's Congress, the
city's legislative body, and will take effect December 1.
</P>
<P>
Energy shortage and mismanagement have been major problems for
economic development in Beijing, officials here said. The city
consumes huge amounts of energy every year, and is second only to
Shanghai in energy use.
</P>
<P>
Much of Beijing's energy comes from coal, which is the major
culprit in the city's heavy air pollution, they said, so the "
methods of implementing China's energy-saving law" call for
transforming Beijing into an energy-saving city, limiting energy-
consumption by industries, and adjusting its energy structure.
</P>
<P>
The methods say that all capital investment projects will have
to have preliminary energy-use studies and major energy users will
be put under stricter controls and supervision, and energy-saving
will have to be worked into the market mechanism. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0082 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore, China Have Confidence in Good Faith: Lee Hsien Loong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Singapore Deputy Prime
Minister Lee Hsien Loong said China and Singapore have confidence
in good faith and problems emerging in carrying out the project of
the Suzhou Industrial Park (SIP) have not affected bilateral ties,
Television Corporation of Singapore (TCS) reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
TCS quoted Lee as telling reporters at the end of his four-day
visit to the SIP that even though there are problems to be
overcome between China and Singapore over the SIP, both sides have
done so in a way which had not affected bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Both countries have been able to establish confidence in good
faith, Lee was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Lee also made it clear that government to government
cooperation on the economic front can be carried out only if
enterprises are commercially viable, TCS said.
</P>
<P>
Lee flew to China on September 13 and then co-chaired the
Fourth Meeting of the China-Singapore Joint Steering Council on
SIP with Chinese Vice Premier Li Lanqing.
</P>
<P>
At the meeting both countries endorsed a memorandum of
understanding (MOU) signed by Chinese and Singapore teams on June
28, 1999, which charted out the SIP's next phase of development.
</P>
<P>
In the MOU, Chinese and Singapore teams agreed on the package
of solution to put the SIP project on a more successful footing.
</P>
<P>
Under the MOU, from January 1, 2001, the Chinese Consortium
will increase its shareholding in the Chinese-Singapore SIP
Development Co. Ltd. (CSSD) from present 35 percent to 65 percent
while the Singapore Consortium will reduce its shareholding in the
CSSD from present 65 percent to 35 percent. 
</P>
</TEXT>
