<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cai Upbeat about Another Clean Sweep </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUILIN, China, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Cai Zhenhua, who guided
the all-conquering Chinese team home from last month's 45th World
Table Tennis Chinese Championships full-handed with all five gold
and silver medals on offer, predicted another Chinese clean sweep
this time here today.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese head coach said unless something extrordinary
happens, China, who fielded a first-string paddlers to '99 China
Grand Prix which started here today, will sweep the board, once
and again.
</P>
<P>
"I am being cautious to say that we can at least land two of
the possible four golds. The fact is, it's every inch possible for
us to make another clean sweep," Cai, himself a world
championships men's singles silver medallist in 1981, said.
</P>
<P>
Though it's a little bit hard to get players motivated after
the Eindhoven world championships - they took some days off to
have a rest from hectic schedules - the Chinese superiority is
clean and clear, Cai said.
</P>
<P>
All the female players - they are all Chinese - who made the
podium at the world championships are competing here while the men
's field appeared depleted as some of the top European players -
such as Jan-ove Waldner of Sweden, Vladimir Samsonov of Russia,
Zoran Primorac of Croatia, failed to show up.
</P>
<P>
Liu Guoliang and Wang Nan, newly-crowned men's and women's
singles world champions respectively, could be struggling to
defend their titles since both of them had injury problem, Cai
revealed, but this would be a good opportunity for other Chinese
players.
</P>
<P>
But Cai, who masterminded the Chinese monopoly at Eindhoven
which saw the table tennis individual worlds transform into a
domestic championship with all the finalists in the five
catogaries are Chinese, refused to predict who are going to emerge
the winners from the ITTF Pro-Tour event.
</P>
<P>
China Grand Prix, inaugurated back in 1988, run from 16-18 with
114 players from 18 countries and regions vying for a 61,000 US
dollars prize money. 
</P>
</TEXT>
