<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Companies Losing to Save Brands </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Stiff competition is underway
among multinational cosmetic companies in efforts to save brands
at a substantial loss, the Globe and Mail reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The insolvent T. Eaton Co. Ltd. is busy negotiating deals, not
of liquidation sales, but of profit-making reselling of cosmetics
to famous suppliers such as Estee Lauder Inc.
</P>
<P>
The industry leader is reported to have cleared its goods
ranging from fragrances to skin care products out of Eaton's,
leaving behind empty shelves that were used for the proud display
of Estee Lauder, Clinique and Prescriptives brands.
</P>
<P>
Chanel Inc., Shiseido Co. Ltd., Elizabeth Arden Canada and some
other high-profile cosmetics makers are still in talks with Eaton'
s liquidators to buy back their products at the stores.
</P>
<P>
Executives of the cosmetic companies would not disclose how
much they offered to buy back their products. But insiders have
expected the repurchasing deals at about 80 percent of their
retail value.
</P>
<P>
In the case of Estee Lauder, up to 20 million Canadian dollars
(about 14 million U.S. dollars) may have been paid for the goods
that were originally sold to Eaton's at 15 million dollars (about
10 million U.S. dollars), the newspaper quoted insiders as saying.
</P>
<P>
The companies don't want to see products they have spent
millions of dollars marketing sold at steep discounts in a fire-
sale atmosphere, the newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
The cosmetic companies began taking steps to retrieve their
products after Eaton's was awarded court protection from creditors
on August 23. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
