<HEADLINE> Bangladesh, Morocco Sign Trade Agreement </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh and Morocco signed a
trade agreement Thursday to develop, extend and strengthen the
commercial relations and promote exchange of goods and services
between the two countries, the official BSS news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The accord, the first of its kind between the two countries,
was signed by Bangladeshi Commerce and Industries Minister Tofail
Ahmed and his Moroccan counterpart Alami Tazi, in Marrakech,
Morocco.
</P>
<P>
The aim of the agreement, which would remain valid for a
five-year period and could be renewed thereafter on a yearly basis
automatically, was to further expand bilateral trade and
investment, the BSS said.
</P>
<P>
The agreement would provide the basic framework of cooperation
between business companies and organization of trade fairs. And
the contracting parties would facilitate the transit of goods
originating from the territory of the other counteracting party or
destined to the other contracting party.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade between the two countries would reach a new
level as "we now have the agreement in place," Ahmed was quoted as
saying.
</P>
<P>
He urged the Moroccan entrepreneurs and investors to invest in
Bangladesh by utilizing attractive facilities provided by the
Bangladeshi government.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladeshi minister called upon the Moroccan authorities
to encourage exchange of private sector delegations, saying that
there was scope for expanding cooperation including joint ventures
between the entrepreneurs of the two countries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
