<HEADLINE> Manila to Send 240-man Contingent to East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines will send to
East Timor an initial contingent of 240 officers and men, mostly
army engineers and doctors, as part of the advance international
peacekeeping force to that strife-torn territory, a senior
military official said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado said he was instructed by
President Joseph Estrada, who is on a four-day state visit to
Chile, to immediately deploy the two companies to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Mercado said he will meet with Air Marshall Douglas Ryding,
vice chief of the Australian Defense Force, Friday here to discuss
details of the U.N. peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
"After we have our discussions tomorrow, we will have a clear
picture of the composition and how it moves," Mercado said. "We
are hoping to deploy this (Philippine contingent) in a week's
time."
</P>
<P>
The Philippine contingent will probably go first to Australia
before proceeding to Dili, the capital of East Timor, Philippine
News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Australia will be the lead country of the U.N. peacekeeping
force to be deployed to East Timor which has been rocked by
violence after pro-independence faction won the ballot for an
independent state.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has committed to the United Nations to sending
one or two battalions to East Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
