<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0099 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai's New International Airport Opens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's Pudong
International Airport opened to traffic today.
</P>
<P>
China Eastern Airlines and Shanghai Airlines, which are based
in Shanghai, had inaugural flights this morning from the new
airport to Xiamen in southeast China's Fujian Province and Kunming
in southwest China's Yunnan Province, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The new airport covers a 12-sq.km. area and has a runway which
is 4,000-meter long and 60 meters wide and a terminal building
with a total floor space of 280,000 square meters.
</P>
<P>
It can handle 20 million passengers and 750,000 tons of cargo
annually.
</P>
<P>
The construction work cost 13 billion yuan (about 1.6 billion U.
S. dollars) and has taken more than two years. The new airport
will make Shanghai the first Chinese city with two large
international airports.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai's air traffic has grown 23 percent annually on average
in recent years and it had 13.7 million passengers in 1998,
according to the official.
</P>
<P>
Its other airport, Hongqiao, has an annual handling capacity of
9.6 million passengers, which is far from adequate for the rapidly
increasing demand, so the new airport will help the city increase
its capacity to meet the needs of future development, the official
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
