<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Archaeological Landmark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists have
discovered 80 pieces of stone armors and 30 stone helmets in a
burial pit at the tomb of China's first emperor, which has been
called by some "the eighth wonder of the world".
</P>
<P>
The 13,000-square-meter pit is in the southeast part of a
burial ground and is similar in shape to the two large pits that
were found earlier.
</P>
<P>
The armors and helmets are made of dark blue stone plates of
uniform thickness that are attached with copper strips,
archaeologists said at a press conference in Xi'an today.
</P>
<P>
They believe that the stone came from a mountainous area 50 km
north of the tomb and some say that it is hard to imagine how
large stone could be worked into small flat plates with holes
drilled without the use of advanced machine tools.
</P>
<P>
One Chinese scholar called the find "unprecedented" and said
that "such perfect craftsmanship has never been recorded and that
the items fill a gap in the understanding of Chinese military
equipment in ancient times."
</P>
<P>
They could be important to the study of political, economic,
military, scientific and cultural developments of the Qin Dynasty,
according to Wu Yongqi, the curator of the Qin Shihuang Terra-
cotta Warrior Museum.
</P>
<P>
The stone helmets help correct a traditional misconception that
during the Qin Dynasty people were unable to make helmets, he
added.
</P>
<P>
Another treasure dug up from the new pit is a 212-kg bronze
tripod, the heaviest found since New China was founded in 1949.
</P>
<P>
Last May, archaeologists unearthed a dozen colored pottery
figurines, some of which have big bellies. One archaeologist
surmised that they are doing Qigong, a system of deep breathing
exercises, or doing acrobatics.
</P>
<P>
According to historical records, the emperor Qin Shihuang
forced 800,000 workers to build the tomb for him when he was only
13 years old.
</P>
<P>
This splendid archeological find was accidentally discovered in
1974 by a farmer who was digging a well. Since then, three huge
pits have been discovered near the tomb.
</P>
<P>
More than seven thousand 2,200-year-old life-sized terra cotta
warriors and horses and tens of thousands of weapons have been
discovered in the three pits.
</P>
<P>
The purpose of the warriors and horses, which are less than a
mile from the emperor's tomb, was to protect the spirit of their
ruler through eternity, an archaeologist explained. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Stages Cancelled after Rain </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUAIROU, Beijing, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The second and the
sixth stages of the first-day route in the China Rally, the 11th
round of the World Rally Championship, are to be cancelled for
rain damage, a top organising official said on Thursday here.
</P>
<P>
Overnight heavy rain on Wednesday caused unpassable damages on
the road in the Qidaohe stage, the longest one of 33.07 kilometers
in the first leg, with 20 stages left in the rally, which is for
the first time included by the FIA in the World Champoinship.
</P>
<P>
The traditional super-special had been cut off due to the rain,
which continually hit the area on Thursday, and the opening
ceremony was postponed to Friday's morning before the start of the
race on eight o'clock of the local time.
</P>
<P>
A total of 67 cars entered the rally, the only round held in
Asia in the World Rally, with defending champion Tommi Makinen of
Mistubishi leading the drivers to start the first leg.
</P>
<P>
Australia's Possum Bourne, leader of the Asia-Pacific Rally
Championship, pulled out of the race because he crashed in a
domestic competition before he came to China.
</P>
<P>
Yoshihiro Kataoka of Japan, who is sharing the top place with
Bourne on 35 points, is set to win the regional race because the
China Rally is the last stop after Rally de Nouvelle Caledonie was
cancelled. 
</P>
