<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Van Gogh Drawing Unveiled 60 Years After Looting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- British auctioneers unveiled
on Thursday a pen-and-ink drawing by Dutch artist Vincent Van Gogh,
which was returned to the family of a Jewish collector 60 years
after being looted by the Nazis.
</P>
<P>
L'Olivette (Les Baux), showing twisted olive trees set in front
of rolling French hills, will be sold in December by an elderly
relative of manufacturer Max Silberberg, who died in a Nazi
concentration camp, the Reuters reported.
</P>
<P>
The drawing could fetch about 3 million pounds (4.8 million U.S.
dollars) at auction.
</P>
<P>
Experts say it may be the first of a wave of art coming to the
market which was seized in Nazi Germany and is now being returned
to its owners' descendants.
</P>
<P>
L'Olivette was returned to 85-year-old Gerta Silberberg last
month after she was able to prove the drawing was seized from her
father-in-law in a "forced sale" before ending up in Berlin's
National Gallery.
</P>
<P>
Silberberg's drawing was handed over by the Berlin gallery once
it became clear there was a legitimate claim on it.
</P>
<P>
Experts said more valuable looted art was likely to be returned
to its owners as archives in eastern Europe, hidden during the
Cold War, were opened up. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
