<HEADLINE> Chinese Paleontologists Getting Close To Origin Of Birds (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese paleontologist and
his colleagues at the Chinese Academy of Sciences' Institute of
Vertebrate Paleontology and Paleoanthropology have published a new
study on the origin of birds in the British journal "Nature".
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old paleontologist Xu Xing and his colleagues have
published 6 articles in "Nature" and in the U.S. journal "Science
" on a feathered dinosaur, Sinornithosaurus, which may be the
ancestor of birds. Xu offers a lot of information for use in the
study of the origin of birds.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, he and the other scientists wrote that the
feathers of modern birds most likely originate from a down-like
integumentary structure on a new kind of dinosaur they found in
northeastern China.
</P>
<P>
However, Professor Hou Lianhai of the same institute disagreed
in an article in "Nature" and challenged the widely-believed
theory of the bird links.
</P>
<P>
After that, Swisher Carl of the Berkeley Geochronology Center
in the United States and Wang Yuanqing and other scientists at CAS
pinpointed the age of many fossils found in Liaoning Province in
northeast China, including several kinds of feathered dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
The results, which were published in "Nature," say that the
fossils were younger than was previously thought and have forced
scientists to re-consider the complexity of evolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
