<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Join U.N. Multinational Force for E.Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia will send a
team of military officers to join the U.N. Multinational Force for
East Timor to restore order, Foreign Minister Syed Hamid Albar
said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Malaysia, having reviewed the latest developments in East
Timor including requests by ASEAN member countries particularly
Indonesia, has decided to be part of the Multinational Force," he
said in a statement here.
</P>
<P>
With this view in mind, the Ministry of Defense is organizing a
team of military officers to join the Multinational Force for East
Timor, he said.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia has, in principle, stated its readiness to participate
in the United Nations Peacekeeping Operation for East Timor when
it is constituted, Syed Hamid said, adding the Multinational Force
will be as authorized by the United Nations Security Council
Resolution 1264 (1999) adopted on September 15, 1999.
</P>
<P>
According to Bernama news agency, Malaysian Defense Minister
Abang Abu Bakar Mustapha said that the strength of Malaysia's team
of military officers would depend on the U.N. which would
determine the number.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian officials in the U.N. are in discussion with the U.N.
on the involvement of a peacekeeping force whose number had not
been determined, Abang Abu Bakar said.
</P>
<P>
The First Phase Multinational Force would be in East Timor for
six weeks, to be followed by the Second Phase U.N. Peacekeeping
Force, the defense minister said, hoping that the Second Phase
will comprise ASEAN countries under the auspices of the U.N.
</P>
<P>
He also hoped the U.N. force commander would be an officer from
an ASEAN country as East Timor is in the ASEAN region. 
</P>
