<HEADLINE> Share Prices Plunge in Tokyo on Yen's Rapid Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices tumbled in Tokyo
Thursday, dampened by the yen's rapid rise against the U.S. dollar.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange lost 485.63 points, or 2.73
percent, from Tuesday's close to end at 17,291.59. The Tokyo
stocks market was closed Wednesday for a national holiday.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, fell 29.01 points or 1.90 percent to 1,495.
78.
</P>
<P>
After opening at the day's high of 17,703.97, the key Nikkei
index remained weak throughout the day, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Wednesday's fall on Wall Street, where the Dow Jones Industrial
Average and the Nasdaq composite index both declined sharply, also
encouraged investors to sell Japanese stocks, they said.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section increased to 602.70 million
shares from Tuesday's 565.95 million shares.
</P>
<P>
Nippon Steel was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Share prices were lower in most business sectors, and export-
oriented issues, in particular, weakened on fears that the strong
yen will hurt their earnings, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers far
outnumbered gainers 820 to 387, with 136 issues ending unchanged.
</P>
<P>
On the Tokyo Foreign Exchange, the U.S. dollar traded at 104.82-
85 yen at 5 p.m., sharply down from 106.55-58 yen late Tuesday in
Tokyo, after falling to the 103 yen level in overseas markets
Wednesday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
