<HEADLINE> Zambia Urged to Sell Copper Mines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Donors have urged the Zambian
government to sell quickly the country's remaining copper mines,
Times of Zambia reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Zambia should weigh all options for the purpose of disposing
Nchanga and Nkana mines of Zambia Consolidated Copper Mines
(ZCCM), the donor community was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, both bilateral and multilateral donors
are anxious to see what the government will do next since the
Chilean mining company, Codelco, has pulled out of a partnership
deal with Angol-American Corporation (ACC) last month.
</P>
<P>
ACC reached a memorandum at the end of last month with Zambia
on the purchase of Nchanga and Nkana mines, which account for more
than 60 percent of ZCCM assets. However, no final deal has been
made.
</P>
<P>
The pulling out of the deal by Codelco will further delay
Zambia's privatization process of its ailing mining industry.
</P>
<P>
The International Finance Company (IFC), which is in the
process of contemplating a financial partnership with ACC, is also
on hold, the newspaper quoted sources as saying.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot say that the IFC is out but they, like everybody
else, are waiting to see what the government will do next," they
said.
</P>
<P>
Zambia has been trying to privatize its mines in order to get
foreign investment, expertise and advanced management into this
sector. 
</P>
</TEXT>
