<HEADLINE> Strong Typhoon Sweeps South China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A strong typhoon with winds
of up to 30 meters per second lashed the capital of the south
China province of Guangdong today, disrupting traffic and forcing
many stay at home.
</P>
<P>
This is the first time since 1975 that the city has been hit
squarely by a typhoon, which is now heading northwest of the
province at 10 to 15 kilometers per hour, according to the
Guangzhou Central Meteorological Station.
</P>
<P>
Since last evening, the city of Guangzhou have been pounded by
strong winds and heavy rains, resulting in flooding and traffic
disruption in the city.
</P>
<P>
All passenger ships in the city were shut down, and bus routes
to the neighboring cities of Zhuhai and Shenzhen were suspended.
</P>
<P>
Around 10 a.m. airports in Hong Kong, Macao, Shenzhen, and
Zhuhai were temporarily closed. At press time, the Baiyun airport
in Guangzhou was still operating.
</P>
<P>
The typhoon, the 10th this year, also forced the closing of
primary and middle schools in the city today.
</P>
<P>
According to forecasts, this typhoon will bring heavy rains to
southern and central Guangdong.
</P>
<P>
The province is closely monitoring the typhoon's movement, and
measures have been taken to deal with damage left in its wake.
</P>
</TEXT>
