<HEADLINE> Typhoon York Causes Damage, Flooding in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Typhoon York caused
widespread damage and flooding to Hong Kong though the No.8
Southwest gale or storm signal has been hoisted to replace the No.
10 hurricane signal at 17:45, said Hong Kong Observatory on
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At 18:00, Typhoon York was about 50 kilometers west of Hong
Kong heading west-northwest at 10 kmh and due to make landfall
near Zhuhai in the Pearl River Delta in Guangdong, China.
</P>
<P>
According to the latest government press release, one man has
died, one is missing and 441 people have been injured during the
passage of Typhoon York, the strongest storm to hit Hong Kong in
16 years.
</P>
<P>
Of those injured, 246 were males and 195 women. Eleven persons
remain in hospital in serious condition, while 133 have been
discharged. The remainder are in stable or satisfactory condition.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong government urged the residents to remain indoors.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Signal No. 10 was hoisted at 06:45 to replace the
Tropical Cyclone Signal No. 9, which was hoisted at 05:20 Thursday.
</P>
<P>
More than 250 flights had been affected by the bad weather,
ferry, tram and KCR services remain suspended while the airport
express railway and two buses companies are providing limited
services and the light rail transit services began resuming
services gradually from 17:50.
</P>
<P>
A total of 40 cases of flooding have been recorded.
</P>
<P>
Up till now, the No.10 signal has been hoisted 12 times in Hong
Kong since 1946, when records were first available.
</P>
<P>
The last hurricane signal No.10 was hoisted on September 9,
1983 during the passage of Typhoon Ellen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
