<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 12:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Algerians Vote on National Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALGIERS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Algerians began voting
Thursday in a referendum on a plan raised by President Abdelaziz
Bouteflika that is meant to achieve national reconciliation in the
war-torn north African country.
</P>
<P>
The 17.5 million eligible voters will cast their votes in 8,553
polling centers and 38,789 stations across the country, the
Algerian news agency reported. Polls will close at 8:00 p.m. (1900
GMT).
</P>
<P>
The ballot in Thursday's voting asks Algerian voters a single
question: "Do you agree with the steps by the president of the
republic toward civil concord?"
</P>
<P>
National reconciliation has been Bouteflika's top priority
since his election in April.
</P>
<P>
In his inaugural speech on May 29, Bouteflika called for
national reconciliation and taking a new stride towards the
reawakening of national consciousness, to free the nation of the
present crisis and to engage in building a prosperous and just
society with the advent of the third millennium.
</P>
<P>
Algeria has been dogged by a civil war that started in early
1992 after the military-backed government canceled elections that
the now-banned Islamic Salvation Front was poised to win. So far,
100,000 people have died in the conflicts.
</P>
<P>
In response to Bouteflika's call for national reconciliation,
the Islamic Salvation Army, the military wing of the Islamic
Salvation Front, announced on June 6 the end of fighting
definitively and the willingness to use its forces for "the
defense of the people and in the service of the nation."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Abbas Madani, the founding member of the front who
is serving a 14-year jail term, also presented message to
Bouteflika on June 11, voicing absolute support of the truce
endeavour.
</P>
<P>
He also called upon all his armed men wherever they may be, in
and out of the country, to respect the effort.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, Bouteflika's national reconciliation call also drew
wide support among various parties and organizations, which
expressed hope to end the bloodshed and restore security and
stability in Algeria.
</P>
<P>
The initiative raised by Bouteflika in July has been passed by
parliament, but he wanted public approval as well. On August 1,
the president signed a decree to hold a referendum on the proposal
on September 16.
</P>
<P>
The centerpiece of the peace plan is an amnesty and reduction
in prison terms for Islamic insurgents found innocent of rape,
murder or planting bombs and provided they give up their weapons.
</P>
<P>
In a goodwill gesture, Bouteflika granted an amnesty Wednesday
to more than 1 million draft dodgers, which would let them get
identity cards necessary for employment and to hold a passport.
</P>
<P>
Bouteflika, Algeria's first civilian leader in 24 years, has
said he will resign if voters fail to approve his proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
