<HEADLINE> Makinen Confident in Mysterious China Rally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUAIROU, Beijing, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Reigning champion
Tommi Makinen seemed never concerned about the completely unknown
China Rally, which for the first time included in the World Rally
Championship, as the Finn was confident to record a fourth
consecutive victory in the world championship.
</P>
<P>
"I'm quiet confident to win here," said the Mitsubishi driver,
who is comfortably leading the drivers championship with 48 points.
"We are still in a good position in the Champoinship, so I think
this rally could be more difficult for the others than for us."
</P>
<P>
Most of the top drivers have no idea of the only round held in
Asia, with just Colin McRae of Ford and Piero Liatti of SEAT Sport
having experiences of the event, which is held north of Beijing
based in Huairou, close to the Great Wall.
</P>
<P>
But Makinen, who has won three rallies this year, was not
worried about the lack of knowledge of the condition. "I don't
think knowing the roads will be so important," He declared.
</P>
<P>
Overnight rain on Wednesday increased the unpredictable vision
on the road, a mixture of gravel and asphalt covered with half-
buried stones and a lot of large rocks, which is one of the
toughest round in the championship as was claimed by every drivers
after recce.
</P>
<P>
McRae's co-driver Nicky Grist said, "Given the very slippery
conditions, it will be a case of a lot more luck than anything
else will help a driver win this rally."
</P>
<P>
While Liatti, who finished second to McRae in last year's China
Rally, thought the experiences in China would play a 10 per cent
advantage coming into the race, which to set off on Friday morning.
</P>
<P>
Both McRae, current sixth in the drivers standings with 23
pionts, and Liatti, who is out of the top ten, almost have no
chance to usurp Makinen in this year's championship, which has
three rounds left after the China Rally.
</P>
<P>
Toyota's team driver Didier Auriol, the closest challenger to
Makinen with 38 points, could not be optimistic to the three-day
event.
</P>
<P>
"I think we need quite a lot of luck for this event," Auriol
said. "I don't really think about the title, I just try to be able
to drive my best in each event. If the title comes it comes, if it
doesn't it doesn't."
</P>
<P>
Auriol's teammate Carlos Sainz shares the third place with
Subaru's veteran Juha Kankkunen on 34 points. Kankkunen has just
won the Finland Rally in an impressive fashion and became one of
the most successive drivers in the 26-year championship with a
record 23 wins.
</P>
<P>
"The surface here is very much like that in Portugal and
Indonesia," Kankkunen said. "The road is very tricky and it's not
so easy (to drive here)."
</P>
<P>
"But it should be good to our car. The car was really going
well in the last rally."
</P>
<P>
Fifth-placed Richard Burns of Subaru has driven in the Hong
Kong-Beijing rally before, but he found no similarity of the two
races.
</P>
<P>
"Before (the rain) we maybe had an advantage knowing how long
the tyres would last in race, but now it is completely different.
So we are on the same footing as everybody else."
</P>
<P>
The China Rally is also the last stop of the prestigious Asian-
Pacific Rally Championship after the Rally de Nouvelle Caledonie
was cancelled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
