<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Preparing For Global Ozone Layer Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China is preparing for the
11th meeting of participants in the Montreal Protocol on depletion
of the ozone layer, which is expected to be held in Beijing, from
November 29 to Decenber 3, a State Environmental Protection
Administration (SEPA) official said today.
</P>
<P>
The Montreal Protocol has been seen as a successful example of
international cooperation on environmental problems. Participants
in the Montreal Protocol, UN organizations, and 1,000 delegates of
non-governmental organizations will take part in the meeting.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has established a preparatory committee,
headed by Vice-Premier Wen Jiabao and SEPA's Director Xie Zhenhua.
</P>
<P>
According to the Montreal Protocol, developing countries were
to stop the production and use of ozone-depleting substances from
July 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The Montreal Protocol, was adopted in 1987 under the United
Nations Environment Program auspices and has 168 participants.
</P>
<P>
China signed the protocol and took part in international
cooperation on ozone layer protection in 1991. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0126 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China Province Leading Reforms, Opening-up </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- After 2 decades of reforms
in China, Guangdong Province in the South, plans to continue its
role as a pioneer in those reforms and opening up, according to
Governor Lu Ruihua.
</P>
<P>
Lu told Xinhua that Guangdong's reforms and opening up will
concentrate on finance and insurance and allowing a greater market
share to go to overseas retail businesses and financial services.
</P>
<P>
Because of its closeness to Hong Kong, Guangdong has been
designated by the Chinese government as an experimental area for
its opening-up policy to provide experience for other parts of the
country to follow.
</P>
<P>
It has 3 of China's first 4 special economic zones in Shenzhen,
Zhuhai, and Shantou, which led the transition to market controls
in the 1980s and the introduction of reforms in State-owned
enterprises in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
The province has set up an overseas-oriented economic system
with more than 57,000 overseas-funded companies and over half the
world's top 100 enterprises are in Guangdong in one way or another.
</P>
<P>
That experiment also made the province the country's major
exporter and source of tax revenues and it accounts for some 10
percent of the country's total GDP.
</P>
<P>
The financial reforms are China's newest experiment in
Guangdong of increasing financial reforms and opening-up while
avoiding financial risks.
</P>
<P>
Overseas banks and insurance companies have already begun
queuing up for a share of the market, and 4 banks in Shenzhen,
which were among the first to be allowed to do the yuan-based
business last year, are considering expanding their business.
</P>
<P>
Overseas retailers are equally interested. The U.S. Wal-Mart,
the first foreign retailer to enter the Chinese mainland three
years ago, has four stores, but it now faces challenges from a
number of competitors like France's Carrefour and Taiwan's Better
Group and Guangdong has become a commercial battle ground for
famous brand names.
</P>
<P>
The foreign competition has stimulated Chinese companies and
Guangdong now has a number of internationally competitive
enterprises with more than 800 branches or companies abroad.
</P>
<P>
To lead the rest of the country and catch up with the world's
industrialized countries in the next century, Guangdong has a goal
of 240 billion U.S. dollars worth of exports and 190 billion U.S.
dollars of overseas investment by the year 2010, the governor
said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0127 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues New Codes on Prosecution of Corruption (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua)-- China's highest procuratorate
today promulgated a new set of codes dealing with crimes committed
by officials such as taking bribery, malfeasance, and abuse of
power, and said these crimes shall be prosecuted.
</P>
<P>
"The new codes relaxed standards on crimes that can be measured
by the amount of illicit money involved, but tightened those on
the deaths or injuries they cause," said Zhang Qiong, deputy
procurator-general of the Supreme People's Procuratorate, at a
press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
"The alterations have been based on China's new realities and
to better facilitate the punishment of corruption according to law,
" Zhang said, noting that the new regulation will help prosecutors
to combat corruption more effectively.
</P>
<P>
According to the new standards, a government employee who has
committed one or more of the following acts shall be investigated
and prosecuted by the public prosecutors:
</P>
<P>
-- embezzling or taking bribes worth more than 5,000 yuan (605
US dollars), or less than 5,000 yuan, but causing dire
consequences;
</P>
<P>
-- misappropriating over 5,000 to 10,000 yuan (1,210 US dollars)
of public funds for illegal activities, or over 10,000 to 30,000
yuan (3,630 US dollars) to seek profit for one's own business,
with the exact amount decided upon by local procuratorates
according to their specific economic situations;
</P>
<P>
-- abusing authority and causing over 200,000 yuan (24,180 US
dollars) of direct economic loss; dereliction of duty, causing
over 300,000 yuan of direct economic loss or one million yuan of
indirect loss.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Issues New Codes on Prosecution of Corruption (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A government department that takes bribes worth more than 100,
000 yuan (12,100 US dollars) shall also be subjected to
prosecution.
</P>
<P>
One of the most notable relaxation of standards is that the
amount for prosecuting the crime of possessing inexplicable
valuable property and concealing secret savings in overseas banks
has been increased from 100,000 yuan (12,100 US dollars) to 300,
000 yuan (36,300 US dollars).
</P>
<P>
"It's relatively easy for an official to make up sources for
property worth 100,000 yuan, and it is difficult for prosecutors
to verify the facts today," Zhang explained.
</P>
<P>
Since the perpetrator of the crime of misuse of public power,
which may cause damages to the life and property of citizens, is
more vicious, the new codes list harsher standards for prosecution.
</P>
<P>
The 41-page regulation deals with all the crimes listed in the
new criminal code promulgated in 1997, including new names for
some crimes.
</P>
<P>
"The new codes are expected to provide China's procuratorates
with explicit and specific legal bases for combating corruption
crimes, which is key to ensure the proper enforcement of the
relevant provisions in the new penal law," Zhang said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0129 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. Africa Launches Plan to Boost Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A 180-million-rand
(30-million- dollar) plan to lure an extra three million foreign
tourists to South Africa in the next three years was unveiled in
Pretoria Thursday, South African Press Association reported.
</P>
<P>
Environmental Affairs and Tourism Minister Valli Moosa said the
 initiative was prompted by an urgency to vitalize the tourism
sector.
</P>
<P>
"In the past five years we have more than held our market
share, but to leave it to fortune and chance would open the door
to complacency," he said, adding that such an approach would spell
disaster in the competitive world of international tourism.
</P>
<P>
The initiative was expected to bring about 8.5 million tourists
to South Africa by the year 2002, compared with 5.7 million
visiting the country last year.
</P>
<P>
This would push the number of jobs created by tourist
activities from 737,000 last year to more than one million by
2002.
</P>
<P>
Moosa said the plan was the first joint tourism effort by the
government and the private sector.
</P>
<P>
"Both the private and public sectors have dug deep in their
pockets to raise the money required to fund the plan," he said.
</P>
<P>
The government and the Business Trust each gave 50 million
rands for the initiative, while the Tourism Business Council would
provide 25 million.
</P>
<P>
Another 45 million rands came from the budget of South African
Tourism (Satour). South African Airways offered 10 million.
</P>
<P>
The first focus of the plan is on short-term marketing
campaigns to boost South Africa's share of tourists from Britain,
the United States, Germany, Italy, the Netherlands and France.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
