<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tuberculosis Remains Killer in Western Pacific </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A total of 355,000 people died
of tuberculosis in 1998 in the Western Pacific region, according
to a report released here at the on-going 50th session of the
World Health Organization Regional Committee for the Western
Pacific.
</P>
<P>
The report says the incidence of tuberculosis tends to rise in
many places of the world over the past several years. In the
Western Pacific region, the reported cases of tuberculosis for
every 100,000 people increased from 18 in 1994 to 23 in 1998.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that there were 1.96 million new tuberculosis
cases in the region in 1998, according to the report.
</P>
<P>
The number of tuberculosis cases in the Western Pacific region
accounts for 29 percent of the total around the world, with 70
percent of the patients range from 15 to 49 years of fertile age.
</P>
<P>
Therefore, tuberculosis prevention and control is one of the
topics at the five-day meeting which opened on September 13.
Participants have conducted extensive exchanges on the supervision,
spread and treatment of the disease as well as the improvement of
public health systems. 
</P>
</TEXT>
