<HEADLINE> All Housing Allocations by Former Nigerian Gov't </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Nigerian government has
revoked controversial housing allocations in Lagos and Abuja by
Former Sani Abacha Administration, Information Minister Chief Dapo
Sarumi said.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting of the Federal Executive Council (FEC) presided
over by President Olusegun Obasanjo, the minister told reporters
Wednesday in Nigerian capital Abuja that all the housing
allocations were declared invalid after the council reviewed the
presentations by Works and Housing Minister Chief Tony Anenih.
</P>
<P>
Sarumi noted that the revocation was dictated by a need to
redress glaring injustices committed in the past, adding this
action was in line with Obasanjo government's efforts to recover
public funds, media reports said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the minister, the council took the decision
because it was discovered that the properties were paid with
public funds.
</P>
<P>
The plots and houses allocated in 1997 were paid with a cheque
issued to the Federal Ministry of Works from the Office of the
National Security Adviser, the minister said.
</P>
<P>
The minister stressed that "the allocation cannot be valid",
because " you allocated a plot of house to an individual and he
(or she) used money from the Central Bank of Nigeria to pay."
</P>
<P>
He noted that the most disturbing aspect of the issue was that
five people and two companies who were allocated plots in Lagos
rejected the allocation, but went round to collect the money paid
for them by the government.
</P>
<P>
The Federal Executive Council has directed the five who are all
military officers and the two companies to pay back the money
immediately, the minister added.
</P>
<P>
Among those affected by the revocation are former military
chieftains including former Chief of General Staff, former Chief
of Defence Staff and Army, Naval and Air Chiefs. 
</P>
