<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Trade Surplus Rises to 755 Million Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Philippine trade surplus, the
export-import gap, ballooned to 755 million U.S. dollars in the
first seven months as against last year's 1.4 billion dollars in
red, as weak peso continued to boost exports.
</P>
<P>
National Statistics Office (NSO) data released Thursday show
payments for imports rose slightly by less than one percent to
17.9 billion dollars while exports rose by 13.7 percent to 18.6
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
This brought the total merchandise trade for the first seven
months of 1999 to 36.5 billion dollars, up 6.7 percent from 34.3
billion dollars in 1998.
</P>
<P>
For the month of July alone, total trade reached 5.6 billion
dollars from 4.9 billion dollars the previous year.
</P>
<P>
Electronics and components remained the top import items during
the month with payments amounting to 655.4 million dollars, an
increase of 23.5 percent from 467.7 million dollars a year ago.
</P>
<P>
This was followed by mineral fuels, lubricants and related
materials earning 271.4 million dollars, up 56.4 percent from
173.5 million dollars in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
Top imports for July also include telecommunication equipment
and electrical machinery, 239.5 million dollars; industrial
machinery and equipment, 167.6 million dollars; and
materials/accessories imported on consignment basis for the
manufacture of other electrical and electronic machinery and
equipment, 131.9 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
The NSO said raw materials and intermediate goods, which
accounts for 42.4 percent of the total imports for July 1999,
grew by 23.9 percent to 1.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Expenditures for capital goods and mineral fuel and lubricants
also increased by 1.3 percent and 54.4 percent to 1 billion
dollars and 271. million dollars, respectively.
</P>
<P>
The United States and Japan remained the top sources of
Philippine imports for the month with payments reaching 574
million dollars and 531.5 million dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
