<HEADLINE> Lazio President Cragnotti Refuses to Attend Home Matches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Lazio president Sergio Cragnotti
says he will no longer attend his side's home matches in Rome's
Olympic Stadium due to an increasingly nasty dispute with the club
's hardcore supporters.
</P>
<P>
"I will not go to the stadium until I am assured that the fan
protests have ended and that these shameful attacks on me and my
family have finished," he told the Rome daily Corriere dello Sport
on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Cragnotti has been strongly criticised by fans for signing a
three-year deal with a travel agency for transport and tickets to
away games in the Champions League.
</P>
<P>
Fans representatives say the agency, which handles 70 percent
of Lazio's ticketing allocation, are charging double the cost of
travelling independently to the game.
</P>
<P>
Lazio supporters are also angry that television rights for
their Champions League games have been sold to pay-per-view
channel Telepiu, meaning even those who don't use the travel
agency and attend the matches must buy a decoder and a
subscription to the channel.
</P>
<P>
Cragnotti says he is also upset at the way protests have
included insults against members of his family.
</P>
<P>
Cragnotti has spent heavily on new players during his reign at
Lazio and under Swedish coach Sven Goran Eriksson the club have
won the Italian Cup and European Cup Winner's Cup in the past two
seasons as well as qualifying for the current Champions League.
</P>
</TEXT>
