<HEADLINE> More Calamity Loans Released in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Social Security
System (SSS) has released more than 1 billion pesos (25 million
U.S. dollars) in calamity loans to 139,874 SSS members since last
month after the floods hit Manila and other provinces in Luzon,
Philippine News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
SSS Senior Vice President Edgar Solilapsi was quoted as saying
that the calamity loans have been released to members in Manila,
Rizal, Pampanga and Pangasinan.
</P>
<P>
"Some 449,530 calamity loan applications were received by the
SSS from August 10 to September 3, the last day of filing for the
application," Solilapsi said.
</P>
<P>
 At least 177 people were killed and millions of pesos worth
of crops and property were destroyed when floods caused by
monsoon rains submerged wide areas in the towns and cities. Many
of the casualties were reported in Antipolo, where houses on the
hillside were destroyed by landslides.
</P>
<P>
Solilapsi said Metro Manila had the largest number of calamity
loan disbursements with 433.08 million pesos (10.8 million U.S.
dollars) released to 54,765 SSS members, the majority of which
were processed at the SSS Quezon City Branch.
</P>
<P>
He said that more than 9,500 members in other provinces of
Luzon were granted loans totaling 59.16 million pesos (1.48
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The government declared a state of calamity in the affected
areas. SSS launched medical missions and relief operations and
beefed up its offices to fast track processing of claims. 
</P>
</TEXT>
