<HEADLINE> Typhoon York Stills Attacks HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A total of 309 persons who
sustained storm-related injuries Thursday were treated at
hospitals, and 102 of them have already been discharged, according
to a government press release.
</P>
<P>
So far, a man who was believed to be hit by objects blown off
from strong winds died at hospital.
</P>
<P>
The Hurricane Signal No. 10, remains hoisted in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
At 3:00 Thursday afternoon, Typhoon York was centered about 50
kilometers west-southwest of the Hong Kong Observatory and is
forecast to move west-northwest at about 10 kilometers per hour
across the west coast of the Pearl River Estuary.
</P>
<P>
York, which was the most powerful typhoon attacking Hong Kong
in the past 16 years, has entered the Pearl River Estuary and
started to move away from Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
When hurricane force winds are no longer experienced in Hong
Kong, the Hong Kong Observatory will consider hoisting the No. 8
gale or storm signal to replace Signal No. 10 in the next two
hours.
</P>
<P>
The Home Affairs Department has opened 36 temporary shelters so
far and a total of 593 people are accommodated.
</P>
<P>
Water and electricity supply in general has not been disrupted
by Typhoon York. Electricity supplied by overhead lines in some
remote villages was interrupted by adverse weather.
</P>
<P>
Repair work is being arranged wherever possible.
</P>
<P>
The Mass Transit Railway is running a limited service. All
services of public buses, ferries, trams, the Light Rail Transit
and the Kowloon-Canton Railway have been suspended.
</P>
<P>
Sections of about 50 roads have been closed because of
dangerous scaffolding or fallen trees.
</P>
<P>
A total of 37 cases of flooding have been recorded. There have
been 148 reports of trees being uprooted, of which 130 are in the
New Territories and 18 in the urban areas.
</P>
<P>
All courts, schools and financial markets are closed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Clinics run by the Department of Health and the Hospital
Authority are closed, but Accident and Emergency services at
hospitals remain normal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
