<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No New Cases of Polio in Western Pacific in 2 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MACAO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- No new cases of poliomyelitis
were detected in the Western Pacific region for over two years, a
WHO official said here at the ongoing 50th Session of the World
Health Organization Regional Committee for the Western Pacific.
</P>
<P>
"This is a real credit to all member states, especially those
who have until recently suffered from the burden of poliomyelitis",
said Dr. Shigeru Omi, director of the regional committee.
</P>
<P>
The annual meeting of the regional committee is being held in
Macao from September 13 to 17 with the participation of more than
100 representatives from the region.
</P>
<P>
WHO launched a poliomyelitis eradication initiative in 1988
when the World Health Assembly, WHO's global governing body,
resolved to eradicate the disease by the end of 2000.
</P>
<P>
At its 39th session in September 1988, the Regional Committee
for the Western Pacific also adopted a resolution on the
eradication of poliomyelitis in the region.
</P>
<P>
The last polio case in the region, a 15-month-old Cambodian
girl, was identified on March 19, 1997. Since then, no new cases
of poliomyelitis have been reported.
</P>
<P>
"I can inform you that the quality of surveillance has been
maintained at the highest level throughout the region. That is why
I can be confident in saying that the transmission of wild
poliovirus has finally been interrupted," Omi said.
</P>
<P>
However, he pointed out, "This will not yet be the end of the
story for poliomyelitis eradication. Our region will have to
maintain surveillance for acute flaccid paralysis (AFP) until
global certification, in order to guard against re-introduction of
imported wild poliovirus, as long as it circulates anywhere in the
world."
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the investment in human resources that has been part
of the poliomyelitis eradication initiative, many countries have
improved their immunization coverage and strengthened their
communicable disease surveillance systems.
</P>
<P>
"Poliomyelitis is a disease of the 20th century that will no
longer trouble us in the 21st century, but the legacy of its
eradication will live on," Omi said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
