<HEADLINE> Men's Weightlifting World Records Surpassed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WEINAN, SHAANXI, China, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A 19-year-old
Chinese strongman surpassed two world records to take the men's 62-
kg weightlifting title here on Thursday at the fourth Chinese City
Games.
</P>
<P>
Shi Zhiyong of Xiamen, Fujian province, snatched up 150.5 kgs
and 152.5 kgs in his second and third attempts to surpass his own
world mark of 150 kgs set up in the World Junior Weightlifting
Championships in the United States on July 4, 1999.
</P>
<P>
The strongman later lifted 175 kgs in jerk in the third attempt
for a two-lift total of 327.5 kgs against the world record of 325
kgs, set up by the International Weightlifting Federation after
the reshuffle of the categories.
</P>
<P>
"I just hope to win the gold medal in the 2000 Olympic Games,
and to improve my skills to lift a two-lift total of 330 kgs,"
said the young strongman.
</P>
<P>
"I'm from a poor family," said Shi, who has a younger sister in
a worker's family, "I hope to win more gold medals in the world
arena to make changes to the life of my parents." 
