<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Too Many Phone Calls Feared to Hinder Y2K Transition </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine National
Telecommunication Commission (NTC) is urging the public to refrain
from making unnecessary telephone calls during the Y2K transition
period to avoid overloading the telecommunications network.
</P>
<P>
Nestor Dacanay, NTC representative in a forum on Y2k readiness
held here Thursday morning, said telecommunications networks might
be overloaded during the computer date-change period.
</P>
<P>
This may happen, Dacanay said, "when people might be impelled
to use the telephones simultaneously out of curiosity or to seek
assurances of safety, comfort and peace during the transition
period."
</P>
<P>
Should an overload occur, Dacanay said, the telecommunication
firms will implement call-dropping. "If it becomes absolutely
necessary, the networks will drop calls to prevent an overload,"
he explained.
</P>
<P>
"This means the telephone firm will deliberately drop your
call, that is, not process it so that you are not able to get
connected to the number you dialed," he explained.
</P>
<P>
Dacanay asked the public to refrain from making unnecessary
phone calls during the last few days of December 1999 up to the
first week of January 2000, the rollover period of the computer
glitch called the Y2K bug.
</P>
<P>
The Y2K bug, also called the millennium bug, is a weakness in
old-model computer systems which cannot read or recognize the
numbers 2000 since their microchip processors were programmed to
read only up to 1999.
</P>
<P>
Dacanay, however, said the country's telecommunications
computer networks are "l00 percent Y2K compliant" as of August 30,
l999.
</P>
<P>
"The telecommunications sector is in its highest state of Y2K
readiness. Almost all telephone carriers are Y2K ready," he
assured, citing as examples telephone giant Philippine Long
Distance Telephone Company, Globe Telecoms, Smart Communications,
Islacom and Extelcom.
</P>
<P>
Others, like Bayantel, are fast-tracking their remediation
efforts to be Y2K compliant before the end of October 1999, he
added.
</P>
<P>
The provincial telecommunications sector has, up to this date,
only 13,000 lines which are not yet Y2K compliant, a small number
when taken in the context of 5 million lines nationwide, Dacanay
pointed out.
</P>
<P>
He further assured of continued and uninterrupted telephone
service during the Y2K rollover period under normal usage and
operations.
</P>
<P>
Barring an abnormal hike in the number of calls,
telecommunications service will remain available even during
possible power or energy interruptions because all
telecommunication service providers have their own back-up power
supply, Dacanay said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0160 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
