<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0164 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Nepal-Bhutan Talks Made Some Progress </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KATHMANDU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The three-day Nepal-Bhutan
Joint Ministerial Level Committee (JMLC) meeting on the Bhutanese
refugee crisis produced no resolution, though it made some
positive progress, said Nepali Foreign Minister Ram Mahat after
the talks ended here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Mahat told reporters that the positive progress is that Bhutan
made concessions on the categorization of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
He said that Bhutan agreed to treat refugees of category 2 in
the same terms as category one.
</P>
<P>
The Bhutanese refugees were divided into four categories in the
first round of ministerial talks between Nepal and Bhutan in 1993.
The four categories are: bonafide Bhutanese who were forcibly
evicted, Bhutanese who emigrated on compelling circumstance,
non-Bhutanese and Bhutanese with criminal records.
</P>
<P>
The second category of refugees has been the obstacle in the
previous talks. Bhutan had refused to take back these refugees.
</P>
<P>
"The other positive side is that they also agreed to go ahead
with free verification, but we had different opinions as to what
should be free verification," said Mahat.
</P>
<P>
"We want to go on a camp-by-camp basis," he said, adding that
Bhutan wanted to verify some part of the refugees.
</P>
<P>
Mahat said they had left this difference at the talks in Bhutan
that will come very soon.
</P>
<P>
The talks will be continued in Thimpu in November, he said.
</P>
<P>
Bhutan Foreign Minister Jigme Y. Thinley said after the talks
that they had achieved substantial results.
</P>
<P>
"We have a mechanism (on verification) in place, which
comprises five members from each side, and will conduct the
verification on the form that had already been agreed upon," he
said.
</P>
<P>
There are 100,000 Bhutanese refugees living in eastern Nepal
after they were evicted from Bhutan around 1990. Seven rounds of
ministerial talks between the two Himalayan kingdoms failed to
reach any solutions.
</P>
<P>
The 7th JMLC meeting held in Kathmandu in 1996 ended in impasse
as Nepal insisted on the repatriation of all refugees, while
Bhutan wanted to take back only those who were forcibly evicted,
mainly the first category of refugees. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
