<BODY>
<HEADLINE> PECC Sets Up Eco-Friendly Residential Area in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Pacific Economic
Cooperation Council recently displayed an eco-friendly residential
area in north China's Tianjin Municipality during its first
International Trade and Investment Fair in the city.
</P>
<P>
The theme of the four-day fair, which started Tuesday, is "
Environment and Living Space in the 21st Century." The
residential area, built in the Tianjin Economic Development Area,
is a combination of Eastern and Western architectural styles with
25 completed single buildings and 18 varieties of outstanding
apartments open to the fair's visitors.
</P>
<P>
The 200,000-square-meter residential area, built by architects
from 18 countries and regions including the USA, Australia, Japan,
Holland, the Philippines, New Zealand, Britain, Hong Kong and
Taiwan, are furnished with hi-tech, energy-saving, and eco-
friendly household electrical appliances and materials.
</P>
<P>
Officials with the Ministry of Construction said they have
approved the area as a base to publicize real estate with new
technology and style in order to inspire enterprises both at home
and abroad to develop apartments and houses suitable for China's
economic development.
</P>
<P>
Altogether, 355 enterprises from 28 countries and regions are
attending the fair, among which are many well-known eco-friendly
apartment developers.
</P>
<P>
They will negotiate on some 272 cooperative projects, and there
will be seminars on investment and markets, water-pollution
prevention, and the environment and habitats.
</P>
<P>
The PECC, established in Australia in September 1980, now has
23 member states providing consultation and negotiation on
economic cooperation and development in the Pacific region. China
became a member of the council in September 1986. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
