<HEADLINE> Australia to Spend Hundreds of Millions on E.Timor Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Australia's participation in
the security force in East Timor would cost several hundred
million Australian dollars, Defense Minister John Moore said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"As to the precise amount, it is pretty hard to estimate,"
Moore told reporters. "But, certainly the cost will run to some
hundreds of millions."
</P>
<P>
Asked about reports it would cost Australia between 300 million
Australian dollars (198 million U.S. dollars) and 400 million
Australian dollars (264 million U.S. dollars) to get underway, he
said: "That wouldn't be unrealistic."
</P>
<P>
His comments came after Treasurer Peter Costello said
Australia's involvement would have significant cost to the budget.
</P>
<P>
"It will take new expenditure," Costello said in Melbourne.
</P>
<P>
The budget was in surplus and it was the government's aim to
keep it in surplus, Costello said.
</P>
<P>
"It will mean spending will have to be tightened in other
areas," Costello added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
