<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Red Cross Leaders Meet in Malaysia to Discuss Aid to East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Leaders of ASEAN Red
Cross and Red Crescent Societies met here Thursday at their 10th
conference to discuss urgent humanitarian aid to East Timor
refugees.
</P>
<P>
Malaysian Red Crescent Society Chairman Abdul Hamid Omar told
reporters that Indonesian Red Cross Secretary-General Soesanto
Mangoensadjito would brief the meeting on the latest situation in
violence-torn East Timor and the type of aid needed.
</P>
<P>
"On behalf of Malaysia and in the ASEAN spirit, we are ready to
assist in whatever way we can," Hamid said. "Time is important. We
can't wait that long to extend relief aid for fear that the
situation in East Timor will deteriorate."
</P>
<P>
East Timor badly needed supply of blood, respiratory equipment
and medication for skin diseases, Soesanto said, adding a fire
three months ago destroyed a blood bank in Jakarta where 500,000
pints of blood were stored.
</P>
<P>
"We highly appreciate the cooperation and humanitarian aid
extended by neighboring countries to alleviate the human problems
in East Timor," he said.
</P>
<P>
A total of 37 Red Cross and Red Crescent leaders from the 10
ASEAN member countries are attending the three-day conference.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN groups Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos, Malaysia,
Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
