<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cambodia to Have Good Wet-Season Rice Crop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHNOM PENH, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Cambodia's wet-season rice
crop this year is expected to exceed 3 million tons, more than
last year's, according to the forecast of the Agriculture
Ministry.
</P>
<P>
A ministry official said Thursday that if the rain is good
until the end of the wet season it could yield a good rice crop
and with many thousand tons of surplus.
</P>
<P>
Cambodia produced more than 3 million tons of rice in 1998,
with more than 2.8 million tons harvested in the wet season.
</P>
<P>
The forecast is based on this year's minimal damage so far to
the country's wet season rice crop from flooding, drought and
insects. Cambodia's wet season begins from May to November every
year.
</P>
<P>
Flood and drought have damaged about 12,000 hectares of paddies
since May, the Cambodia Daily said, but only 81 hectares of
paddies have been damaged by hopper-grass and caterpillars in
Kompong Cham province, compared to thousands of hectares of
paddies destroyed in Takeo, Kompong Speu and Kompong Cham in 1998.
</P>
<P>
With the good crop prospects, the Cambodian government will not
ban the export of rice this year. More than that it will seek to
find overseas markets for the surplus. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Nigerian First Family Warned Over Allegedly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian authorities have
warned wife and son of the late Head of State Sani Abacha against
sabotaging government's efforts to recover public funds allegedly
stashed in foreign banks by the family.
</P>
<P>
The Vanguard, a leading Nigerian newspaper, reported Thursday
that Mrs. Abacha and her son Mohammed Abacha were summoned Tuesday
to the capital Abuja by the Office of the Chief Security Adviser
to the President, where they were interrogated and released after
some hours.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a presidency source as saying that Mrs. Abacha
had indeed attempted to fly out of the country last weekend but
was stopped by security agents acting on "instruction from above".
</P>
<P>
The two key figures of the former first family were barred from
 travelling abroad until the recovery of the looted money.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted sources as saying that government was aware of
alleged plans of the Abacha family to cause public disaffection
through riots and protests.
</P>
<P>
"The government is quite aware of the fundamental rights of its
citizens but will not allow any act by any individual that will
disturb the public peace, " the sources said.
</P>
<P>
The Abachas began contacting some powerful individuals in and
outside the country to plead their case with government as soon as
they received the summon to report at Aso Rock, Nigeria's
president villa, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Abacha is back in Kano, where her family is located, from
Abuja after giving an undertaking to be law-abiding.
</P>
<P>
National Security Adviser Lt.-Gen. Aliyu Mohammed recently
traveled to Europe to recover some of the money allegedly hidden
in foreign banks by the Abachas and aides to the late head of
state. 
</P>
</TEXT>
