<HEADLINE> Algerians Begin Voting in Referendum on National Reconciliation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Some 17.5 million Algerian
voters began to vote Thursday morning on a law seeking national
reconciliation after seven years of violence killed more than 100,
000 people, said reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
The government has mobilized 400,000 agents to ensure the
smooth process of the voting, the result of which will be
announced on Friday.
</P>
<P>
President Abdelaziz Bouteflika has appealed to Algerians to
vote for his "civil concord" law aimed at giving clemency to all
Islamists except those who have enrolled in killing or raping.
</P>
<P>
At a cabinet meeting on Wednesday, Bouteflika said that this "
demarche of peace" is the only way to let Algeria go out of the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Widely expected to be approved, the civil concord law is valid
for six months until January 13 for Islamists who want to benefit
for the clemency measures.
</P>
<P>
So far, about 300 armed Islamists have surrendered to the
government, said Algerian Prime Minister Smail Hamdani.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the French daily Liberation, the number
three of the outlawed Islamic Salvation Front, Abdelkader Hachani,
said that the government should first of all make clear the
responsibility of everybody in the seven-year violence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
