<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East countries.
</P>
<P>
ANKARA -- The International Monetary Fund (IMF) has decided to
provide an emergency loan of 330 million U.S. dollars for repair
of earthquake damage in Turkey, local Daily News reported here
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Following a visit to the earthquake-stricken region in Turkey,
IMF official Carlo Cotarelli maintained that they were trying to
increase the amount of relief fund to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- An international conference on the banking
strategies of the 21st century will be held in Abu Dhabi, the
capital of the United Arab Emirates (UAE), from October 18-20, the
Gulf News daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
More than 400 bankers from the UAE and worldwide will take
part in the conference, which will discuss such topics as
regional challenges faced by the banking sector, finance in the
age of globalization, developments of the stock exchange markets
and information technology.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Gulf Beauty '99, an international trade fair for
perfumes, cosmetics and personal care products, will be held in
Dubai, the United Arab Emirates, from September 20 to 23.
</P>
<P>
According to organizers of the event, more than 170
participants from 22 countries will showcase their latest products
at the exhibition, local media reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The German pavilion will have 30 manufactures represented.
German cosmetics exports to the Gulf markets reached 96 million
U.S. dollars in 1998, the organizers said.
</P>
<P>
Other big participants will include the United States, France,
Italy, Spain and Thailand.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Middle East Optical and Ophthalmic Exhibition,
to be held in Dubai, the United Arab Emirates, from February 10
to 13, 2000, is drawing participants from across the world, the
Khaleej Times daily reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Exhibitors from the Netherlands, Switzerland, France, Austria,
Italy, China, Britain, Singapore and other countries will be
taking part in the biennial event which has been recognized by
the optical industry as its most significant showcase in the
Middle East, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will feature the latest in eyewear, eye care,
optical aids and accessories and cater to a fast-growing demand
for optical products in the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 edition of the exhibition drew more than 125
companies from 24 countries with business worth 5 million
U.S. dollars concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
