<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AIDS Becomes Top Killer to African Youths </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- AIDS has become the top killer
to the youths in Sub-Saharan Africa, a new study revealed.
</P>
<P>
The study, made available here thursday, said it is estimated
that about seven million young people aged between 15 and 24 in
Sub-Saharan Africa were infected with HIV or had developed AIDS by
the end of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The report said nearly three million young people aged 15-24 in
the world were infected with HIV in 1998, and nearly two million
of them live in Africa.
</P>
<P>
It said among 14 million people who have died of AIDS to date,
three million were African children.
</P>
<P>
The top nine of 10 countries listed with the most number of
HIV- infected children are all in Sub-Saharan Africa.
</P>
<P>
"The countries range from Ethiopia in the first position with
an estimated 140,000 HIV-infected children, through Nigeria with
99,000, South Africa, Tanzania, Uganda, Kenya, Zimbabwe and
Mozambique, to the Democratic Republic of the Congo with 49,000
infected children," said the report.
</P>
<P>
The report was contained in a paper titled "Listen, Learn,
Live" presented at the on-going 11th International Conference on
AIDS and STDs (sexually transmitted diseases) in Africa in Lusaka,
Zambia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
