<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient "Underground Treasure House" Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China hailed another momentous
event in its archeological history by announcing today the
excavation of a large "underground treasure house" some 20
kilometers north of the ancient city of Xi'an, capital of
northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
A decade-long excavation has revealed that the "underground
treasure house" is actually the burial site, known as Yangling, of
Liu Qi, the fourth emperor of the Western Han Dynasty (206 B.C.-
24 A.D.).
</P>
<P>
The many pits associated with the emperor's tomb contain large
quantities of colored pottery animals as well as terra-cotta
warriors and horses.
</P>
<P>
"This is the largest collection of pottery animals ever
unearthed since the founding of new China in 1949," said Zhao
Dequan, vice governor of Shaanxi, at a press conference here today.
</P>
<P>
Unlike the serious demeanor of the terra-cotta warriors and
horses found at the tomb of Qin Shihuang, the first emperor of the
Qin Dynasty (221-207 B.C.), the pottery at Yangling are lovely
small animals including meek lambs, naive pigs and long-eared
wolfhounds.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, 90 burial pits have been found in the 12-
square-kilometer rectangular cemetery dominated by the emperor's
tomb.
</P>
<P>
On the eastern side of the cemetery are 28 pits containing
terra-cotta sheep, dogs, pigs and colored terra-cotta infantrymen,
cavalrymen, chariots and horses.
</P>
<P>
The 21 pits along both the northern and western sides contain
large numbers of articles for daily use, as well as cavalrywomen,
something that has never before been found. Excavations will
continue in the 20 pits on the southern side of the site to
determine what is in them.
</P>
<P>
In addition, archeologists have discovered 10,000 burial pits
in a 3.5-square-kilometer attendant cemetery one kilometer east of
Liu Qi's tomb. Over 5,000 cultural relics have been unearthed
from 280 pits there, said Jiao Nanfeng, leader of the
archeological team.
</P>
<P>
Other brilliant achievements of the excavation include the
discovery of China's earliest chessboard and the largest tile made
in the Han Dynasty at the ruins of Sanchu Gate, a gate-tower
symbolizing the imperial ranks, he said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese experts describe the current discovery at Yangling as
the country's most comprehensive excavation of an imperial tomb
built in the Han Dynasty. It not only has high academic value, but
also will be easily turned into a new tourist resort.
</P>
<P>
An exhibition displaying the treasures unearthed at the
Yangling Tomb will be opened to visitors at the end of this month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
