<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt Urges Israel to Renounce Nuclear Weapons </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak has reiterated a call on Israel to renounce nuclear
weapons, the Egyptian Gazette newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The nuclear acquisition and capabilities would not stand Israel
in good stead, Mubarak said on Wednesday in an interview with The
Armed Forces newspaper.
</P>
<P>
"I think all the countries in the world have the conviction
that Israel must get rid of its nuclear weaponry if it really
wishes to live in security and peace, and is keen on maintaining
regional stability," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Israel is widely believed to have developed nuclear weapons.
But it has neither confirmed nor denied the allegation, and
refused to sign the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT).
</P>
<P>
Egypt signed a peace treaty with Israel in 1979, becoming the
first Arab country to do so. However, over the years a wall of
mistrust still remained between the two neighbors, with each
expressing concern over the other's purchase of advanced weapons.
</P>
<P>
"Why do Israelis talk about Egypt's military power and do not
talk about the development of their defense?" Mubarak asked.
</P>
<P>
He conditioned Egypt's signing of a ban on chemical weapons on
Israel's signing of NPT.
</P>
<P>
Egypt will continue to develop and modernize its armed forces,
but it has no intention to be engaged in an arms race with any
other country, Mubarak said.
</P>
<P>
"Egypt is a great country that keeps its obligations and
complies with its pacts but at the same time it is capable of
protecting itself," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
