<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia: ASEAN Should Play Role in Resolving E. Timor Conflict </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations (UN)
action in asking Australia to head the peacekeeping force in East
Timor is not a good development, Malaysian Foreign Minister Syed
Hamid Albar said.
</P>
<P>
The ASEAN countries should be given preference to play a role
in resolving the dispute and conflict in East Timor as Indonesia
was a member of the regional body, Syed Hamid said in the southern
city of Johor Baharu Wednesday night, Bernama news agency reported
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia felt that Australia had been hasty in offering itself
to head the multinational force to be sent to East Timor, he said
when asked to comment on reports that UN Secretary-General Kofi
Annan had asked Australia to head the peacekeeping force in East
Timor despite objections from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Syed Hamid said any contingent joining the peacekeeping force
should have the confidence of all parties including the people of
East Timor itself.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia, as an ASEAN member, should also be careful if
Australia headed the multinational force as it feared many
problems would have to be faced including rejection by the local
people.
</P>
<P>
"The important thing is...we have to instill confidence... that
the countries involved in the peacekeeping force are stable
countries and not one-sided and at the same time able to
discharge their duties and responsibilities well," the foreign
minister was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He said Malaysia, nevertheless, was ready to send its
peacekeeping force under the auspices of the UN and was waiting
further instructions from the world body.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia would also give humanitarian aid to the people of East
Timor, Syed Hamid said, adding the form and method, however, had
not been decided yet. 
</P>
</TEXT>
