<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: CPC Meeting to Design Future of State-Owned Sector ( 1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China's state-owned
enterprises (SOEs) will soon have clear directions as to what they
should do, and there is every indication that the 4th Plenary
Session of the 15th Central Committee of the Communist Party of
China will work out solutions to issues critical to the fate of
SOEs.
</P>
<P>
Included in the package to be formulated at the meeting are
measures for streamlining the state sector and steering them
toward more a market orientation.
</P>
<P>
Observers in Beijing say that the meeting, which will open on
Sunday, will have a far-reaching impact on the development of
China's state-owned sector in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Holding the meeting on the eve of the 50th birthday of the
People's Republic fully demonstrates the CPC Central Committee's
high attention to the reform and development of state-owned
enterprises. Authoritative analysts predict that a range of
strategic decisions will be formulated to promote the reform of
SOEs.
</P>
<P>
General Secretary of CPC Central Committee Jiang Zemin has made
quite a number of inspection tours this year, and chaired five
forums in different areas especially on SOE reform and development,
a move rarely seen before.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of the state-owned economy in the national
economy determines the significance of SOE reforms. Among the
urban employed population, 60 percent are in the state-owned
sector, while 55 percent of state financial revenues come from
SOEs.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jiang Zemin's New Zealand Tour Successful, FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Foreign Ministry spokesman
