</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: CPC Meeting to Design Future of State-Owned Sector ( 2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
One thing is clear, people expecting overall privatization in
China will continue to be disappointed. The dominating status of
the publicly owned economy is protected by the national
constitution, and it is a critical tool by which the central
government drives and regulates economic and social development.
</P>
<P>
Only a month ago, President Jiang Zemin reiterated a month ago
that China "will never practice privatization. This is a major
principle that allows not a bit wavering."
</P>
<P>
Under this principle, China's reform has always been pursued in
a pragmatic way. Since the early 1980s, SOE reforms have
experienced step-by-step progress, from delegating power and
allowing enterprises to retain more profits to contracted
operations. In the 1990s, SOE reforms advanced into a new stage of
system remolding.
</P>
<P>
The deepening of reforms has uncovered many problems
accumulated from the past. Some SOEs failed to adapt to the rules
of a market economy and are trapped in difficulties, while some
others are suffering from either obsolete technologies or
irrational structures and heavy debt pressures.
</P>
<P>
These difficulties have not forced the Chinese to bow. Rather,
sober-minded policy makers recognized that SOE reform is the key
knot that must be untied for successful economic system reform,
hence the goal of freeing most large- and medium-sized SOEs from
difficulties in three years time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: CPC Meeting to Design Future of State-Owned Sector ( 3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Over the past two years, the central government held high the
policy of encouraging corporate mergers, standardizing bankruptcy
procedures, diverting laid-off workers, and increasing efficiency
by downsizing staff, in order to produce a competitive mechanism
that selects the superior and eliminates the inferior.
</P>
<P>
Thanks to the state's policies of stimulating domestic demand,
the overall condition of SOEs began to turn for the better in the
first half this year, with the rate of growth accelerated and
profits nearly doubled.
</P>
<P>
After years of theoretical study and practical research, a
blueprint has taken shape for the state-owned sector to develop
under market conditions. Chinese officials and economists
generally hold that it is a must for SOEs to establish a modern
enterprise system that is suited to market mechanisms in an all-
round way.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, they asserted that this is the time to put an
end to the malady of managing enterprises directly by the
government. The ongoing government restructuring is expected to
result in a genuine separation of government functions from
business operations.
</P>
<P>
Specific research of the problems faced by SOEs is also
progressing. Two weeks ago, Beijing saw the first case of
converting bank credit rights to equity in an SOE, a practice
believed to effectively cut enterprise debt burden.
</P>
<P>
In some places, the system of yearly payment for enterprise
managers or the practice of offering them share options are also
on trial. Managers of SOEs will be paid much more than their old
salary if they can make the enterprises profitable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> News Analysis: CPC Meeting to Design Future of State-Owned Sector ( 4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Authoritative analysts point out that when these trials prove
successful, they will certainly be widely spread in the near
future.
</P>
<P>
They hold that the strategic readjustment of the national
economy and strategic restructuring of SOEs will comprise the
major part of China's economic reform and development for years to
come.
</P>
<P>
Since the 15th National Congress of the CPC in 1997, it has
become a common view that the over-extended state-owned sector
must be compressed. The green light will still be given to
industries and areas that are critical to the lifeline of national
economy, while enterprises suffering from overproduction, low
efficiency, and waste will inevitably be annexed or eliminated.
</P>
<P>
How to give full play to human resources is another urgent
issue that needs resolution. To ensure the healthy development of
the national economy in the next century, China needs large
numbers of high-quality management personnel. Technological
innovation and high-tech industrial development are also critical
for raising China's comprehensive national strength.
</P>
<P>
In fact, policy makers have had unprecedented insight in these
respects, which is evidenced by the national technological
innovation conference held last month, and a range of other
related measures.
</P>
<P>
It should be noted that the Chinese people do not expect SOE
reforms to be accomplished in a limited time. While stressing the
importance and urgency of SOE reforms, Jiang Zemin reminded people
that they should "know the long-lasting and hard nature of the
work."
</P>
<P>
Through having witnessed the great changes in China over the
past 20 years, people have every reason to believe in the country'
s determination, confidence, and capability in creating new
conditions for SOEs through reforms and development.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Multi-National Force Consists of 7,000-12,000: Indonesian FM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
multi-national force in East Timor would consist of 7,000 to
12,000 personnel and be led by an Australian commander and a
Malaysian as deputy commander, Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali
Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
"The first contingent of the force would be deployed in East
Timor at the latest as of next Monday (September 20). Aside from
the Australian contingent, the first batch of the force would also
consist of three to four ASEAN (Association of Southeast Asian
Nations) countries, including Malaysia and the Philippines," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Talking to Antara News Agency reporters in New York on
Wednesday night, Alatas said although Indonesia does not impose
any conditions on the composition for the multi-national force,
Indonesia prefers ASEAN contingents over an Australian one.
</P>
<P>
This is because there are some problems with Australia which
are seen by some camps in Indonesia as too eager and provocative,
he said.
</P>
<P>
The minister said based on the U.N. experience and tradition,
usually the commander is selected from the country with the
biggest contribution of personnel, equipment and finance.
</P>
<P>
This is the reason the U.N. selected Australia to lead the
multi-national force, as it is the most ready in any aspect.
</P>
<P>
Among the nations having expressed readiness to deploy their
forces are Malaysia, the Philippines, Thailand, South Korea,
Britain and some European and African countries.
</P>
<P>
According to Alatas, Australia is not the only nation that can
lead the multi-national force, but as other countries are facing
financial problems in the deployment, thus Australia was chosen as
the commander.
</P>
<P>
And as this is different from the traditional peace-keeping
force which is financed by the U.N., the multi-national force
would be financed by those involved in the operation, Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
This multi-national force has a wide mandate, including using
weapons to restore peace. The force is also given mandate to use
all efforts needed to implement its mandate, including killing the
pro-integration militia, he added.
</P>
<P>
Alatas said the deployment of the multi-national force does not
mean the Indonesian Military (TNI) would be withdrawn from the
territory. Now, a discussion is going on about how the
8,000-member TNI would take part in the operation.
</P>
<P>
There is a big possibility that TNI will function as liaison
officers, as the task of restoring peace and order would be taken
by the multi-national force. TNI is now only supporting, and not
the operational organizer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
