<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Takes Lead in Fishing Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Years ago, fish was still a
luxury to most Chinese citizens. Nowadays, aquatic products have
become bread and butter on most dining tables.
</P>
<P>
China has lead the world's fishing industry for ten years in a
row, and its per capita fish production has exceeded the world's
average since 1995.
</P>
<P>
As a result, the Chinese market now abounds in aquatic products
of every kind.
</P>
<P>
Figures from the National Bureau of Statistics show that the
country turned out 39 million tons of aquatic products in 1998, 75
times the 1949 figure.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the Bureau of Fisheries under the Ministry of
Agriculture attribute this substantial increase to the rapid
growth of aquiculture.
</P>
<P>
Over the past fifty years, China has expanded its aquiculture
from coastal regions and regions along the major rivers including
the Yangtze and the Pearl, to the inland areas.
</P>
<P>
Areas for aquiculture in China amounted to 6.07 million ha. in
1998 with per hectare output hitting 3,600 kg, up from 1,077 kg in
1952.
</P>
<P>
Also, the total breeding output of aquatic products has
increased from 400,000 tons in 1952 to 21.8 million tons in 1998,
making China the only country whose breeding industry outstrips
its fishing industry among major fishing nations.
</P>
<P>
China's fishing output stands at 17.3 million tons at present,
9.4 times the 1954 figure.
</P>
<P>
However, in a bid to protect marine resources, the Chinese
government initiated a summer fishing ban in the East China Sea
and the Yellow Sea in 1995. This year, the ban was extended to the
South China Sea with the goal of freezing the growth of the
country's offshore fishing output.
</P>
<P>
Latest statistics show that the fishing ban has paid off as
China's offshore fishing output declined by 220,000 tons in the
first half of this year compared with the same period last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
