<HEADLINE> Chinese Enterprises Pioneering: Japanese Giant Auto Manufacturer (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Japanese auto giant Honda
says it is impressed with the pioneering spirit the Chinese have
shown during cooperative business deals.
</P>
<P>
"After several years of cooperation, the open-minded and career-
minded Chinese people have made a deep impression on us," Kadowaki
Koji, general manager of Guangzhou Honda Automobile Co. Ltd., said
in an exclusive interview with Xinhua.
</P>
<P>
"Honda is full of confidence for the future cooperation with
the Chinese partners," Kadowaki said.
</P>
<P>
After its success in motorcycle manufacturing in Guangzhou,
Honda invested in the production of a popular style car there.
</P>
<P>
Honda started its cooperation with the Chinese in the 1970s,
after attending the China export commodity fair held annually in
Guangzhou.
</P>
<P>
In the 1980s, a joint venture was established for making
motorcycles. However, the auto industries in Guangzhou were
granted bank loans of only three million yuan (361,000 U.S.
dollars) a year and lacked professional management or skilled
workers.
</P>
<P>
Honda, a leading automobile manufacturer in the world, worried
about the quality of products here, Kadowaki said.
</P>
<P>
Honda's first involvement with Chinese automakers was in the
introduction of technology only. In 1987, Honda sent two samples
and some key fittings to the Guangzhou auto plant which Guangzhou
workers copied.
</P>
</TEXT>
