<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda Probes Kisangani Clash with Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
KAMPALA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's Army High Command
has formed a new inquiry team to investigate the causes of August
14-17 armed clashes between Ugandan and Rwandan troops in
Kisangani in the Democratic Republic of the Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
The new committee, composed of five members and chaired by
State Minister for Defense Steven Kavuma, began work Tuesday, one
day after the High Command rejected the report presented at the
weekend by Army Commander Jeje Odongo, the New Vision newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The committee also includes State Minister for Regional
Cooperation Amama Mbabazi, former State Minister for Defense David
Tinyefuza, Deputy Chief of Military Intelligence Noble Mayombo and
President Yoweri Museveni' s principal Private Secretary in charge
of the military James Mugiira.
</P>
<P>
The new inquiry team was given the task to study the previous
report and establish whether the report was genuine and to address
all areas of complaints.
</P>
<P>
The High Command meeting on Monday chaired by President
Museveni expressed disappointment with the report, describing it
as shallow and compromised.
</P>
<P>
The Odongo report, compiled jointly with a Rwandan team,
accuses Uganda of provoking the shoot-out in which hundreds of
people including soldiers from both sides were killed.
</P>
<P>
A joint investigation team was formed two days after President
Museveni and Rwandan Vice President Paul Kagame met on August 17
in western Uganda over the clashes.
</P>
<P>
The contents of the Odongo report are still kept secret in
Kampala while Paul Kagame promised to publish the report when he
addresses the Rwandan Parliament Thursday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
