<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Electric Appliance Exports to Grow 10 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua)-- Exports of major household
electrical appliances increased remarkably in the first half this
year, laying a solid foundation for achieving the goal for the
entire year.
</P>
<P>
The sector is targeted to earn 3.9 billion U.S. dollars in
exports this year, which would be up 10 percent from 1998.
</P>
<P>
Sources at the State Administration of Light Industry said
that from January to June, household air conditioners brought in
280 million U.S. dollars in export revenue, a 56 percent growth
over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Exports of microwave ovens, electric pans, and refrigerators
also saw an 30 percent increase, according to the source.
</P>
<P>
Currently, China is the third-largest household electrical
appliance market in the world, with sales here accounting for 10
percent of the world's total. Almost 90 percent of the country's
exports in this category went to North American, Asia, and Europe.
</P>
<P>
Liu Fuzhong, an official with China's Household Electric
Appliance Association, said that the sector is undergoing major
restructuring with the focus on technological renovation.
</P>
<P>
Domestic enterprises have increased technological input from 3
percent two years ago to 8 percent at present, he said.
</P>
<P>
China recently announced more incentives, such as bank loans,
to encourage domestic enterprises to set up factories and sales
outlets abroad.
</P>
<P>
The Chunlan Group and the Haier Group, China's two major air
conditioner and refrigerator providers, signed deals with Russia
and the United States early this year, and their overseas
factories are now under construction.
</P>
<P>
Global household electric appliance sales are growing by 6
percent annually, and total sales will exceed 250 billion yuan (
about 30.22 billion U.S. dollars) by the end of this year, experts
predict.  
</P>
</TEXT>
