<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feathered Galloping Dinosaur, Ancestor of Bird (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A fossil recently discovered
in China indicates that a kind of feathered, meat-eating dinosaur,
adept at running, may be the ancestor of birds.
</P>
<P>
In today's British authoritative academic journal "Nature,"
Chinese paleontologist Xu Xing and his colleagues published their
recent discovery of a fossilized feathered dinosaur, called
Sinornithosaurus, which may date back 124.6 million years.
</P>
<P>
"Without doubt, it was a dinosaur, not a bird. But compared
with other feathered dinosaurs discovered in recent years, the
Sinornithosaurus has a closer connection with birds," Xu Xing, 30,
with the Chinese Academy of Sciences' Institute of Vertebrate
Paleontology and Paleoanthropology, told Xinhua here today.
</P>
<P>
Unearthed in Beipiao City in northeast China's Liaoning
Province, the fossilized dinosaur belonged to the dromaeosaurid
family, and the skeletal structure of the 1.2-meter-long dinosaur
has many characteristics of early birds.
</P>
<P>
"Its shoulder girdle is the same as the archaeopteryx, the
earliest bird discovered in Germany," Xu said.
</P>
<P>
"Although Sinornithosaurus could not fly, its bone structure
was adapted to flying, and its forelimbs could flap in both sides
of the body, a prerequisite for flight," said Xu.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of the Sinornithosaurus' body to its quarters
indicates that it could run fast, according to Xu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
