<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feathered Galloping Dinosaur, Ancestor of Bird (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The meat-eating dinosaur lived on small mammals and lizards.
When some dinosaurs were running to catch quarries, their
forelimbs flapped to increase the speed, and then evolved for
flight, some paleontologists conjecture.
</P>
<P>
United States scientist Philip Burgers has calculated that the
archaeopteryx could run at a speed of seven meters per second by
flapping their forelimbs, exceeding the lowest speed required for
flight, six meters per second.
</P>
<P>
"Another conclusion of our research is that feathers are not
unique to birds. The development of feathers was earlier than the
origin of birds," said Xu.
</P>
<P>
So far, scientists have found five kinds of feathered-dinosaur
fossils in the western region of Liaoning Province, and these
fossils represent different stages in the evolution from dinosaur
to bird, according to Xu.
</P>
<P>
Another paleontologist, Zhang Fucheng, also of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences, said a larger number of academics worldwide
now favor the view that birds originated from dinosaurs.
</P>
<P>
"But the evolution of life is a complicated procedure, and a
definitive conclusion requires more evidence," said Zhang.
</P>
<P>
The "feathered dinosaur" has become a hot topic in
international scientific circles. This year, scientists at the
Chinese Academy of Sciences' Institute of Vertebrate Paleontology
and Paleoanthropology have published four articles about feathered
dinosaur in the journal "Nature". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
