<HEADLINE> Microsoft to Buy Visio Corp for 1.3 Billion U.S. Dollars </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Microsoft Corp. said
Wednesday that it agreed to buy Visio Corp., a maker of technical
drawing software, for 1.3 billion U.S. dollars in stock.
</P>
<P>
The purchase will help Microsoft strengthen its grip on the
market for business productivity software, already dominated by
its Office suite of work processing, spreadsheet and presentation
products.
</P>
<P>
"There are very few areas Microsoft is not a player in. This is
one of them," said Frank Catalano, an industry analyst in Renton,
Washington.
</P>
<P>
Visio, founded in 1990, says its technical drawing software is
used by 3 million customers and posted 166 million U.S. dollars in
sales last year.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Seattle-based Visio will become a division
within Microsoft's business productivity group, which includes the
Office suite of products, the software giant's biggest and most
profitable business line.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft senior vice president Bob Muglia said the company
planned to continue offering the recently released Visio 2000 line
of products as a "separate but complementary" addition to the
Office programs.
</P>
<P>
Analysts said they expected some of Visio's diagramming and
drawing programs to be eventually integrated into the Office suite.
</P>
<P>
Microsoft chose to acquire Visio rather than develop similar
software in-house because Visio has a well-known product with
loyal customers, said Microsoft senior vice president Bob Muglia.
</P>
<P>
The deal, which is expected to close by mid-December at the
earliest, will add "very modestly" to Microsoft earnings
immediately and more over the long term as the business grows,
Microsoft Chief Financial Officer Greg Maffei said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
