<HEADLINE> Indonesia Abrogates Security Agreement With Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government has
decided to abrogate the security agreement with Australia, signed
on December 18, 1995, Coordinating Minister for Political and
Security Affairs Feisal Tanjung announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"The Indonesian government deeply regrets Australia's attitude,
which has undermined bilateral relations with Indonesia as
indicated by its decision to stop military cooperation and
assistance, and to review cooperation in the security field,"
Feisal told reporters here.
</P>
<P>
Based on the agreement, Indonesia and Australia will consult
about matters affecting their common security and develop
cooperation on security matters.
</P>
<P>
The agreement also contains provisions where the two countries
will consult each other in the case of adverse challenges to
either party, or to their common security interest, and, if
appropriate, consider measures which might be taken either
individually or jointly.
</P>
<P>
Australia suspended military cooperation with Indonesia last
week.
</P>
<P>
Director General for Political Affairs of the Foreign Ministry
Nugroho Wisnumurti said, "We don't intend to take further steps
that might worsen our relations (with Australia), but this is up
to the Australian side."  
</P>
</TEXT>
