<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 08:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Scientists Say Universe to Expand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Two Israeli scientists said
they have discovered new evidence that proves the universe is
infinite and will expand forever.
</P>
<P>
The research by two Hebrew University cosmologists, Avishai
Dekel and Idit Zehavi, is published Thursday in the Nature science
magazine.
</P>
<P>
The pair's study is a continuation of research done in this
regard by U.S. scientists.
</P>
<P>
The scientific world has been divided for some time between
two conflicting schools of thought regarding the nature of the
universe. One claims that the universe is finite and, at some
stage, will cease to expand and begin to contract. The other
school believes that universe to be infinite and asserts that it
will never cease to expand.
</P>
<P>
Both schools are based on the works of Albert Einstein, who
initially believed that at some point gravitation ceases to draw
objects together, reversing itself and instead causing objects to
pull apart.
</P>
<P>
According to Einstein, this negative gravity causes the
universe's expansion to constantly gain momentum - hence the
theory that it will infinitely expand, since the greater the
distances the stronger negative gravity becomes.
</P>
<P>
Later in his life Einstein retracted his theory, calling it
"the biggest mistake of my life." But recent research by American
scientists proves that Einstein had it right the first time.
</P>
<P>
By measuring the expansion rate of supernovas, or exploding
stars, and comparing it to the expansion rate of supernovas that
exploded 4 million years ago, scientists came to the conclusion
that the expansion rate has increased, thus proving that the
universe's expansion is infinite.
</P>
<P>
Dekel said that while the evidence does prove that the universe
is infinite, it does not mean that its rate of expansion will
always increase.
</P>
<P>
"It is possible that at some point, if the distances are great
enough, the forces will exactly balance each other out or even
cease to exist. If this is the case, the universe will continue
expanding, but at a uniform, unchanging rate," Dekel said.
</P>
<P>
Dekel and his team have taken their research one step further,
succeeding in mapping the density of what physicists call "dark
matter." The result show that the density of this material is
great enough to prove that gravity and antigravity do not cease
to exist, no matter how great the distance. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0228 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC to Offer Refund for Athletics Schedule Change </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The International Olympic
Committee will pay for their decision to change the athletics
schedule for next year's Sydney Olympic Games by offering refund
for those ticket-buyers.
</P>
<P>
IOC will also underwrite the costs of any returned tickets that
were not re-sold, John Coates, vice-president of the organizing
committee SOCOG said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
