<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0234 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Expansion Project at East China Port Ok'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
QINGDAO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The second-phase expansion
project at Qianwan Area of Qingdao Port, east China's Shandong
Province, has passed a State-sponsored appraisal.
</P>
<P>
Completion and operation of the Qianwan project helps expand
Qingdao Port from Jiaozhou Bay's eastern bank to its western bank.
</P>
<P>
Listed as a key coastal construction project during the ninth
Five-Year-Plan period (1996-2000), Qianwan went under construction
in December 1995 and cost 1.57 billion yuan (about 189 million U.S.
dollars).
</P>
<P>
Six deep-water berths have been built during the second-phase
expansion, including one container berth, considered the country's
biggest, which is capable of handling the world's latest
generations of large container ships.
</P>
<P>
Qingdao Port has 14 docks, 72 berths and has a combined
handling capacity of about 100 million tons. It offers navigation
services in crude oil, coal, mineral ores, containers, sundry
goods and passengers.
</P>
<P>
The port operates navigation services to over 450 harbors of
more than 130 countries and regions and has established friendly
ties with four foreign harbors including Seattle in the U.S.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
