<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon-Related Injuries Climb in HK (Update) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A total of 216 persons
sustained storm-related injuries and were admitted to hospitals,
when Typhoon York affected Hong Kong Thursday morning, according
to the latest government press release.
</P>
<P>
Among those injured, 87 have already been discharged after
treatment. A man injured was certified dead at United Christian
Hospital of Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
The Home Affairs Department has opened 33 temporary shelters so
far and a total of 494 people are accommodated.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Signal No. 10, which was issued at 6:45 Thursday
morning, is still hoisted, meaning that winds with mean speeds of
118 kilometers per hour or more are expected. The public are
advised not to relax their precautions.
</P>
<P>
At 1:00 p.m., Typhoon York was centered about 30 kilometers
west-southwest of the Hong Kong Observatory and is forecast to
move west-northwest at about 12 kilometers per hour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
