<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Manufacturing Sector Records Highest Sales in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's manufacturing
sales increased by 18.9 percent in July 1999, the highest
year-on-year growth registered in 17 months, the Statistics
Department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The manufacturing sales in July this year amounted to 22.1
billion ringgit (about 5.815 billion U.S. dollars) against 18.6
billion ringgit (about 4.894 billion U.S. dollars) recorded in the
same month last year, the department said in a preliminary report
released here.
</P>
<P>
For the month under review, the sales value was 2.3 percent
better than 21.6 billion ringgit (about 5.684 billion U.S.
dollars) achieved a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
As a result, for the first seven months of 1999, Malaysia's
total manufacturing sales stood at 139.3 billion ringgit (about
36.657 billion U.S. dollars), up 9.1 percent from 127.7 billion
ringgit (about 33.605 billion U.S. dollars) recorded in the same
period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
The department said that the number of employees engaged at the
end of July 1999 grew by 4.3 percent to 943,976 persons and was
0.3 percent higher in comparison with 940,963 persons employed at
the end of June 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tibetans Kicks off Bathing Festival </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LHASA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- As they have every Autumn since
the 12th Century, health-conscious Tibetans are heading to a river
in southern Lhasa to splash about in the sun.
</P>
<P>
For the next month, men and women in Tibet's capital city can
be seen bathing joyfully in the river water, usually in the
afternoon when the water temperature is most enjoyable. Like their
ancestors 800 years ago, they believe that the river water in
Autumn has the power to prevent a variety of diseases.
</P>
<P>
Many bathers have set up tents on the site and brought
alcoholic drinks.
</P>
<P>
Some local people have tried to profit from the tradition. A
local park in Lhasa, which used to open free of charge for the
event, now sells tickets.
</P>
<P>
Quzhen, a woman who owns a drugstore at the riverside, said
business has been brisk. "Towels, beer and soft drinks are
bestsellers," she said.
</P>
<P>
While they do have fun with a good custom, Tibetans have never
denied modern life. Public and private bathing facilities and even
saunas have appeared in Tibetan-populated areas. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
