<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0248 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's SEZs Striving to Stay Special(1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Editor's note: This year
marks the 50th anniversary of the founding of the People's
Republic of China. China's economic successes over the past five
decades has attracted the attention of the world. Xinhua began
issuing stories on the country's economy on August 17. This is the
24th.
</P>
<P>
Shenzhen, a small town in south China two decades ago with 310,
000 rural residents, has now grown into a modern city of 3.5
million people. The explanation for this miracle is attributed to
its good luck in having been chosen as the country's first special
economic zone (SEZ).
</P>
<P>
The central government approved the establishment of the
Shenzhen Special Economic Zone in August 1980. Not long after,
China set up three more SEZs in the coastal cities of Zhuhai,
Shantou, and Xiamen. And in 1988, China established its fifth SEZ
on the island province of Hainan.
</P>
<P>
During the process of China's reform and opening, these zones
have served as "experimental areas." Shenzhen, for example, has
pioneered more than 200 important aspects of the reform program,
including price reform, ownership transfer of enterprises, and
housing reform.
</P>
<P>
The central government now is pushing ahead with a port
management system reform experiment in Shenzhen, as it attempts to
open the service sector and foreign trade wider to overseas
investors.
</P>
<P>
"SEZs can try reform measures that cannot be tried in the
inland areas, a sign that SEZs are still something special," said
Li Haiyan, a State Council official.
</P>
<P>
In addition to geographical advantages, central to the success
of SEZs are the flexible and preferential policies granted to them
by the central government, such as helping the zones accumulate
their development funds and providing long-term bank loans at low
interest rates, Li said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 07:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UAE to Hold Mideast Optical Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Middle East Optical and
Ophthalmic Exhibition, to be held in Dubai, the United Arab
Emirates, from February 10 to 13, 2000, is drawing participants
from across the world.
</P>
<P>
Exhibitors from the Netherlands, Switzerland, France, Austria,
Italy, China, Britain, Singapore and other countries will be
taking part in the biennial event which has been recognized by
the optical industry as its most significant showcase in the
Middle East.
</P>
<P>
The exhibition will feature the latest in eyewear, eye care,
optical aids and accessories and cater to a fast-growing demand
for optical products in the Middle East, according to the Khaleej
Times newspaper.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 edition of the exhibition drew more than 125 companies
from 24 countries with business worth 5 million U.S. dollars
concluded. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0250 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's SEZs Striving to Stay Special(2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As a matter of fact, their not being special demonstrates the
fundamental experimental nature of the zones, and shows that the
experience of the zones has spread to and influenced other parts
of the country.
</P>
<P>
Starting in the 1990s, the SEZs began to restructure their
industries, and now they have largely relocated their old labor-
intensive operations and created technology- and capital-intensive
enterprises in their place.
</P>
<P>
In Shenzhen, for example, garment and textile manufacturers
have been shifted to inland sites, while hi-tech industries
devoted to the production of computers, telecom, bioengineering,
and the like, are developing rapidly, rising by 60 percent
annually in the past five years.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that last year the output value of Shenzhen's
hi-tech sector topped 65.5 billion yuan, nearly 40 percent of the
city's total industrial output value.
</P>
<P>
Similar restructuring has taken place in the other four zones,
as have impressive economic growth rates. Last year, the gross
domestic product (GDP) of the five zones reached 284.3 billion
yuan, more than 100 times that of 20 years ago. And in 1998 their
imports and exports registered 65.8 billion U.S. dollars, 20
percent of the country's total.
</P>
<P>
"Once again our SEZs are showing the way -- this time with
restructuring -- and setting an example for the entire nation's
economic development," Li said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
