<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Denies Alleged Bombing of Civilian Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Sri Lankan government
Thursday denied alleged bombing of civilian targets as fighting
between government troops and Tamil rebels escalated in the
country's north.
</P>
<P>
The air force on Wednesday conducted two missions successfully
against selected Tamil rebels' camps, military spokesman Brigadier
Sunil Tennakoon said.
</P>
<P>
He told a weekly press briefing that the government forces
would never bomb civilian targets.
</P>
<P>
The separatist Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam (LTTE) alleged
in a statement that 22 civilians were killed and another 41
wounded in an air raid on the village of Puthukkudirruppu in
Mullaitivu district, some 290 kilometers northeast of the capital.
</P>
<P>
The International Committee of the Red Cross confirmed the
attack, adding that reports so far from its officials in the
region said 21 civilians had been killed.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE said in the statement that government jets attacked as
the refugees were shopping at a village market.
</P>
<P>
The attack came after fierce battles between the government
troops and the rebels killed at least 169 combatants over the
weekend in the northern Wanni region.
</P>
<P>
The LTTE has been fighting for a separate homeland for minority
Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east since 1983. Over 55,000 have
been reported to be killed in the ethnic conflicts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
