<HEADLINE> Pyongyang Denounces U.S. Double-dealing Tactics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PYONGYANG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A Foreign Ministry
spokesman from the Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK) on
Wednesday denounced the U.S. for its double-dealing tactics,
saying this only deepens Pyongyang's mistrust of, and heightens
its vigilance against, Washington.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. is clinging to double-dealing tactics by saying one
thing at negotiations with the DPRK and another behind the scene,
the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
"As we have already clarified more than once, when the U.S.
shows good faith, we will reciprocate it," he said.
</P>
<P>
The United States, Japan and South Korea held a "tripartite
summit meeting" on September 12 before the opening of the APEC
meeting, at which they issued a "joint press statement."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said that in the statement, the United States
talks nonsense by suggesting that a comprehensive, joint and
integral stand by the U.S., Japan and South Korea would provide a
precious opportunity of ensuring peace and security on the Korean
Peninsula and that the three are ready to take all measures to
improve relations with the DPRK according to the step it takes for
detente and durable peace.
</P>
<P>
The United States produced such a statement at the time when
high-level negotiations are underway over the pending issues
between the DPRK and the U.S. It is an ill-intentioned attempt to
avail itself of an international meeting which can easily draw
world attention to force the DPRK feel a "sense of psychological
oppression" once again and wrest a sort of concession from it, the
spokesman announced.
</P>
<P>
"If the United States is truly interested in peace and
stability on the Korean Peninsula, it should fundamentally rectify
its policy to stifle the DPRK, withdraw from South Korea its
forces, which is the main stumbling block in the way of peace and
security on the peninsula, and root out all threats to the DPRK,
including joint military exercises, before urging the DPRK to show
an affirmative response," the spokesman said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Increase Flower Production, Export </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Famous for its orchids and
other tropical flowers, Thailand is aiming to become a flower
production center by increasing the number of commercial
nurseries, The Bangkok Post reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to the newspaper, the Agriculture and Cooperative
Ministry is planning to increase commercial flower nurseries by 10
percent to 50,000 rai (8,000 hectares) within two years.
</P>
<P>
The ministry is also making efforts to improve the quality of
locally-grown flowers to substitute for imports from Malaysia and
the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
The ministry expects the imports of foreign-grown flowers, such
as roses, chrysanthemums and gerberas, could be reduced by 10
percent by developing local substitutes.
</P>
<P>
Annual production of flowers in Thailand was expected to rise
to 71,741 tons from 64,570 tons by 2001. The ministry aims to
export 15,571 tons in 2001, up from 11,699 tons in 1998.
</P>
<P>
The baht's devaluation during the financial crisis has been a
help to make Thai flowers more competitive in the world market.
</P>
<P>
Under the ministry's plan, a flower export zone and central
market will be established. Participating growers and exporters
will be registered and required to meet high quality standards.
</P>
<P>
Seed development will be stepped up and nurseries will be
encouraged to try new varieties. Nurseries will be urged to use
new technology and the best growing techniques.
</P>
<P>
There will also be a database on production and marketing to
provide the ministry with information it needs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
