<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Ants Become Arthritis Medicine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The first medicine in the
world made from wild ants to treat rheumatoid arthritis has been
licensed by China's State Drug Administration.
</P>
<P>
The medicine, developed by Wu Zhicheng, a doctor at the Jinling
Geriatric Hospital in Nanjing, capital of east China's Jiangsu
Province, is now in trial production at Nanjing's Zhongshan
Pharmaceutical Factory.
</P>
<P>
China has a long history of using ants as medicine. Ben Cao
Gang Mu or Compendium of Materia Medica, the best-known and
respected Chinese medical manual written by Li Shizhen in the Ming
Dynasty (1368-1644), includes a detailed description of the
medicinal properties of wild ants.
</P>
<P>
Wu began his pharmacological research on wild ants in the early
1980s. His studies show that wild ants are rich in various types
of protein, amino acids and minerals, and are able to reduce
inflammation and ease pain.
</P>
<P>
More than 300 clinical tests conducted at six hospitals in
Beijing, Shanghai and Nanjing indicate that the new wild ant-based
capsule has proven effective on 81.7 percent of the test cases, a
better result than that of other medicines.
</P>
<P>
Doctors don't know the cause of rheumatoid arthritis, a
progressive disease characterized by inflammation and swelling of
the joints.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0257 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Number of Visitors to World Horticulture Expo Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, September 16 (Xinhua) --The number of visitors to the
ongoing World Horticulture Exposition in Kunming, the provincial
capital of Yunnan Province in southwest China, is on the decline,
tourism officials here say.
</P>
<P>
In July and August, the number of visitors peaked at an average
50,000-plus per day and on July 24 reached a record high of 81,100.
In recent weeks, however, the tally has dropped to a low daily
average of 22,000.
</P>
<P>
Tourism officials say that the ticket sales have dropped at
least partly because Chinese kids and college students have
returned to school.
</P>
<P>
The international horticulture show, in which the Chinese
Government alone invested as much as 1.6 billion yuan, has
attracted numerous domestic and overseas people with its floral
gardens built by different countries, large greenhouses, and a man-
made Nature Hall.
</P>
<P>
The event is the source of huge tourism income for the province,
especially the provincial capital, where all hotels and
restaurants are usually full during the run. 
</P>
</TEXT>
