<HEADLINE> Motorola Plans to Acquire General Instrument </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Motorola Inc. announced its
plan here on Wednesday to acquire General Instrument Corp. at 10.
66 billion U.S. dollars in a great effort to push itself into the
cable television market.
</P>
<P>
"This allows us to participate in the fastest-growing segments
of the telecommunication industry," said Christopher B. Galvin,
chairman and chief executive officer of Motorola, best known for
cellular phones and pagers.
</P>
<P>
General Instrument is the nation's largest producer of cable TV-
set-top boxes -- one of the key ingredients for delivering
broadband services to consumers. After its acquisition of General
Instrument, Motorola will offer broadband cable services to
consumers, including Internet, video and audio.
</P>
<P>
Industry experts said the number of set-top boxes will increase
from 20 million to 113 million in American homes over the next
five years.
</P>
<P>
Motorola will compete with AT&AMP;T Corp., the nation's largest
cable and long-distance telephone company, in the cable TV market
in future. 
</P>
</TEXT>
