<HEADLINE> Myanmar Produces 509 Megawatts of Power in 11 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Power plants in Myanmar, built
since 1988 when the present government took office, have generated
a total of 509 megawatts (mw) of electricity, said Myanmar leader
Senior-General Than Shwe.
</P>
<P>
Meeting with members of the Union Solidarity Development
Association here Wednesday, Than Shwe, chairman of the Myanmar
State Peace and Development Council, disclosed that the
electricity produced during the period included 255 mw generated
by the natural gas power plants, 143 mw by steam power plants and
111 mw by hydro-electric power plants.
</P>
<P>
He also said 407 mw more will be produced by five
hydro-electric power projects -- Paunglaung , Zaungtu, Mone,
Thaphanseik and Maipan -- being implemented, official newspaper
The New Light of Myanmar reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, there will also be 1,264 mw more to be generated by
four other new projects -- the Yeywa in Mandalay division, the
Bilin in Mon state, the Kun in Bago division and the Shweli in
northern Shan state.
</P>
<P>
According to official statistics, the installed capacity of
Myanmar's state-run Electric Power Enterprise, the main
electricity supplier of the country, was 1,055 mw as of the end of
April this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
