<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0266 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thai Exporters Benefit From Strong Yen, Weak Baht </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Thai exporters are reaping a
double windfall from the baht's weakness and the yen's surge
against the U.S. dollar, The Nation reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese yen reached 103.36 per dollar Wednesday, its
highest level for three and a half years.
</P>
<P>
Masatsugu Nagato, general manager of Industrial Bank of Japan
in Bangkok, was quoted as saying that a stronger yen means
Japanese exporters would lose their competitiveness and that is
good for exporters of Thailand.
</P>
<P>
The stronger Japanese currency also reflects clear signs of
economic recovery, pointing to the fact that Japan can buy more
goods from Thailand, where export income contributes around 40 to
45 percent of the total gross domestic product growth, the
newspaper said.
</P>
<P>
Local exporters were also benefiting from the weakness of the
baht, which had dived to a new 11-month low of 39.75 baht against
the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Nagato said local importers could be hurt a little. However,
the economic crisis still discourages imports and investment in
Thailand and thus the potential degree of difficulty for them is
only slight. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand to Open Farm Futures Exchange Next Year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Agricultural Commodities
Futures Exchange of Thailand (ACFET) plans to open by March or May
next year with four important goods -- rice, shrimp, tapioca and
rubber, The Nation reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Commerce Minister Phaitoon Kaewthong said after chairing
the committee on the futures market establishment that the draft
Futures Market Act is in the process of being published in the
Royal Gazette. The act will take effect within six months after
publication.
</P>
<P>
The committee also approved the setting up of a subcommittee to
draw up regulations, contract forms, documents, minimum and
maximum trading volumes and a transaction system.
</P>
<P>
The committee will ask the experts from the Stock Exchange of
Thailand to help set up all necessary systems such as computers to
complete transactions in the initial stages.
</P>
<P>
Phaitoon said the electronic system is likely to be selected
because it is more transparent than traditional brokering.
</P>
<P>
ACFET aims to stabilize commodity prices and reduce funds spent
on government intervention programs every year. In addition, it
will also generate higher incomes for farmers. 
</P>
</TEXT>
