<HEADLINE> Another Apartment Building Blown up in Russia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Another apartment building in
Russia was blown up early Thursday, this time in the southern city
of Volgodonsk, killing four people and injuring over 70, the Itar-
Tass news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The blast happened at 05:50 Moscow time (0150 GMT), and
demolished a nine-story building made of prefabricated panels,
Tass said.
</P>
<P>
It was not clear how many people were inside the building, but
the death toll is expected to rise in the explosion that was said
to be caused by a bomb inside a GAZ-53 truck parked near the
building in 35 Gagarin Street.
</P>
<P>
This is the fifth explosion that rocked Russia since August 31,
when a bomb went off in an underground shopping mall near the
Kremlin, killing one person and injuring dozens of others.
</P>
<P>
On September 6, a car bomb destroyed a residential block inside
a military compound in Buinaksk, Daghestan, killing 64 people,
many of them women and children.
</P>
<P>
More than 200 people were killed in two subsequent explosions
in the capital city on September 8 and 12.
</P>
<P>
Authorities believe terrorists with links to Chechen rebels
were behind the blasts and security has been beefed up in Moscow
and around the country, especially near vital installations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
