<HEADLINE> Thailand Prepared to Send Troops to East Timor: PM </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Thai Prime Minister Chuan
Leekpai said Thailand is ready to send a peacekeeping force to
East Timor, state television station Channel 9 reported Thursday
morning.
</P>
<P>
Chuan said Indonesia hopes that members of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) would take part in the
multinational peacekeeping force for East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Thailand, Singapore, the Philippines and Malaysia are among
the members which have expressed willingness to be part of the
force.
</P>
<P>
Thai Foreign Minister Surin Pitsuwan said on Wednesday that
Thailand will send a 700-strong battalion including engineers and
medical personnel to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
He said the first batch of the Thai contingent will leave for
East Timor this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The advance team of 30-40 personnel will make preparations for
the contingent.
</P>
<P>
General Surayud Chulanont, the army chief, said the Thai troops
can undertake an assignment within two weeks of notification. They
will stay in East Timor for at least six months and will not be
replaced.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Wednesday approved a multinational
military force for East Timor to restore order there and get vital
aid to thousands of refugees. 
</P>
