<HEADLINE> Thai Electronic Assemblers Turn to Local Parts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 16 (Xinhua) -- More electronic assemblers in
Thailand turned to locally-made components, saving the country at
least 1 billion baht (26.3 million U.S. dollars) a year, The
Bangkok Post said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The trend was promoted by the Board of Investment (BOI), which
launched a Unit for Industrial Linkage Development (BUILD)
project.
</P>
<P>
Established in November 1997, BUILD served as a link between
buyers and manufacturers of industrial products. It now has about
500 small and medium-sized enterprises as members.
</P>
<P>
BOI officials said that as more electronic assemblers were
joining the project, the country might save up to 1.5 billion baht
(39.4 million dollars) a year.
</P>
<P>
However, the figure was still small when compared with the
whole industry. Each year, Thailand exports electronic products
worth about 600 billion baht (15.8 billion dollars) while
importing parts for about 500 billion baht (13.2 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
BOI officials urged more buyers and suppliers to join the BUILD
project so as to promote the development of local electronic
components manufacturing industry and save the country more
foreign reserves. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
