<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Profile: Author of China's Civil War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Before Huang Jiren, no
Chinese writer had ever tackled the story of the life of POWs in
China's 1945-1949 civil war.
</P>
<P>
Huang has been writing about the POWs' since 1977, when he was
still in college.
</P>
<P>
His first book, "The War Not Only On the Battlefield," tells
the tale of how the Kuomintang (KMT) officers and men who
surrendered in the war were re-educated by the central government
and until they were no longer enemies of the Chinese people.
</P>
<P>
The civil war ended in 1949 with KMT's retreat to Taiwan.
However, many KMT members did not follow their colleagues, but
remained and surrendered to the Communist Party of China (CPC).
</P>
<P>
Based on its consistent principle of giving preferential
treatment to POWs, the CPC showed them the true nature of KMT's
leader Chiang Kai-shek and the truth of socialism in order to turn
enemies into friends, instead of putting them in prison.
</P>
<P>
The book reflects this history and created a great public buzz.
</P>
<P>
His contemporaries called him the "author of the civil war" who
explored a new field in culture. His books "Collapse" and "
Chongqing Negotiation" have been made into films that were
nationally acclaimed.
</P>
<P>
Huang attributes his success to his unique experiences. His
father was a high-ranking officer in the KMT army. In Huang's
first book he interviews his father, along with some 100 famous
former KMT military officers, including Du Yuming and Huang Wei,
who had similar experiences.
</P>
<P>
In the turmoil of the Cultural Revolution (1966-1976), Huang
was persecuted because of his relationship with the KMT. So was
his father, who died in prison.
</P>
<P>
Huang then had to carry sand along the Yangtze River to make a
living. Then he spent eight years in an outlying rural area of
Sichuan province, doing farm work and living with local farmers
until the national college entrance examination was resumed by the
government in 1977s. Huang took it and entered Neijiang Normal
College.
</P>
<P>
The Third Plenary Session of the 11th CPC Central Committee
which convened in late 1978 was a turnaround in Huang's life. No
one would look down upon him any more because of who he was or had
been.
</P>
<P>
To date, he has written eight books which have established his
reputation. He has been elected to be a deputy to the National
People's Congress (NPC) and to a member of the National Committee
of the Ninth Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (
CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
Huang has recorded the development of China's democratic
construction in his book "A NPC Deputy's Diary," including the
details of the discussion on the proposals for the Three Gorges
Project and Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
He said his new book about the NPC system and the construction
of democratic and legal system will be issued on October 1, as a
gift for the 50th birthday of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lee Teng-hui's "Two States" Statement Goes Nowhere: FM Spokesman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The "two states" statement
made by Lee Teng-hui of Taiwan, which runs counter to the
historical trend, goes nowhere in the international arena and Lee'
s attempt to split the motherland is doomed to failure, said
Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi here today.
</P>
<P>
Sun made the remarks when referring to the fact that the
General Committee of the 54th session of the UN General Assembly
has again refused the proposal raised by a small number of
countries to list the issue of Taiwan's "representation" in the
United Nations on the agenda of the session.
</P>
<P>
Sun said that the fact has fully demonstrated the firm stand of
most UN member nations to safeguard the purpose and principles of
the UN Charter, maintain the UN Resolution 2758 and adhere to the
"one China" policy.
</P>
<P>
Facts have again indicated that the attempt of the Taiwan
authorities to create "two Chinas" and "one China, One Taiwan" in
the United Nations is "futile and unpopular", the spokesman said.
</P>
