<HEADLINE> More Typhoon-Related Injuries Reported in Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A total of 116 persons
sustained storm-related injuries and one of them died in hospital
as Typhoon York was approaching Hong Kong Thursday morning,
according to the latest government press release.
</P>
<P>
Three of them have already been discharged after treatment, but
a man injured in Tseung Kwan O was certified dead at United
Christian Hospital.
</P>
<P>
So far 347 people have sought refuge at 32 temporary shelters
run by the Home Affairs Department.
</P>
<P>
Northeasterly winds reaching hurricane force are affecting
parts of Hong Kong three hours after Hurricane Signal No. 10 was
hoisted at 6:45 a.m.
</P>
<P>
York's eye is affecting the southern part of the region. The
Hurricane Signal No. 10, the most serious in the past 16 years in
Hong Kong, means that winds with mean speeds of 118 kilometers per
hour or more are expected. 
