<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Reviews Surfing Law as Rainstorm Approaches </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong government is
reviewing a law banning surfing at beaches ordered closed during a
typhoon, the English-language newspaper Hong Kong Standard
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The move came as the No. 10 Typhoon Signal was hoisted early
Thursday as severe tropical Typhoon York was moving closer to Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
At present, surf offenders face a maximum fine of 2,000 HK
dollars (256 U.S. dollars) and 14 days' imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
But the Urban Services Department said the law has never been
executed, because it was hard to implement.
</P>
<P>
"It's quite impossible to block off an entire beach, and life
guards cannot stay on the beaches round the clock," the paper
quoted Paul Cheung Kwok-yee, the department's senior staff officer,
as saying.
</P>
<P>
More than 100 people had to be rescued off Hong Kong beaches
when Typhoon Sam struck Hong Kong last month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
