<HEADLINE> Thailand Seen as Vegetable Seed Hub </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Thailand is likely to become
a leader in seed production, especially of vegetables, the
newspaper Bangkok Post said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Thailand is well-placed because it produces high-quality seeds
for the local and export markets, Anthony Tse, president of the
Asia and Pacific Seed Association (APSA), was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
Tse is in Thailand this week to attend the Sixth Asian Seed
Conference in Bangkok.
</P>
<P>
The Thai private sector is very active in seed production and
Thai farmers accept the cultivation of hybrid varieties, he said.
</P>
<P>
"Besides Japan, Taiwan and South Korea, Thailand is moving to
be a leader in tropical Asia," he added.
</P>
<P>
The development of the seed industry in Asia will come at a
faster pace with the assistance of new technology, which will
speed up the process by offering a better selection of genes, Tse
noted.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Manas Chiaravanond, executive vice-president of Chia
Tai Co. Ltd., who received the APSA Special Award this week, said
Thailand is a leading global production base for vegetable seeds.
</P>
<P>
Thailand has done very well in the production of watermelon,
cucumber, pepper, tomato, pumpkin and squash seeds, according to
Manas.
</P>
<P>
Thai farmers are well-recognized internationally in the
production of vegetable seeds for hand-pollinated crops, he noted.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
