<HEADLINE> Floating Bridge Over Danube Opens to Traffic in Yugoslavia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BELGRADE, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A floating bridge over the
Danube in Novi Sad has been constructed and was opened to traffic
Wednesday, the Yugoslav news agency Tanjug reported.
</P>
<P>
The bridge, which is 390 meters long and nine meters wide, has
two lanes and two walkways.
</P>
<P>
The reconstruction of the Beska Bridge, another bridge spanning
the Danube in the city, was finished on July 20, said the report.
</P>
<P>
In the opening ceremony, Dragan Tomic, president of the
assembly of the Serb Republic of Yugoslavia, said "the Federation
of Yugoslavia has become the largest construction site in Europe."
The country is in the process of being reconstructed as a result
of the war.
</P>
<P>
The three bridges over the Danube in Novi Sad in northern
Yugoslavia were destroyed during NATO's 79-day bombing campaign
against Yugoslavia, which began on March 24. 
</P>
</TEXT>
