<BODY>
<HEADLINE> East Asian Tourists Flock to Sri Lanka </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, September 16 (Xinhua) -- There has been a sharp
increase in tourist arrivals from East Asian countries to Sri
Lanka following the gradual recovery of the Asian financial
situation, tourist officials said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
They said the increase in tourist arrivals also could be
attributed to promotional activities to build a positive image for
the tropical island nation during the past two years.
</P>
<P>
From January to July this year 27,708 tourists from East Asia
visited Sri Lanka, registering an increase of 39.1 percent over
the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
According to the statistics, Japan topped the arrival list of
East Asia with a total of 9,519 tourists arrivals recording a
49.3-percent increase.
</P>
<P>
Arrivals from Malaysia recorded a 66.3-percent rise to 3,168,
while the number of tourists from Singapore went up by 39.7
percent to 3,873.
</P>
<P>
Increases were also recorded in tourist traffic from Thailand
(42.6 percent) and South Korea (34 percent).
</P>
<P>
During the first seven months of this year a total of 246,054
tourists visited Sri Lanka, recording an increase of 21.4 percent
over the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Last year Sri Lanka earned about 14.8 billion rupees (224
million U.S. dollars) from 381,063 tourists. The tourism sector
has become one of the major foreign exchange earners for the
country.
</P>
<P>
The Tourist Board has predicted a 17-percent rise in tourist
arrivals this year to around 446,000. 
</P>
</TEXT>
