<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bulgaria, Kazakhstan Sign 7 Bilateral Pacts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- During Kazakh President
Nursultan Nazarbayev's visit to Bulgaria, the two countries signed
on Wednesday seven bilateral agreements, including a presidential
declaration, on promoting bilateral economic ties.
</P>
<P>
In the declaration, Bulgarian President Peter Stoyanov and his
Kazakh counterpart voiced their will to further promote
friendship and cooperation.
</P>
<P>
The document stressed the strategic importance of the
implementation of the Interstate Oil and Gas Transport to Europe
Program and the "new silk road project," which will make the
European and Asian transcontinental transport networks accessible
to Central Asian and Caucasus countries.
</P>
<P>
The other six agreements included four inter-governmental
accords on mutual promotion and protection of investments,
cooperation in tourism, standardization, meteorology,
certification and aviation.
</P>
<P>
The remaining two were inter-departmental accords on
cooperation in education and agriculture.
</P>
<P>
At a joint news conference, the Bulgarian President said that
there are untapped opportunities for promoting commercial,
economic and cultural relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Stoyanov in particular cited the silk road restoration as a
major long-term project that would involve not only the
establishment of a transport corridor but also possibilities for
oil and gas shipment.
</P>
<P>
He also viewed the promotion of trade and joint ventures as
short-term tasks.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, commodity exchanges between the two countries were
worth only 22.5 million US dollars, unsatisfactory to both sides.
</P>
<P>
On his part, Kazakh President Nazarbayev described as being of
bilateral interest the implementation of the silk road project,
which would involve transport arteries and oil pipelines through
the Caspian to the Black Sea.
</P>
<P>
Although Kazakhstan is rich in oil and gas resources, its
annual oil output is only at 26 million tons for lack of export
possibilities, Nazarbayev said.
</P>
<P>
Kazakhstan hopes to boost its oil exports to 120 million tons
in 2007 and 230 million tons in 2012, and will need a transport
corridor through Bulgaria, he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
