<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0291 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Facts and Figures on China's Foreign Trade </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Editor's note: The People's Republic of China celebrates its
50th founding anniversary this year and Xinhua will release 10
stories on key facts and figures on the nation's economic and
social development over the last half century. This is the second.
</P>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- In the 50 years since the
founding of new China, China has developed from one of the poorest
countries in the world into a major power in international trade,
as indicated by the following facts and figures.
</P>
<P>
China is the world's 11th largest trade power in 1998, compared
to the 32nd in 1978.
</P>
<P>
It exported 183.8 billion U.S. dollars-worth of products in
1998, which is 80 times more than that of 1959, and 18 times over
1978.
</P>
<P>
It imported 140.2 billion dollars-worth of products in 1998,
which is 242 times the figure for 1950 and 13 times over 1978.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China exported 163.2 billion dollars worth of
manufactured goods, or 89 percent of its total export value.
</P>
<P>
Machinery and electronic products were leaders in China's
export products for the fourth consecutive year in 1998. The
export of these products was worth 66.5 billion dollars in 1998,
accounting for 36 percent of China's total export value.
</P>
<P>
China had more than 60 trade partners during the 1950s. The
number of China's trade partners increased to 180 in 1980 and is
now at 227.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, China's top 10 export markets were: Hong Kong, the
United States, Japan, Germany, the Republic of Korea (ROK), the
Netherlands, Britain, Singapore, Taiwan and France.
</P>
<P>
Its top 10 import source countries and regions in 1998 were:
Japan, the United States, Taiwan, ROK, Germany, Hong Kong,
Singapore, Russia, France and Australia.
</P>
<P>
Processing trade is now the most important foreign trade form
for China. Its value in 1998 was 173 billion US dollars, making up
53 percent of the country's total foreign trade value.
</P>
<P>
In 1978, foreign trade accounted for 10 percent of China's
gross domestic product (GDP). The figure rose to 34 percent in
1998.
</P>
<P>
China's foreign reserve stood at 145 billion US dollars in 1998,
compared to 840 million dollars in 1979.
</P>
<P>
China now has more than 23,000 enterprises engaged in export
and import business. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0292 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Shows Cataracts Still Top Cause of China's Blindness </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIANJIN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- A recent sample survey
conducted by Chinese ophthalmologists shows that cataracts are the
leading cause of blindness for 41.6 percent of Chinese blind
people.
</P>
<P>
The survey's findings were announced at the ongoing Asian-
Pacific contract operation conference here, which has drawn some
300 experts from more than 30 countries in the region.
</P>
<P>
The study, conducted according to the World Health Organization
(WHO) standards, shows that more than five million Chinese people
suffer from cataracts, or 0.46 percent of China's population.
</P>
<P>
Blind and sight-impaired people make up 0.43 percent and 0.58
of China's population. Among this group, 49.38 percent of the
sight-impaired have cataracts and 73.13 percent of the blind and
sight-impaired people over 60 suffer from cataracts.
</P>
<P>
The survey also indicates that the cataract incidence in lower-
latitude areas in south China and the plateau regions is much
higher than in the north. For instance, the cataract incidence in
south China's Guangdong province and in Tibet Autonomous Region
are 0.69 percent and 1.04 percent, while in northeast China's
Heilongjiang the figure is merely 0.26 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, people who live in high altitudes
which have more hours of sunshine are more prone to cataracts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
