<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Taiwan Semiconductor Equipment Industry Benefits from Foundry Boom </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Taiwan now accounts for
two-thirds of revenue's worldwide for foundry-produced integrated
circuits, according to data released Wednesday by a global trade
association.
</P>
<P>
Taiwan's share of the worldwide semiconductor equipment market
has burgeoned from one percent in 1990 to a projected 18 percent
by the end of 1999, surpassing South Korea and Europe, and nearly
catching up with Japan, which accounts for 21 percent, according
to data from the California-based Semiconductor Equipment and
Materials International (SEMI
</P>
<P>
Semiconductor equipment capital spending in Taiwan has
increased from 80 million U.S. dollars in 1990 to 3.28 billion
dollars in 1998, and is projected to reach 4.2 billion dollars
this year and 5.2 billion dollars in 2000.
</P>
<P>
Foundries represent 25 to 30 percent of world chip production.
A foundry is a semiconductor manufacturer that makes chips for a
third party, while a "fabless," or fabricationless, refers to a
semiconductor vendor that does not have in-house manufacturing
facilities but does design and test chips.
</P>
<P>
Now nearly every fabless integrated circuit design house and
integrated device manufacturer has part or all of its products
made at a foundry based in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The foundry business model, and its corresponding emerging
customer model, the fabless company, emerged in the early-to-mid
1980s. The emergence of the foundry industry is a structural
response to the need to concentrate capital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0295 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Venezuelan "Basket of Crude" Oil Prices Rising </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CARACAS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The Venezuelan "basket of
crude" oil prices closed at 20.50 US dollars per barrel on
Wednesday, said acting Energy and Mines Minister Alvaro Silva on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The price of the Venezuelan basket rose by 87 cents per barrel
last week, and closed at 19.13 US dollars.
</P>
<P>
So far this year and until last Friday, the Venezuelan
petroleum basket has sustained an average price of 13.55 dollars
per barrel, 4.55 dollars above the previous average sale price of
9 dollars per barrel, which was used to calculate the nation's
budget for 1999.
</P>
<P>
The international petroleum market is recuperating due to a
lowering of U.S. inventories, and the compliance of production
cuts by the members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries (OPEC).
</P>
<P>
The independent producers and OPEC members agreed to reduce
petroleum production by 2.1 million barrels per day for a year on
April 1. 
</P>
</TEXT>
