<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0297 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Pit Found Near First Emperor's Tomb </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archaeologists recently
discovered a new pit at Qin Shihuang's Tomb -- the world-famous
burial grounds of China's first emperor which have been dubbed the
"eighth wonder of the world."
</P>
<P>
The 13,000-square-meter apparently subordinate pit lies in the
southeast of the burial grounds. Its square shape is similar to
that of the two large pits which were found earlier and contain
the renowned life-sized terra cotta warriors and horses.
</P>
<P>
In the new and third pit, archaeologists found 80 stone suits
of armor and 30 stone helmets. All of the armor and helmets are
made of dark blue stone plate of the same thickness. Pieces are
attached with copper strips.
</P>
<P>
A Chinese expert has called the discovery "an unprecedented
event in the archaeological history of both China and abroad."
</P>
<P>
"Such perfect craftsmanship has never been recorded in any
historical documents. Discovery of these objects has filled a gap
in our understanding of Chinese military equipment from ancient
times," he said.
</P>
<P>
Qin Shihuang forced 800,000 workers to build the tomb for him
when he was only 13 years old.
</P>
<P>
The "most splendid archeological find" in this century was
accidentally discovered in 1974 by a local farmer while he was
digging a well. Since then, three huge pits have been discovered
near the tomb.
</P>
<P>
More than 7,000 2,200-year-old life-sized terra cotta warriors
and horses along with tens of thousands of pieces of weaponry have
been uncovered from the three pits. The purpose of the warriors
and horses, located less than a mile from the emperor's tomb, was
to maintain and protect the spirit of their ruler throughout
eternity. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0298 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Funds Beefing up Tree Planting in Southwest China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Chongqing Municipality in
southwest China is using foreign funds to shore up its
afforestation efforts.
</P>
<P>
Over 100,000 hectares of forests have been added to the city in
recent years, mainly along the Yangtze River where the Three
Gorges Hydro-electric Power Project is under construction.
</P>
<P>
Chongqing, an inland industrial heartland, became China's
fourth municipality directly under central government jurisdiction
in 1997, joining the ranks of Beijing, Shanghai, and Tianjin.
</P>
<P>
Since 1995, the World Bank has financed the city's tree-
planting programs, with about 200 million yuan (about 24.1 million
U.S. dollars) in loans. This year, the German government has begun
to provide some 12 million DM in funds to the city government for
a major afforestation program in the Three Gorges Dam area.
</P>
<P>
The Chongqing section of the Yangtze is one of the most eroded
areas in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
