<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0304 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Myanmar Collects 150 Million U.S. Dollars in Taxes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YANGON, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Myanmar's State Internal
Revenue Department collected a total of 155.7 million U.S. dollars
of taxes in fiscal 1998-99 which ended in March, a 21.83-percent
increase over the previous fiscal year when the 127.8 million
dollars was collected.
</P>
<P>
Of the total, commodities and services tax and commercial tax
accounted for 46.97 percent while income tax represented 34.26
percent and profit tax 8 percent, the latest government statistics
show.
</P>
<P>
To reduce the impact of the Asian financial crisis, the Myanmar
government adopted some new policies to collect taxes in the
country in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Exemption of customs duties on the import of agricultural
implements, including related machinery, pesticide and fertilizer,
 was among the measures taken to ensure that agriculture, the
mainstay of the country's economy, is not effected.
</P>
<P>
Other measures cover raising the customs duties of luxury goods
imported and levying an 8-percent commercial tax on foreign
currencies beginning January 1, 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
