<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China in Top Gear to Clean up Major Lake </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HEFEI, September 16 (Xinhua) -- China has started the countdown
to clean up one of its major lakes, Chaohu, in eastern Anhui
Province by the end of this year.
</P>
<P>
Pollutant plants have been ordered to shut down without delay
or face harsh penalties imposed by the State Environmental
Protection Administration, China's watchdog on ecology and
environment.
</P>
<P>
Clearing Chaohu lake is one of the nation's largest
environmental protection projects this century, which is expected
to cost millions of U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
China launched an ambitious program in 1997 to rein in
pollution in and around three rivers and two lakes -- Huaihe,
Haihe, Liaohe, Dianchi, and Chaohu.
</P>
<P>
The target at Chaohu is to make all industrial enterprises
around the freshwater lake reach the State-set pollutant discharge
standard by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
As one of China's largest freshwater lakes, Chaohu seats on a
major migration route between Australia and China for many wading
birds and is a winter home for 200 species of migratory birds.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the lake has been threatened by pollution and
dwindling wetlands areas. Migratory birds are seldom seen hovering
and few fishermen can be spotted in the lake, which is filled with
withering reeds.
</P>
<P>
An estimated 280 million tons of industrial sewage and that
created by nearby residents flows into the lake every year, and a
13,000-kilometer area around the lake suffers from serious soil
erosion.
</P>
<P>
Some 9.6 million people are affected by the deteriorating
environment, and many are becoming more involved in protecting
their surroundings.
</P>
<P>
Researchers at a chemical plant located by the lake are
developing a large variety of phosphorus-free detergents and
washing powder. They said it exceeded their expectations that the
plant's new products were sold out as soon as they hit the stores.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0308 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Eximbank Issues More Bonds </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Export and Import Bank of
China (Eximbank) successfully issued three billion yuan (361
million US dollars) worth of two-year financial bonds Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to today's China Daily, the Eximbank has obtained
approval of the People's Bank of China, the central bank, and its
second market-adjusted issuance of policy financial bonds follows
a similar five billion yuan floatation on May 6, this year.
</P>
<P>
Eximbank is one of the three Chinese policy banks, which is
specialized in supporting mechanical and electronic exports.
</P>
<P>
The offering followed the practice of public bidding that the
bank is pursuing for more effective management.
</P>
<P>
The interest rate is set at an annual 2.91 percent as a result
of heated bidding, the bank said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
About 29 financial institutions participated in the bidding
before 20 of them won out and became the underwriters of the three
billion yuan batch.
</P>
<P>
Underwriting offers from the bidders totaled 7.27 billion yuan,
more than double the amount offered by the Eximbank. 
</P>
</TEXT>
