<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hebei To Be Another Center for Chinese Economic Growth </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Hebei Province has long
tried to attract more overseas investment while at the same time
expanding its export business on other continents, a top
provincial official said recently.
</P>
<P>
Ye Liansong, secretary of the Hebei Provincial Committee of the
Communist Party of China, said that the province has garnered a
total 9.06 billion U.S. dollars, and set up 4,521 solely foreign-
funded enterprises, joint ventures, and cooperative firms, with
the overseas financing used accounting for over 11 percent of the
province's fixed assets.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with Xinhua reporters, Ye said that most joint
ventures are engaged in the six export-oriented pillar industries,
including textile and clothing, machinery and electronics,
pharmaceuticals and chemistry, building materials, light industry,
and high-quality agricultural and sideline products.
</P>
<P>
In addition to the markets in Hong Kong, Macao, and Taiwan, as
well as in Japan and countries in Southeast Asia, it is also
trying to get its exports into the markets in Europe, Central and
Latin America, Africa, and Oceania.
</P>
<P>
To accomplish this, Hebei has in the last two decades spent a
significant sum to build up its infrastructure, particularly
transport, telecommunications, electricity, and water-control
facilities, said Ye.
</P>
<P>
And it has issued preferential policies and set up an
administrative center to offer services to foreign-funded
enterprises and to ensure the legal rights of overseas businessmen.
</P>
<P>
Ye said Hebei is encouraging overseas investment in the fields
of agriculture, energy resources, telecommunications, energy-
saving and technological upgrading projects, which will benefit
both the province and the country. A high proportion of hi-
technology is crucial for rapid growth of the provincial economy,
he added.
</P>
<P>
The province is located in the central area of the Bohai Bay
surrounding Beijing and Tianjin, a port city in north China, with
a coastline of 487 kilometers. Officials there are striving to
make the Bohai Bay area another vital contributor to the Chinese
economy after the Pearl River Delta area and the Yangtze River
Delta area, Ye said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0310 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia to Cooperate With Multinational Force </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The Indonesian government and
military said they had accepted the U.N. Security Council decision
to send an Australia-led multinational force to East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian President B.J. Habibie welcomed Australia's role,
Minister of Information Muhammad Yunus said after a cabinet
meeting here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"Indonesia never has any hostile feeling against any other
countries," Yunus said, adding that Indonesian Military (TNI)
members will act as liaison officers and observers in the force.
</P>
<P>
TNI spokesman Maj. Gen. Sudrajat said Wednesday that the
military was not in any position to reject the U.N. decision.
</P>
<P>
"We will be very cooperative. TNI is prepared to join the
multinational force if asked. But if it is not needed, we will
only be too happy to stay out," he said.
</P>
<P>
When asked about the role of Australia in the force, Sudrajat
said: "People should understand that there have been bitter
feelings between people in the two countries. Political leaders in
Indonesia and Australia should understand the situation, and this
should not jeopardize our bilateral relationship that has been
going on very well, (but) now is slightly disrupted."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Coordinating Minister for Political and Security
Affairs Feisal Tanjung maintained that Australia should bear the
risk of troop deployment in East Timor in view of its unpopularity
among the Indonesian public.
</P>
<P>
"I believe there is a risk that Australian contingent might
face in East Timor," he said.
</P>
<P>
Dewi Fortuna Anwar, a senior adviser to Habibie, warned that
Australian troops could be singled out for militia attacks.
</P>
<P>
"There is a very strong feeling of animosity towards Australia,
rightly or wrongly, from the pro-integration forces in East
Timor," she said.
</P>
<P>
Two election winners, the Indonesian Democratic Party of
Struggle (PDI-P) and the Golkar Party, Wednesday appealed to the
United Nations to respect Indonesian sovereignty in East Timor up
to the general meeting of the People's Consultative Assembly in
November.
</P>
<P>
PDI-P Chairperson Megawati called on the Indonesian people to
control their emotion about any U.N. decision on the deployment of
troops in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Golkar Chairman Akbar Tanjung expressed his disappointment at
the Australian role. Australia's leadership in the force could
make the entire multinational force less than neutral, he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Wednesday authorized a multinational
force to move into East Timor to restore peace and security there.
</P>
<P>
U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan hailed the Australian
readiness to lead the force to be deployed immediately.
</P>
<P>
Australian Defense Minister John Moore was quoted by The
Indonesian Observer as saying the force is ready to leave for East
Timor no later than Monday.
</P>
<P>
In Dili, capital of East Timor, the Military Emergency Command
said it had begun preparations to make way for the arrival of the
multinational force.
</P>
<P>
Until the arrival of the U.N. force, TNI would continue with
its job of restoring peace in East Timor, particularly in Dili,
command chief Maj. Gen. Kiki Syahnakri was quoted by The Jakarta
Post as saying. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
