<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0312 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ancient Brick Tomb Excavated in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, September 16 (Xinhua)-- A tomb dating back to the
period between Song and Jin Dynasties (960 A.D.-1279) was
discovered in north China's Shanxi Province recently.
</P>
<P>
It was found by a group of construction workers on the site of
a residential building in the city of Houma. They immediately
reported it to local cultural relics department.
</P>
<P>
Further excavation shows that the tomb is 2.45-meters long and
2.38 meters wide with a brick chamber in which lay four skeletons
and some burial objects.
</P>
<P>
The chamber's inner walls were carved with magnificent designs
and scenes described in ancient stories.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists agreed that the tomb illustrated high-level
design and construction standards in ancient times.
</P>
<P>
It will add to the study of folk customs, architectural
characteristics and social development of the Song and Jin
Dynasties, they said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
