<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0316 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon York Attacks Hong Kong </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Typhoon York that is
approaching Hong Kong forced the suspension of most public
transport services and closure of banks and schools Thursday.
</P>
<P>
At 9:00 a.m. Thursday, York was centered about 25 kilometers
south-southeast of Hong Kong and is forecast to move west-
northwest at 15 kilometers per hour toward Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Hurricane Signal No. 10 was hoisted at 6:45 a.m. to replace the
Tropical Cyclone Signal No. 9, which was hoisted at 5:20 a.m. This
means that winds with a mean speed of 118 kilometers per hour or
more are expected. The red rainstorm warning was hoisted at 5:27 a.
m.
</P>
<P>
Up to 6:00 a.m. Thursday, nine flights had been diverted.
Airlines ceased to check in passengers temporarily due to the
forced cancellation or delay of flights.
</P>
<P>
Services of some bus and ferry lines have been suspended or
limited to certain routes. The Kowloon-Canton Railway services
between Hung Hom and Lo Wu stations have been reduced to 10-minute
intervals. Mass Transit Railway is running at 15-minute intervals.
</P>
<P>
Light Rail Transit is running services normally.
</P>
<P>
All schools, banks and courts will be closed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The Home Affairs Department has opened 28 temporary shelters
and so far 83 people have sought refuge at the shelters.
</P>
<P>
There have been four cases of damage to trees. However, no
incidents of flooding or landslide have been reported so far.
</P>
<P>
Three persons were injured and admitted to hospital, of whom
two had been discharged after treatment. One woman, aged 64, was
admitted in serious condition at the Yan Chai Hospital. 
</P>
</TEXT>
