<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0030 GMT, September 16 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz said on
Wednesday that Iraq will accept nothing less than the total
lifting of sanctions imposed on the country more than nine years
ago.
</P>
<P>
Aziz told reporters Wednesday evening on the sideline of the on-
going 9th International Popular Islamic Conference which has been
intended to show solidarity with the Iraqi people. (Iraq-London
Meeting-Sanctions)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
BRUSSELS -- The North Atlantic Treaty Organization and Russia
held an ambassadorial level meeting in Brussels Wednesday to
discuss "ways to further improve the security situation in Kosovo".
</P>
<P>
At the NATO-Russia Permanent joint Council (PJC) meeting, both
sides condemned "all acts of violence and called upon all the
people of Kosovo to support and cooperate with the international
security and civil presence". (NATO-Russia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- The United States said on Wednesday that it sends
hundreds of American troops to East Timor as part of a
multinational force in order to protect its military and economic
interests.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Rubin said Indonesia stands
astride critical sea lanes and lines of communication, which are
critical to the U.S. interests. (US-E.Timor)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- More than three million Americans fled inland
Wednesday as Hurricane Floyd thrashed along the U.S. southeast
coast, pounding beaches with heavy surf and ripping down tree
limbs and power lines.
</P>
<P>
About 3.2 million people had been urged to evacuate, said
officials in Florida, Georgia and South Carolina, and more people
joined the exodus Wednesday in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
Federal emergency officials said it was the biggest evacuation
in U.S. history. (US-Hurricane)
</P>
<P>
---
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations General Committee on
Wednesday decided not to consider the issue of so-called "Taiwan's
participation at the United Nations" during the 54th session of
the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the General Committee held a long debate
about it. It is the seventh consecutive year that the General
Committee made such a decision. (China-Taiwan-UN)  
</P>
</TEXT>
