<HEADLINE>   O'Neill Could Quit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Leicester boss Martin O'Neill
has refused to rule out resigning in the wake of the latest
boardroom chaos at the club, according to local reports on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
O'Neill promised he would "say something tomorrow" regarding
his future and, on the possibility of quitting, adding: "I'll have
a look at it.
</P>
<P>
"Let me put it this way - I really want to stay at this
football club," he said.
</P>
<P>
O'Neill has become increasingly disillusioned with boardroom
rows deflecting from on-field matters.
</P>
<P>
Things came to a head once again this week when chief executive
Barry Pierpoint issued a statement on the Stock Exchange claiming
that chairman John Elsom and plc boss Sir Rodney Walker had
resigned.
</P>
<P>
Elsom and Walker have since denied that they have quit.
</P>
<P>
The timing of the latest row clearly angered O'Neill, who
agreed to stay at Filbert Street last year with the warning: "
There must be no more interference in football matters."
</P>
<P>
But O'Neill felt the latest row hampered the team's
preparations for last night's Worthington Cup match against
Crystal Palace.
</P>
<P>
He added: "Not just for myself, it's unsettling for the players
and it's unsettling for the whole football club as well.
</P>
<P>
"Sir Rodney Walker has made a statement today and I'll be
saying something tomorrow," he told BBC Radio 5 Live. 
</P>
</TEXT>
