<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada Welcomes U.N. Resolution on East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Canada expressed welcome
Wednesday to the unanimous passage of the United Nations Security
Council resolution on East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy said in a statement
released here that the passage of the resolution "demonstrates the
international community's sense of urgency over the situation in
East Timor."
</P>
<P>
The resolution authorized a multi-national force to restore
peace and security in East Timor and, if necessary, to use force
under Chapter VII of the U.N. Charter.
</P>
<P>
The minister urged for a rapid deployment of the peacekeeping
force and the delivery of humanitarian assistance under secure
conditions.
</P>
<P>
Up to now, Canada has pledged to contribute 600 troops to the 7,
000-strong multi-national force led by Australia. U.N. Secretary-
General Kofi Annan said that an advance contingent could be on the
ground in East Timor by this weekend "at the latest".
</P>
<P>
Waves of violence have been reported since September 4, when
the results of an autonomy ballot was announced in the former
Portuguese colony annexed by Indonesia in 1976. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
