<HEADLINE> Mammoth Fossil Discovered in North China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HUHHOT, September 16 (Xinhua) -- The fossil remains of a
mammoth have been discovered in the north China city of Manzhouli
(Manchuria) on the Sino-Russian border.
</P>
<P>
This is yet another major archaeological discovery, which
brings the number of mammoth fossils ever found in China up to
four.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, this fossil is 2.6 meters long and
20 centimeters in diameter at the basis. It was discovered four
meters deep by local residents Wang Xudong and his father as they
were building a vegetable cellar outside their house. The cellar
is now sealed off.
</P>
<P>
Mammoths were a kind of large elephant which lived some 30,000
years ago. In 1980 and 1983, coal miners with the Zhalainuo'er
Mining Administration in north China's Inner Mongolia Autonomous
Region unearthed the fossil remains of three other mammoths 40
meters beneath the ground while digging in eastern Manzhouli.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0337 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drought Reduces Grain Output in North China Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, September 16 (Xinhua)-- North China's Hebei
Province says it is sure to have a decline in grain output this
year following a heavy drought.
</P>
<P>
The provincial drought-control office said that half of its 3.
04 million hectares of farmland has suffered the drought, which
lasted form November last year to March this year. During this
period, an average of 9.3 millimeters of rainfall was recorded,
less than one-third of the province's normal amount.
</P>
<P>
Over 200 rivers ceased flowing and over 60 percent of the
wells dried up in Hebei. By the end of August, 1.5 million people
and some 400,000 livestock had insufficient drinking water. Among
those hard hit are the traditionally poor areas.
</P>
<P>
The government of this major grain producing province has
mobilized local people and material recourses to fight the drought,
focusing efforts on bringing drinking water and ensuring a best
possible autumn harvest. 
</P>
</TEXT>
