<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former Mexican Prosecutor Suspected Committing Suicide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Mexico's former top drug
prosecutor, Mario Ruiz Massieu, who fled from authorities in his
own country in 1995 and was arrested in the United States, was
found dead on Wednesday in New Jersey, USA.
</P>
<P>
Massieu, whose extradition was refused three times by U.S.
authorities, reportedly died from an overdose of anti-depression
tablets in his apartment, said a spokesman from the Mexican
Justice Department.
</P>
<P>
Massieu, who left Mexico in 1995 after a split with the Mexican
government, was the brother of the assassinated secretary general
of the ruling Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI), Francisco
Ruiz Massieu.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. authorities declined to confirm whether the death was
a suicide. The body was discovered on Wednesday afternoon in his
apartment in Palisades Park, New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
The ex-prosecutor, who was under house arrest in his New Jersey
apartment, was to appear before the Houston court on Friday, where
he was facing charges of laundering money.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. authorities had found bank accounts belonging to
Massieu, containing almost 9 million dollars, which supposedly
came from laundering money and trafficking in drugs.
</P>
<P>
The Mexican authorities were in the process of preparing for
the fourth time an attempt to extradite Massieu, whom they also
accused of money laundering, illegal enrichment, drug trafficking
and obstruction of justice in the death of the former secretary
general of the PRI.
</P>
<P>
Massieu was captured in 1995 in Newark Airport, New Jersey, en
route to Spain, with 50,000 dollars in cash in his possession. He
was arrested for "failing to make a proper declaration". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
