<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chile to Appeal to the Hague on Pinochet Case </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Chilean Foreign Minister
Juan Gabriel Valdes said on Wednesday that Chile has no other
option than to appeal to the International Court of the Hague, as
Spain refused an arbitration to end the case of former Chilean
leader Augusto Pinochet.
</P>
<P>
Valdes said at a press conference that to put the case to the
Hague is not only for the sake of resolving the conflict
immediately, but is indispensable to clear up the issue of
extraterritoriality.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish attitude, in its refusal to allow arbitration or
diplomatic negotiation on the case, makes it impossible "to
resolve the theme between equals".
</P>
<P>
Valdes did not rule out the probability of withdrawing the
Chilean ambassador to Spain in the next few hours, but added that
measures to be taken would be studied by the cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet, 83, has been under arrest in London since last
October 16 on a warrant from Spanish Judge Baltasar Garzon. Spain
wants him extradited to its territory for trial. A hearing on the
request is to begin September 27.
</P>
<P>
Chile has repeatedly demanded that Pinochet be allowed to
return home for trial. It has asked Spain to agree to
international arbitration on who has jurisdiction over the case.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0342 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cuba Urges All Ibero-American Presidents to Attend Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Cuban Foreign
Minister Felipe Perez Roque Wednesday called on all the heads of
state of Ibero-American countries to attend the upcoming summit in
Havana.
</P>
<P>
"Our will and aspiration is that all the heads of state attend
the summit," said Roque, who arrived in Madrid on Wednesday for a
two-day visit.
</P>
<P>
He added that the participation by all the governments of the
Ibero-American region was necessary, due to the themes to be
debated at the summit, which is to be held in mid-November in
Havana
</P>
<P>
"We have not yet received official confirmation that any
specific country will not attend, although we have seen
declarations in the press to this effect by certain heads of state,
" said Roque.
</P>
<P>
Chilean President Eduardo Frei had announced he would not be
attending the ninth Ibero-American Summit in Havana, in protest
against the detention of ex-president Augusto Pinochet in London
at the request of a Spanish judge.
</P>
<P>
Argentine President Carlos Menem also said he would not attend,
in support of Frei. 
</P>
</TEXT>
