<HEADLINE> Australian PM Sees Possible Casualties in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, September 16 (Xinhua) -- Australian troops going into
East Timor are facing a high degree of risk and the public should
prepare itself for the possibility of casualties, Prime Minister
John Howard said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Howard's comments came amid warnings that militias in East
Timor could target Australians.
</P>
<P>
Howard said there was no doubt Australian troops face risks in
East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"It will be a dangerous operation and I've never pretended
otherwise," Howard told ABC radio.
</P>
<P>
"And I think the Australian public must prepare itself for all
of the consequences that could be involved in an operation like
this," he added.
</P>
<P>
Howard said the government had made sure the element of risk
to Australian soldiers is as low as possible.
</P>
<P>
"We believe we have achieved that. But there comes a point at
which you can't deploy a peacekeeping force without accepting a
degree of risk," he said.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council Wednesday authorized a multinational
force to move into East Timor to restore peace and security there.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
