<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Heyns Wins 100M Breaststroke at All Africa Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 15 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's double
Olympic champion Penny Heyns blitzed her second-fastest time on
home soil as she won All Africa Games gold in the women's 100
meters breaststroke at a packed Ellis Park here Wednesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The triple world record holder clocked a Games record in one
minute 7.58 seconds -- more than a second slower than the 1:06,52
world mark she set at the Pan Pacific Championships in Sydney last
month.
</P>
<P>
Heyns, who has successfully defended the 100m and 200m titles
she won at the previous Games in Harare in 1995, was followed home
by compatriot Ziada Jardine in a personal best of 1:15.31 and
Lauren Harvey of Zimbabwe in 1:18.05.
</P>
<P>
"I wonder if it was perfect conditions, sea level and all that..
. I don't say I would have beaten the world record, but I would
have come close," said Heyns, also owner of the 50m and 200m world
marks.
</P>
<P>
"It's nice to know I can hold my condition on a long taper,"
added the crowd favorite, who rested properly after setting four
world records at the Pan Pacs.
</P>
<P>
"Part of me wanted to swim only to win tonight, but that would
have been unfair on the crowd. Given the altitude, I swam it the
best I could. I went out slow to bring it in fast," she added.
</P>
<P>
For 14-year-old Jardine, the silver medal marks her first
international show since being included in the South African team
as a development swimmer a year ago.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, South Africa also claimed gold-silver finishes in the
earlier individual races.
</P>
<P>
Deaf swimmer from Durban Terence Parkin and Johannesburg blonde
Mandy Loots, already the men's and women's 400m individual medley
title holders, set Games records as they claimed their second gold
medals of the competition.
</P>
<P>
Pan Pacs bronze medalist Parkin easily took the 200m
breaststroke, racing the four laps in a speedy 2:16.29.
</P>
<P>
Greg Owen was second in 2:21.14 and Ayman Khattab of Egypt
finished third in 2:26.98.
</P>
<P>
Loots had no difficulty winning the women's 100m butterfly,
touching in 1:01,32. Candice Crafford won the silver in 1:03.64
and Zimbabwean Teresa Moodie finished third in 1:05.18.
</P>
<P>
And Free Stater Ryno Markgraaff, who trains with triple Pan
Pacs medalist Ryk Neethling at the University of Arizone in Tuscon,
won the men's 400m freestyle in 4:06.93.
</P>
<P>
James Willcox took the silver in 4:08.00 and Glen Walshaw of
Zimbabwe was third in 4:09.65. 
</P>
</TEXT>
