<BODY>
<HEADLINE> General Committee Decides Not to Consider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
General Committee on Wednesday decided not to consider the issue
of the so-called "Taiwan's participation at the United Nations" in
the 54th session of the Genera Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The move came after the General Committee held hours of debate
on the issue. It has been the seventh year that the General Committee
made such a decision, which foiled Taiwan's plots aiming at
splitting a sovereign country and creating"two Chinas", "one
China, one Taiwan" or "one country, two governments."
</P>
<P>
Representatives from sixty-eight countries made statements
during the debate. Most of the countries, including the United
States, Britain, France and Spain, firmly opposed the proposal and
reiterated their countries' position of "one China" policy.
</P>
<P>
Representatives from Tanzania and Pakistan stressed that the
issue of so-called "Taiwan's participation at the United
Nations has already been solved by Resolution 2758 adopted at
the 26th session of the United Nations General Assembly, and
that the proposal had been repeatedly rejected by the
General Committee.
</P>
<P>
They said this should be the last time to debate on this issue
and the United Nations should concentrate its sources on matters
which need urgent attention.
</P>
<P>
On August 11, 1999, Nicaragua and a very small number of other
countries addressed a letter to the U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan in which they requested to inscribe in the agenda of the
54th session of the General Assembly an item of the so-called
"Taiwan's participation at the United Nations."
</P>
<P>
The General Committee comprises the President of the General
Assembly and the Vice-Presidents of the Assembly, and the chairs
of the six Main Committees.  
</P>
</TEXT>
