<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy to Send 600 Troops to East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Italy will send 600 soldiers to
participate in the UN peacekeeping mission in East Timor, with a
company of 200 parachute troops expected to arrive in the island
within five to seven days, the Italian Defense Ministry said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Following the United Nations Security Council's approval of a
peacekeeping force early Wednesday morning, the ministry said 600
Italian troops would be sent to the island, including two hundred
from the Folgore regiment, who have been standing by since moves
to create an international peace force began.
</P>
<P>
The troops will be joining an 8,000-strong force in which there
will be 4,500 Australians. About 2,000 Australians with British
Gurkhas and troops from New Zealand are expected to disembark
within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
The first task will be to take control of the airport at Dili,
the East Timorese capital, and the port. Italy's parachute troops,
for example, will be flown to Dili, and Italy will also deploy a
G-222 plane for tactical air support.
</P>
<P>
Most Italian troops and supplies will be transported by sea on
board the San Giusto, which recently took part in humanitarian
operations for earthquake-stricken Turkey, the ministry said.
</P>
<P>
The San Giusto left the port of Brindisi Wednesday afternoon
for La Spezia, where it will load soldiers and supplies. It is
expected to arrive in East Timor within four weeks.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, the United Nations revealed that Indonesian
paramilitary troops had already started leaving East Timor ahead
of the arrival of peacekeeping forces. 
</P>
</TEXT>
