<HEADLINE> Clinton Expected to Ease Sanctions on DPRK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill
Clinton is expected to ease sanctions as early as this week on the
Democratic People's Republic of Korea (DPRK), an administration
official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The president may well announce something this week," the
official said.
</P>
<P>
He said the action would allow bank transfers between the
two countries, open up commerce and allow port calls by ships.
</P>
<P>
But the United States would not support international loans
to the DPRK, or permit technology transfers or foreign
assistance, he added.
</P>
<P>
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and National Security
Adviser Sandy Berger recommended the sanction easing this week
after the two countries made some progress on the missile test in
their talks in Berlin last week. 
</P>
