<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Benefits of Caffeine on Alertness May Be Less Than Thought </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Caffeine-filled cups of tea
and coffee may not really provide the boost to alertness that
people think, British researchers said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
New study by Dr Peter Rogers, a psychologist from Britian's
University of Bristol, showed regular caffeine consumers
experience significant negative effects following overnight
abstinence from caffeine.
</P>
<P>
Dr Rogers and his colleagues found that caffeine consumption
after overnight caffeine abstinence appears to merely restore mood
and performance to "normal" levels.
</P>
<P>
"In other words, caffeine influenced the participant's liking
for the drink mainly because it relieved the negative effects
arising from withdrawal from the caffeine they had consumed the
previous day," Rogers told the British Association's Festival of
Science in Sheffield, England.
</P>
<P>
The researchers tested their idea in studies in which caffeine
ingestion was paired with the consumption of novel-flavored fruit
juices.
</P>
<P>
The results, as expected, showed that caffeine acts most
reliably as a reinforcer of overnight caffeine withdrwal,
relieving negative states such as feelings of fatigue and
tiredness.
</P>
<P>
The new study may help explain the popularity of caffeine
containing drinks, while at the same time suggesting that regular
caffeine consumption benefits mental alertness much less than is
generally supposed, the researchers said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990916.0353 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hurricane Forces Millions to Evacuate in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- More than three million
Americans fled inland Wednesday as Hurricane Floyd thrashed along
the U.S. southeast coast, pounding beaches with heavy surf and
ripping down tree limbs and power lines.
</P>
<P>
About 3.2 million people had been urged to evacuate, said
officials in Florida, Georgia and South Carolina, and more people
joined the exodus Wednesday in North Carolina.
</P>
<P>
Federal emergency officials said it was the biggest evacuation
in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
Thousands of Florida residents were without power, but that
state escaped the worst as Floyd swung northward.
</P>
<P>
Virginia and Maryland have declared states of emergency and
asked residents of waterfront and low-lying areas to make
preliminary evacuation plans.
</P>
<P>
The storm weakened slightly Wednesday to a Category 3
hurricane, with sustained wind blowing at 200 kph instead of the
peak of nearly 250 kph when it battered the Bahamas. The enormous
storm spread rain along the coast from Florida to Connecticut, and
heavy surf advisories were posted as far north as Massachusetts'
Cape Cod.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday afternoon, the storm's center was about 345
kilometers south of Myrtle Beach, South Carolina. Floyd was moving
north-northwest near 22 kph, and a turn to the north and increase
in forward speed was expected later Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vice President Al Gore said Wednesday that President Bill
Clinton had declared states of emergency in South Carolina and
North Carolina, making them eligible for federal disaster relief.
</P>
<P>
Floyd's expected track would take its wind and rain across
Virginia, the District of Columbia, Maryland and Delaware, eastern
Pennsylvania, New Jersey, the New York City area, and into
Connecticut, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, Vermont, Maine and
Canada's Maritime Provinces by Saturday night. 
</P>
</TEXT>
