<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Congress Leader Calls for Team to Bosnia on Corruption </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- A leading U.S. House
leader called for a special international team to be sent to
Bosnia to fight against corruption in the country.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the hearing of the House International Relations
Committee on corruption in Bosnia, Benjamin Gilman, chairman of
the House International Relations Committee, said the team should
be composed of special judicial officials and investigators.
</P>
<P>
The hearing is the first of a series on the corruption in
Bosnia that may have led to the diversion of up to one billion
U.S. dollars of assistance to the country.
</P>
<P>
The New York Times reported on August 17 that international
donors to Bosnia may have lost one billion U.S. dollars since the
signing of the Dayton peace plan in late 1995. Of the lost money,
the U.S. share was at least 20 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Bosnia is one of the largest recipients of foreign aid in the
world on a per capita basis.
</P>
<P>
"While the U.S. and other European donors have not suffered
losses so great as alleged, corruption does impede progress
towards our major goals in Bosnia," Gilman told the hearing.
</P>
<P>
A Congressional staff team sent by Gilman to Bosnia after the
New York Times report came back and found that corruption does
exist in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
"In the most shocking revelation, we found that funds to
provide gravestones for the victims of the Srebrenica massacre
were stolen by the canton's prime minister. Hundreds of millions
of dollars were stolen in various scams," Gilman said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the team also found that local Bosnian officials
refused to cooperate with the international community to fight
corruption.
</P>
<P>
Gilman suggests a team of "untouchable investigators and judges
to clean up Bosnia." "It should be highly trained to try to
remediate this mess," he said.
</P>
<P>
Also speaking at the hearing, Ambassador Larry C. Napper, the
State Department's coordinator on assistance in Eastern Europe,
said the administration already was planning to intensify its
2-year-old fight against Bosnian crime and corruption.  
</P>
</TEXT>
