<HEADLINE> U.S. Consumer Prices and Business Inventories Rise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- U.S. consumer prices rose
0.3 percent in August as energy costs surged for a second
consecutive month, the Labor Department reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In both August and July, energy was the big force pushing
prices upward. For August, two-thirds of the total price increase
was attributed to a 2.7 percent jump in energy costs. Food costs
edged up a small 0.2 percent, the report said.
</P>
<P>
If excluding the volatile energy and food categories, prices
were up just 0.1 percent in August.
</P>
<P>
This performance of the "core" rate of inflation was even
better than economists' expectations and will provide ammunition
for those arguing there is no need for the Federal Reserve to
boost interest rates for a third time.
</P>
<P>
So far this year, consumer prices have been rising at an annual
rate of 2.6 percent, compared with a gain of just 1.6 percent for
all of 1998. However, all of the increase reflects higher energy
costs, which have rebounded this year after a steep plunge in 1998
that reflected slumping global demand in the wake of steep
recessions in many nations hit by a global currency crisis.
</P>
<P>
The August's 2.7 percent jump in energy costs was even bigger
than July's 2.1 percent increase. Gasoline prices advanced 5.6
percent last month and are up 25.1 percent at an annual rate so
far this year.
</P>
<P>
The 0.2 percent rise in food prices in August matched the
modest July increase. Clothing prices fell by 0.3 percent, the
fourth consecutive drop.
</P>
<P>
Airline fares fell by 2.7 percent in August after having posted
a sharp 6.5 percent increase in July.
</P>
<P>
In a separate report today, the Commerce Department said that
inventories held by businesses on shelves and backlots increased
by 0.3 percent in July while business sales jumpedat an even
faster 0.4 percent clip.
</P>
<P>
So that made the ratio of inventories to sales at a record
low of 1.34 months, meaning it would take this length of time to
exhaust supplies at the current sales pace. 
</P>
</TEXT>
