<HEADLINE> U.S. House Approves Defense Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- The U.S. House Wednesday
passed a defense bill including military pay raise.
</P>
<P>
The 289-billion-U.S.-dollar bill, 8.3 billion U.S. dollars more
than sought by President Bill Clinton, cleared 375-45, despite
concerns raised by a number of Democrats about the degree of
autonomy given the new, largely independent nuclear weapons agency
within the Energy Department.
</P>
<P>
The compromise bill, which was already approved by a House and
Senate conference, must still be given final approval by the
Senate before it is sent to the White House.
</P>
<P>
U.S. Administration officials indicated a possible veto over
the nuclear weapons agency, but congressional Republicans and
Democrats said a veto would be politically difficult given the
widespread support for the defense package.
</P>
<P>
The bill includes a widely popular 4.8 percent military pay
raise, more money for military barracks and family housing and
increase spending for military hardware -- everything from 176
million U.S. dollars for 17 new Black Hawk helicopters to 3.7
billion U.S. dollars for a ballistic missile defense system.
</P>
</TEXT>
