<HEADLINE> Protein Finding Raises New Hope for TB Treatment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Proteins found in tuberculosis
(TB) bacterium acting as wake-up call for dormant bacteria and as
growth factors may help create future TB drugs and vaccines,
British scientists said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Professor Mike Young, of the University of Wales at
Aberystwyth, was studying bacteria related to TB when he
discovered that they produce a chemical "alarm call" that rouses
other bacteria of that species from dormancy.
</P>
<P>
"The protein is not just a wake-up call but also a growth
factor for the bacteria," Professor Young told the British
Association's Festival of Science held in Sheffield, England.
</P>
<P>
After studying genetic blueprint of TB bacterium, which has
4,000 sequenced genes, the researchers found that the TB bug
produces five growth factor proteins with similar properties.
</P>
<P>
Professor Young said that if the human immune system can be
persuaded to recognize those proteins, it could lead to TB
vaccines.
</P>
<P>
Understanding how the proteins control growth and finding ways
to block them could also make it possible to prevent an infection
developing into the disease.
</P>
<P>
A third of world's population may carry the TB bacterium in its
dormant form, but they cannot be treated because anti-TB drugs
only work if the bacteria are active.
</P>
<P>
The newly-discovered proteins could be used to wake up a
dormant infection and force the bacteria into an active state,
which the researchers believed would allow the bugs to be attacked
by drugs and cleared. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
