<HEADLINE> Wall Street Stocks Fall Sharply </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>

<P>
NEW YORK, September 15 (Xinhua) -- Wall Street stocks fell
sharply Wednesday as investors feared higher interest rates
despite little evidence of rising inflation in a government
report.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average closed down 108.91 at
10,801.42, adding to a loss of 120.00 Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500 index fell 18.32 at 1,317.97 and the technology heavy
Nasdaq composite index fell 54.12 at 2,814.17.
</P>
<P>
The Labor Department reported that the Consumer Price Index
rose 0.3 percent in August, matching the July advance. But the
modest increase did not convince investors that the Federal
Reserve will not raise interest rates for a third time this year
in its effort to fight inflation.
</P>
<P>
The continued weakness in the U.S. dollar also drove stocks
lower. The dollar slid to 104.29 against Japanese yen from
105.79 Tuesday in New York, putting more pressures on stocks.
</P>
<P>
The NYSE index fell 6.64 at 608.47 and the American Stock
Exchange index fell 4.00 at 797.48. The Russell 2000 index of
smaller companies fell 1.91 at 436.33.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 3-to-2 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, with 1,774 down, 1,195 up and 542
unchanged.
</P>
<P>
NYSE volume increased to 779.58 million shares from 719.94
million in the previous session.  
</P>
</TEXT>
